<FIRST>r a AM-D'Amato-Audit     06-08 0381</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-D'Amato-Audit,0395</SECOND>
<HEAD>HUD Audit: Island Park Officials Excluded Blacks</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Officials of Island Park, home village of U.S.
Sen. Alfonse M. D'Amato, rigged the distribution of federally
subsidized homes in the early 1980s to keep out blacks, according to
a published report.
   The New York Times in its Thursday editions reported that an
audit by the Department of Housing and Urban Development indicates
that one person who received preferential treatment was D'Amato's
cousin, Anthony Ciccimarro.
   At the time, D'Amato was supervisor of the Town of Hempstead, of
which Island Park is an incorporated subdivision. He was elected to
the U.S. Senate shortly after that, the newspaper said.
   Ciccimarro was selected to buy a $40,000 HUD house, the Times
said.
   Also receiving preferential treatment was Geraldine McGann, a
village board member and a high-ranking HUD administrator whose son
received a $44,500 house, it said.
   In the 1980s, Nassau County got enough money to build 285 houses
for lower-income families. Island Park, which is 97 percent white,
got enough money to build 44 homes ranging from $40,000 to $64,000.
   The audit does not say if the people selected for the HUD houses
actually were eligible to buy them. Buyers included the niece of the
village clerk, the niece of a village trustee, two village
supervisors, a lawyer who soon will become a village justice and the
daughter of a village employee, the newspaper said. None of them are
black.
   The HUD houses were supposed to be advertised in local newspapers
so lower-income residents, especially minorities, would have a
chance to buy a home.
   Instead, some selected residents were told in advance when the
ads would appear and they slipped their applications under the
Village Hall door before dawn, the Times reported.
   The 1984 audit recommended disciplinary action against Mrs.
McGann and the village but no penalties.
   Mrs. McGann last year was promoted to regional HUD administrator
after her friend, D'Amato, lobbied Congress and the White House on
her behalf, the newspaper said.
   When the Times requested a copy of the audit, Mrs. McGann deleted
the names of eight villagers, including her son.
   ``This program was a mockery,'' said Jeff Pless, who did the
audit. ``It took everyone's tax money and gave it to the people who
didn't need it.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
