<FIRST>r a AM-SpottedOwl-BLM     06-08 0257</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Spotted Owl-BLM,0263</SECOND>
<HEAD>Appeals Court Restores Timber Injunction</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal appeals court Wednesday restored
the injunction prohibiting the U.S. Bureau of Land Management from
selling old-growth timber around northern spotted owl nests in
Western Oregon.
   Acting on an appeal brought by the Portland Audubon Society and
other environmental groups, the 9th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals
without comment restored the year-old injunction lifted last month
by a federal judge.
   The action was praised by environmentalists, who contend the
spotted owl will become extinct unless the ancient forests where it
lives and hunts are preserved.
   The timber industry contends that thousands of jobs will be lost
unless logging of old growth timber on federal lands is allowed to
continue.
   The action means as much as 400 million board feet of timber, a
third of the agency's annual harvest in Oregon, won't be offered for
sale, said BLM spokesman Don Smurthwaite.
   Five timber sales on the Medford and Coos Bay BLM districts which
were sold during the course of the legal wrangling weren't included
in the injunction.
   The action was separate from a lawsuit filed by environmentalists
against the U.S. Forest Service pending in U.S. District Court in
Seattle that stopped harvest of 1 billion board feet of timber on
national forests in Oregon and Washington.
   In lifting the injunction, Judge Helen Frye said the BLM failed
to consider new information in preparing its managment plans for
spotted owls, which the U.S. Fish &amp; Wildlife Service has proposed
for listing as a threatened species.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
