<FILEID>AP-NR-06-08-89 0117EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-APAppointment     06-08 0179</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-AP Appointment,0182</SECOND>
<HEAD>New Seattle Bureau Chief Named</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Dan Day, director of Associated Press operations
in Nebraska since 1985, has been appointed bureau chief in Seattle.
   Louis D. Boccardi, president and general manager of The
Associated Press, announced the appointment Wednesday.
   Day, 32, will take over the news cooperative's operations in four
Washington offices _ Olympia, Spokane, Yakima and the control bureau
in Seattle. He succeeds Thomas Slaughter, who has been promoted to
general executive at AP's New York headquarters.
   A Cleveland native, Day graduated from Holy Cross College in
Worcester, Mass., and received a master's degree in journalism from
Marquette University in Milwaukee. He worked for the Daily Times in
Ottawa, Ill., before joining the AP in Milwaukee in 1981.
   In 1982, Day was appointed Wisconsin broadcast editor and in 1983
was promoted to news editor in Omaha, Neb. Two years later, he was
elevated to correspondent in charge of Omaha. In 1988, Omaha was
upgraded from an office reporting to Des Moines, Iowa, to an
independent bureau and Day became bureau chief.
</TEXT>
