<FIRST>r a AM-TielessTeacher     06-08 0470</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Tieless Teacher,0488</SECOND>
<HEAD>Tieless Teacher Wins Court Victory</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KELLY P. KISSEL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHARLESTON, W.Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A teacher was illegally suspended by a
school board for refusing to wear a tie in his classroom, a circuit
judge ruled Wednesday.
   The ruling doesn't ensure that Bill Webb, 46, will return to his
Point Pleasant High School classroom, but it undermines the Mason
County Board of Education's main charges in the math teacher's
firing.
   ``If they couldn't suspend him, they sure as hell couldn't fire
him,'' the teacher's wife, Julie, said in a telephone from the
couple's Gallipolis, Ohio, home.
   Her husband was en route to Chicago to appear on ``The Oprah
Winfrey Show,'' which planned a program Thursday on people fired
because of the way they dress.
   The Mason County board suspended Webb three times last fall,
accusing him of insubordination for violating a dress code requiring
male teachers to wear dress pants and ties.
   Webb, whose standard classroom wardrobe consisted of blue jeans
and cotton shirts, openly challenged Superintendent Charles
Chambers' order, drawing suspensions lasting 4, 11 and 30 days
before being fired Dec. 19.
   Kanawha Circuit Judge Charlie King's ruling set aside the 11-day
suspension, meaning Webb will be paid for that time, said the
teacher's attorney, Larry Kopleman.
   A hearing on the firing and the 30-day suspension is pending,
Kopleman said. Webb didn't challenge the four-day suspension because
he was paid.
   King said the dress code was improperly established and that Webb
had the right to disobey rules he believed were illegal.
   ``If you challenge a rule that is in effect unlawful, it's not
insubordination,'' said Kopleman. The board claimed Webb should have
worn a tie while challenging Chambers' order.
   ``The superintendent didn't have the authority to unilaterally
issue a dress code,'' said Kopleman. ``Only the board has the
authority. That was one of our premier arguments.''
   Board member Harry Siders, who introduced a proposal to fine
Webb, said Wednesday night he wasn't aware of King's decision and
that the board had not talked about what to do if Webb's appeals
were successful.
   Board president Emma Kearns could not be reached. Chambers and
board attorney Diane Johnson have unlisted numbers.
   The next board meeting is scheduled for June 19.
   The controversy began in August 1988, when the board said male
instructors would have to wear ties, a change from contracts
teachers signed last spring. Webb, who has worked for the Mason
County school system for 19 years and is also a farmer, has spent
his spare time working around the house and at a body shop he runs.
   Mrs. Webb said her husband will be wearing denim from top to
bottom on the Oprah Winfrey program Thursday.
   ``I pressed them before he left,'' she said. ``I seldom press
them, but this is big time.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
