<FILEID>AP-NR-06-08-89 0002EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u w AM-Foley-GOP 3rdLd-Writethru a0741 06-08 0757</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Foley-GOP, 3rd Ld-Writethru, a0741,710</SECOND>
<HEAD>GOP Official Resigns in Uproar Over Foley Memo</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: INSERTS grafs 6-7: ``The president,'' with Sununu interview</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STEVEN KOMAROW</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A national Republican Party official resigned
Wednesday in the uproar over a memo he wrote comparing House Speaker
Thomas S. Foley's voting record with that of a homosexual
congressman.
   President Bush as described as ``disgusted by this entire
incident'' and as considering it closed.
   However, Democratic Party chief Ronald Brown said the resignation
of ``one staffer'' wasn't good enough and suggested his Republican
counterpart, Bush's former campaign manager Lee Atwater, should be
fired by the president.
   Mark Goodin, a press assistant in Bush's 1988 presidential
campaign, wrote the memo and had it distributed as communications
director of the Republican National Committee.
   The memo, which Goodin said was sent out without his boss
Atwater's knowledge, compared Foley's voting record to that of
liberal Rep. Barney Frank, D-Mass. The memo was titled: ``Tom Foley:
Out of the Liberal Closet.''
   ``The president was very upset,'' said White House chief of staff
John Sununu in an interview reported in Thursday editions of The New
York Times. ``I was upset. It went too far. It was wrong. The
innuendo was wrong. It's wrong not because it damages our
relationship with the Democrats. It's wrong because it's wrong.
   ``It's a terrible thing to happen at this time. It was not
appropriate or fair,'' said Sununu, who said both he and Bush had
rebuked Atwater.
   White House spokesman Marlin Fitzwater said Bush called Atwater,
his 1988 campaign manager, Wednesday morning, shortly before the
resignation was announced. Atwater had telephoned Foley to apologize
Tuesday night.
   Bush's spokesman said, ``He was disgusted by this entire
incident.''
   ``We consider the matter closed,'' he added.
   Foley, likewise, commenting after a previously scheduled meeting
with Bush at the White House, said, ``The issue is closed.'' He said
there was no mention of it during the meeting.
   Earlier at the Capitol, Foley said that on the telephone Atwater
had been ``deeply apologetic for any inferences of personal
character.''
   ``He repudiated the statement and apologized ... I accepted
that,'' said Foley, adding that Atwater promised there would be no
more such attacks.
   Foley, in his first full day as House speaker, said any
suggestion that he is homosexual is ``entirely untrue of course.''
   Brown, the chairman of the Democratic National Commitee, said of
Goodin's resignation, ``One staffer can't take the fall for an
entire Republican political operation that's up to its knees in
sewer-style politics. I think it's fair to ask President Bush if
he'll also have his hand-picked party chairman, Lee Atwater, to
resign.
   ``The president himself has to be accountable for the activities
of his henchman,'' Brown said in a statement.
   Congressional Republican leaders also decried the memo and the
strategy it seemed to represent.
   Senate Minority Leader Bob Dole said on the Senate floor, ``I
would guess this is a rather deliberate effort on the part of some
to smear Tom Foley ... on his first day as speaker. ... I would say
this is not politics. This is garbage. We're disgusted by it.''
   Dole declared, ``To those who have now departed the Republican
National Committee, I say, `Good riddance!'''
   House Minority Leader Robert Michel, R-Ill., expressed dismay
over the memo Tuesday and called both Bush and Atwater, aides said.
   Michel, at the White House for the meeting with Bush and Foley,
told reporters, ``It was a mistake obviously from the national
committee's point of view.''
   He said he did not know if Goodin had been asked to resign but
said he had told Atwater, ``There's got to be some remedy for what
took place, and Lee, it's your shot. Do whatever you think is
appropriate.''
   Goodin said in his resignation letter to Atwater, ``At no time
did I ever intend to damage anyone's reputation. Nonetheless, the
purpose of the memorandum has been misconstrued. And in that regard,
I have no one to blame but myself.''
   Rep. Tony Coelho of California, the second-ranking House
Democrat, said Bush needed to take more responsibility.
   ``They're playing good cop, bad cop,'' Coelho said before the
resignation was announced. ``Here's a guy sent in by Bush to do the
dirty deeds, and he calls and apologizes after the fact. If they're
really upset about these tactics, all they have to do is fire
somebody.''
   Rep. Mickey Edwards, R-Okla., chairman of the House Republican
Policy Committee, said, ``I think we're going to be moving rather
strongly to make sure it stops.''
</TEXT>
