<DOCNO> AP890608-0021 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-08-89 0543EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-DroughtRelief     06-08 0421</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Drought Relief,420</SECOND>
<HEAD>Drought Relief Decision May Not Come Til Fall</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DIANE DUSTON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   If winter wheat farmers are to get any drought
relief aid, it may not be decided until the end of the fiscal year,
Sept. 30.
   During an informal meeting Wednesday with Agriculture Secretary
Clayton Yeutter, Senate Agriculture Committee Chairman Patrick
Leahy, D-Vt., said he didn't want to pass legislation that would
have to be revised later.
   ``It seems too early to cover spring planted crops,'' said Leahy
during the meeting which attracted 20 other senators.
   ``We don't known whether such crops are going to be weather
damaged. To act now on spring-planted crops shifts the risk of
production almost totally to the federal government _ I don't think
that is a good idea.''
   Yeutter was critical of a bill passed last month by the House
Agriculture Committee, calling it a ``Christmas tree'' because it
promises relief to many crops other than winter wheat, just in case
weather later in the year damages them.
   ``If we do develop legislative response, it ought to be very
narrowly defined and circumscribed to the people who have been
hurt,'' Yeutter said.
   Yeutter pointed out that rain has been falling steadily in the
past few weeks, even to the point of causing planting delays in some
parts of the country.
   Leahy's committee has not yet acted on any legislation, though a
bill authored by Sen. Bob Dole, R-Kan. and one sponsored by Sens.
David Boren, D-Okla., and Robert Kerrey, D-Neb. have been introduced.
   Those measures would extend assistance provided under the 1988
drought relief act to crops planted in 1988 for harvest in 1989 _
mostly winter wheat.
   But Leahy said, ``If you have a winter wheat bill, it becomes the
vehicle for the year,'' and he doesn't want a measure the country
can't afford.
   He said cost estimates for any bill are suspect at this early
date, though damage to winter wheat has been estimated to be about
$1 billion.
   He said he didn't want to give farmers assistance in a bill that
would have to be taken away because of budget restraints.
   But Dole said he didn't see any reason to wait.
   ``I hope we don't have to hold the Midwest hostage until we see
if there are problems in other states,'' he said. He said his bill
is budget neutral, in that it would use deficiency payments being
saved because of higher wheat prices to pay the farmers who are
facing losses.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
