<DOCNO> AP890608-0022 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-08-89 0543EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-Deland-Environment     06-08 0574</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Deland-Environment,560</SECOND>
<HEAD>Environmentals Hope Deland Can Boost Role of Presidential Council</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By H. JOSEF HEBERT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Environmentalists say they hope the selection
of Michael Deland to the president's Council on Environmental
Quality will signal a revival for the advisory panel, which was
largely ignored in the Reagan administration.
   President Bush announced Wednesday he plans to nominate Deland,
regional administrator in New England for the Environmental
Protection Agency, to the three-member council and then make him its
chairman.
   The selection of Deland brought praise from several environmental
groups. He has gained a reputation as a strong enforcer of
environmental laws as the EPA's chief in Boston.
   The council advises the president on environmental matters, but
the panel languished with little money, staff or power during the
eight years of the Reagan administration. President Reagan largely
ignored its members.
   ``Mike Deland is a first rate environmentalist and I think he's
an outstanding choice,'' said Jay Hair, head of the National
Wildlife Federation. ``The bigger question is whether or not the
president will give him both the resources and the respect in order
to revitalize, rebuild and redirect the CEQ.''
   David Gardiner of the Sierra Club said Deland was ``a very strong
environmentalist'' and called his selection ``very much a positive
step'' and that he assumed that Deland ``would not have taken the
job if he had not had some assurances of what the CEQ's authority
would be'' in the White House.
   The council's influence largely will be ``a question of staffing
and money,'' said Gardiner. In the Carter administration the CEQ was
provided with professional staff that could research issues and
brief council members who, in turn, had strong influence on the
president.
   ``Under the Reagan administration they (the staff) vanished,''
said Gardiner. President Reagan had at one time sought to abolish
the council.
   Deland, who has been mentioned as a possible Republican
gubernatorial candidate in Massachusetts, has been director of the
EPA's regional office in Boston since 1983 where he gained a
reputation for aggressively pursuing polluters. He sometimes was at
odds with the agency's Washington headquarters.
   Earlier this year he was mentioned widely as a top prospect to
become head of the EPA in the Bush administration. William K. Reilly
was selected instead.
   During last year's presidential race, Deland added fuel to the
Bush campaign's attack on Democratic opponent Michael Dukakis for
failing as Massachusetts governor to clean up Boston Harbor. But
while Deland criticized Dukakis for delaying the cleanup, he
acknowleged that the federal EPA under the Republican administration
also shared blame. When Bush took reporters on a boatride through
the polluted harbor, Deland refused to go along.
   Deland 47, whose back problems force him usually to rely on a
wheelchair, had occasional clashes with his superiors in Washington
during the Reagan years as well as with then-New Hampshire Gov. John
Sununu, now White House chief of staff.
   He stood his ground against opposition from EPA headquarters and
blocked the development of a shopping mall in Attleboro, Mass.,
arguing the complex would destroy environmentally important
wetlands. He clashed with Sununu over a proposed development in New
Hampshire's Loon Mountain and endorsed a moratorium on development
on Cape Cod.
   Deland is a graduate of Harvard College and Boston College Law
School. He worked for the president of the University of
Massachusetts, on the EPA's legal staff and as a private consultant
before taking the EPA job in Boston.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
