<DOCNO> AP890608-0023 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-08-89 0213EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-Gingrich-Lukens     06-08 0533</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Gingrich-Lukens,580</SECOND>
<HEAD>Gingrich Won't Challenge Convicted Republican's Right To Vote In
House</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID PACE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Rep. Newt Gingrich of Georgia, who rose to
prominence in the House with his ethics crusades against Democrats,
says he won't challenge a fellow Republican's right to vote in the
House while appealing his conviction for having sex with a teen-age
girl.
   Gingrich, the House Republican whip, said in an interview
Wednesday that Rep. Donald ``Buz'' Lukens, R-Ohio, should not have
to give up his right to vote because his conviction involved a
misdemeanor, not a felony.
   He said the conviction for contributing to the delinquency and
unruliness of a minor is ``a serious offense, but it's a serious
misdemeanor'' which will not cause Lukens to lose any citizenship
rights.
   Lukens faces up to six months in prison and a $1,000 fine for his
conviction.
   ``I think the Lukens case will go to the ethics committee and I
think the Republican Conference will insist on it,'' Gingrich said.
``But I think it is inappropriate for us to impose our judgment on
the courts of Ohio'' and bar Lukens from voting while his conviction
is on appeal.
   Lukens' chief of staff, Bill Jarrell, said the congressman would
have no response to Gingrich's comments.
   ``Congressman Lukens is not going to take out time and react to
every statement that comes down the pike,'' he said. ``He's taking
care of business here on Capitol Hill.''
   Gingrich has insisted since his freshman term in 1980 that any
congressman convicted of a felony should not be permitted to vote in
the House while appealing his conviction.
   He moved to expel then-Rep. Charles Diggs, D-Mich., in 1980 after
he continued to vote following his fraud conviction, and he
threatened similar action against then-Rep. Mario Biaggi, D-N.Y.,
after his 1987 conviction for accepting illegal gratituties. Biaggi
stopped voting after the threat.
   ``The principle in regard to the felony convictions of Biaggi and
Diggs was that if you're convicted of a felony, you lose certain of
your political rights, including the right to vote,'' Gingrich said.
   Gingrich said his decision not to challenge Lukens' right to vote
was not influenced by his frienship with the Ohio congressman, who
was one of the conservative Republicans who joined with Gingrich to
form the Conservative Opportunity Society in the early 1980s.
   He compared Lukens' case to that of Rep. Gerry Studds, D-Mass.,
who along with then-Rep. Daniel Crane, R-Ill., was censured by the
House in 1983 for sexual misconduct with teen-age pages. Studds has
remained in Congress and is now chairman of a House subcommittee.
   Gingrich predicted that Lukens eventually will be punished by the
House, and he suggested that a resolution of censure, such as that
imposed on Studds and Crane, might be appropriate.
   During the 1983 House debate over punishment for Studds and
Crane, however, Gingrich argued that they should be expelled from
Congress.
   ``There is no high school or college in America where exploiting,
seducing or sleeping with students, boy or girl, would be punished
with a reprimand,'' he said in the 1983 debate. ``The teacher would
be fired. Similarly, the two congressmen, like a teacher, must be
fired.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
