<FILEID>AP-NR-06-08-89 0214EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-MedicareSurcharge     06-08 0682</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Medicare Surcharge,690</SECOND>
<HEAD>Senate Panel to Review Medicare's Catastrophic Health Provisions</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JERRY ESTILL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Senate, after narrowly rejecting an attempt
to postpone major parts of the new catastrophic health provisions of
Medicare, has ordered a committee review of the program.
   The aim of the Finance Committee review is to consider reducing
the income tax surcharge on the elderly that pays for the new
benefits.
   Sen. John McCain, R-Ariz., fell two votes short Wednesday evening
of attaching an amendment to separate legislation that would have
forced a delay of at least one year in the so-called ``supplemental
premium'' imposed this year on Medicare-eligible individuals to pay
for a package of benefits that start taking effect next January.
   However, McCain also would have pushed back those benefits yet
another year, and opponents argued that his proposal effectively
would have killed major parts of the program approved overwhelming
by Congress last summer. It is the first major expansion of Medicare
since its creation two decades ago.
   Senate Majority Leader George Mitchell, seeking to head off the
McCain attempt, introduced a substitute amendment that put the
Senate on record as instructing the Finance Committee to look into
reducing the surtax if it is shown that more money is being
collected than will be needed.
   Finance Committee Chairman Lloyd Bentsen, D-Texas, first raised
that possibility several weeks ago but the administration, as well
as influential House leaders, are on record against any tax rollback.
   In debate on McCain's proposal, Bentsen also pledged to look
closely at ways to exempt from the catastrophic surtax those retired
Americans who have equal coverage under ``Medigap'' policies that
are paid in full or part by their former employers.
   And he said he would renew efforts to attach the catastrophic
coverage to Part B of Medicare, thus making it voluntary. Part B of
Medicare, the section that pays doctor bills, is voluntarily taken
by more than 95 percent of those eligible _ in large part because
the federal government foots the bill for 75 percent of the costs.
   Although members of Congress have been hit by thousands of
letters protesting the new catastrophic program, opponents of the
McCain proposal argued that opponents still represent a tiny
minority of the 32 million people covered by Medicare.
   The idea behind the financing mechanism adopted last year was
that _ with huge budget deficits making it impossible to provide new
government benefits without additional revenue to pay for them _ it
was reasonable to expect that those being offered additional
benefits be required to pay for them.
   Moreover, framers of the program maintained, it was fair for
middle- and upper-income retired Americans to pay a proportionately
larger share of the cost just as the federal tax system in general
is pegged to a percentage of income.
   The catastrophic 15 percent tax surcharge follows that principle,
except the maximum imposed on any individual this year is $800,
regardless of income.
   Opponents of the McCain attempt argued that an estimated 59
percent of the 32 million Medicare beneficaries do not have enough
income to qualify for income tax and would pay only $4 a month for
the additional coverage.
   They cited Congressional Budget Office estimates that 70 percent
of those eligible for Medicare would pay $100 or less a year in
additional surtaxes and that only 5.6 percent in upper income levels
would pay the maximum $800 tax.
   The catastrophic coverage started taking effect Jan. 1 with
unlimited hospitalization coverage after a once-a-year $560
deductible. However, a $1,370 cap on out-of-pocket doctor bills does
not kick in until next year and a new prescription drug benefit
begins a three-year phase-in period in 1991.
   It was those benefits beginning next January that McCain wanted
to delay, along with the surtax imposed to finance them.
   Prior to Jan. 1, Medicare provided full hospital coverage for
only 59 days a year. Medicare pays 80 percent of physician bills
after a $75 annual deductible, but until the new catastrophic
provisions on doctor fees take effect there is no cap on the
patient's share.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890608-0025 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-08-89 0214EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-SpendingBill     06-08 0586</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Spending Bill,580</SECOND>
<HEAD>House, Senate Face Deep Differences Over Domestic Spending Bill</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALAN FRAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The House and Senate face pressure to resolve
their differences speedily over a long-delayed spending bill, but
the widest gulf is over one of the hottest political issues: illegal
drugs.
   A bipartisan Senate voiced approval Wednesday for legislation
pouring an extra $3.3 billion this year into veterans, student loan
and other programs. The vote capping lawmakers' fourth day of debate
came more than two months after President Bush asked Congress for a
$2.2 billion version of the bill.
   The House passed its own $3.7 billion measure on May 24 on a
contentious party-line vote. As is usual with spending legislation,
each chamber sprinkled its own bill with provisions boosting
individual lawmakers' favorite projects.
   The biggest difference between the two bills is $822 million the
House included for a host of anti-drug programs. Majority Democrats
there inserted the money into the bill, over veto threats from Bush
administration officials arguing that the spending would further
inflate the deficit.
   The Senate version contains no drug monies. Despite public
opinion polls indicating that illegal drugs is the pre-eminent
domestic problem, Senate Democrats heeded Bush's warnings and joined
Republicans in preventing some legislators from putting drug
spending into the bill.
   Massachusetts Rep. Silvio Conte, ranking Republican on the
Appropriations Committee, said he did not believe it would be
difficult for the two houses to work out their differences over
financing new anti-drug efforts.
   ``I think I can get the White House to compromise on something,''
he told a reporter.
   But one administration official, speaking on condition of
anonymity, insisted Wednesday there was still ``no way'' Bush would
sign the final bill if any drug spending was included. That was also
the conventional wisdom among lawmakers and congressional aides.
   Legislators will be pressed to bargain quickly by many groups
hoping to garner money from the bill, but foremost among them will
be the nation's veterans. In each house's measure, there is $1.2
billion for health care, compensation increases and other programs
for the nation's 27 million veterans.
   There is no disagreement that the coffers of the Department of
Veterans Affairs are running low. The agency has already begun
curtailing medical services, purchases of new equipment and other
efforts.
   The two bills also contain money for the Guaranteed Student Loan
program, forest fire fighting, foster care, refugee assistance,
United Nations peacekeeping and other initiatives.
   Before they can send a compromise bill to Bush for his signature,
lawmakers will have to make trade-offs over whose pet projects
remain in the measure.
   There are many.
   The House bill has provisions directing the Corps of Engineers to
build a road at Saylorville Lake, Iowa; allowing extra money to be
spent on an agriculture research center in Lane, Okla.; and
temporarily blocking development of a laser device in New Mexico as
an anti-satellite weapon.
   The Senate measure provides $75 million to replace a broken
300-foot radio telescope in West Virginia; supplies $7.3 million for
the cleanup of the Alaska oil spill; and urges the government to buy
more apples for the school lunch program.
   On Wednesday, the Senate rejected 51-49 an effort by Sen. John
McCain, R-Ariz., to amend the bill with a provision delaying much of
Medicare's new catastrophic care program for a year.
   Instead, senators agreed to non-binding language promising a
future look at altering the program, which imposes a surtax on the
elderly that some have complained costs them too much.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
