<FILEID>AP-NR-06-08-89 0303EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-MissileContract     06-08 0549</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Missile Contract,550</SECOND>
<HEAD>Navy Seeks End to Contractor's Favored Status on Cruise-Missile Engines</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TIM BOVEE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Navy, faced with a declining need for
cruise-missile engines because of arms-reduction treaties, wants to
torpedo a 1978 agreement that requires it to buy 240 of the
components annually from a Michigan company.
   The Navy's determination to end Williams International's favored
position in supplying the engines has prompted intervention by Sen.
Carl Levin, a Michigan Democrat who for years has criticized the
Pentagon for waste and non-competitive procurement practices.
   The Pentagon asserts the agreement with Williams is illegal under
a 1984 law authored by Levin, chairman of the Senate oversight of
government management subcommittee.
   Levin on Wednesday accused the Pentagon of trying to break a
promise out of convenience rather than a concern for the law.
   ``I think it is pure expediency, and it is full out unfair,''
Levin said.
   The outlines of the agreement were contained in correspondence
between Levin and the Navy made public both by the senator and a
Washington-based whistle-blower group, the Project on Military
Procurement.
   The agreement, negotiated because the Navy wanted a second source
of F107 engines for the Tomahawk cruise missile, required Williams,
of Walled Lake, Mich., to license its technology to a competitor,
Teledyne Industries Inc.
   In return, the Navy agreed to buy at least 240 engines a year
from Williams, plus 25 percent of any additional purchases up to
1,200 engines annually.
   The agreement has no expiration date and applies to all
government contracts for F107 engines.
   The Navy must contract through Williams in buying engines from
Teledyne. Williams has been paid about $36,000 for each of the 708
engines built by Teledyne, according to figures provided Levin by
the Navy.
   In a letter to Levin dated April 11, then-Navy Undersecretary H.
Lawrence Garrett III said the agreement violated Levin's amendments
to the Armed Services Procurement Act because it required the
government to buy the engines under contracts not yet negotiated.
   ``No contracting officer has the authority to bind the government
to award future contracts,'' wrote Garrett, who is now secretary of
the Navy.
   From 1990, the Navy plans to award the contracts ``without the
constraints of (the agreement), on the basis of the best value to
the government and the taxpayer,'' Garrett wrote.
   The contract was negotiated by William Parkin, a consultant and a
former Navy employee, Garrett wrote.
   Parkin and the former Navy engineer he bribed were given 26-month
prison terms June 2 for illegally scheming to help two companies get
Pentagon contracts.
   He and Stuart Berlin were each fined $25,000 and ordered to serve
two years of supervised probation after their release from prison.
Parkin pleaded guilty to charges that he bribed Berlin to provide
secret Navy bid information that would help Teledyne and Hazeltine
Corp. of Long Island, N.Y., obtain lucrative contracts to sell
electronic equipment to the Pentagon.
   The Associated Press sought comment from the Navy on the
agreement. The Navy's press office said Wednesday it was unable to
provide information immediately. Both the Navy and Levin's office
confirmed the existence of the Garrett letter.
   Williams vice president for public relations, David Jolivette,
declined to discuss the issue on the advice of counsel, saying the
matter had not yet been resolved.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890608-0029 </DOCNO>
