<FIRST>r i PM-Philippines-China     06-08 0484</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Philippines-China,0498</SECOND>
<HEAD>Filipino Evacuation Plans Thrown Into Confusion</HEAD>
<BYLINE>With PM-China, Bjt ^By MIGUEL C. SUAREZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANILA, Philippines (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Plans to evacuate Filipinos from
Beijing were thrown into confusion today and it took a private radio
station to unravel the mess by forcing officials to talk by
telephone with harried diplomats in China.
   The sometimes testy conversations, broadcast live by radio DZMM,
were between a foreign affairs undersecretary, an assistant to
President Corazon Aquino, officials of the state-run Philippine
Airlines and Filipino diplomats in Beijing.
   For more than a week, Philippine Charge d'Affaires Ariel Abadilla
and his deputy in Beijing, Corazon Tatarata, said there was no need
to evacuate some 300 Filipinos in the Chinese capital. But
Philippine Airlines and Air Force planes were ready at a moment's
notice, officials said.
   When the decision to evacuate came, arrangements were not in
place. Officials blamed each other.
   The situation ``is very alarming'' Miss Tatarata told the radio
station, and she appealed for PAL to send a plane to Beijing today
instead of Friday.
   Some embassy dependents had to beg for seats aboard a Singapore
Airlines flight because PAL failed to come and fetch them.
   ``You should not blame the department,'' snapped Foreign Affairs
Undersecretary Jose Ingles, clearly angry over insinuations that his
office was not acting urgently enough on messages from Beijing.
   ``We are doing our best,'' Ingles said. He then refused to talk
further with Miss Tatarata, saying he would deal directly only with
Abadilla.
   Ingles then blamed Philippine Airlines, which he said was
imposing unreasonable conditions.
   PAL, according to Ingles, had scheduled an Airbus-300 to fly to
Beijing Friday on condition Chinese authorities guarantee there
would be enough fuel at the airport and that the aircraft, crew and
passengers would be safe.
   ``PAL is imposing conditions over and above the ordinary
obligation of government,'' Ingles said. In the first place, he
added, he could not understand why PAL had canceled its regular
weekly flights to Beijing and other Chinese cities.
   Other national carriers, which had even increased flights to
evacuate their nationals, were flying in and out of the Chinese
capital without any conditions, he noted.
   Nevertheless, Ingles said he instructed Abadilla to obtain those
guarantees from the Chinese foreign ministry ``but up to now, he has
not informed us if these guarantees are forthcoming.''
   In a few moments, a panting Abadilla was on the phone. He said
Chinese authorities had provided the necessary guarantees and that
he had so reported in a telex sent Ingles' department a half hour
earlier.
   DZMM then let Adolfo Azcuna, President Corazon Aquino's legal
adviser and spokesman, speak privately to Ingles and Miss Tatarata
off the air.
   In a few minutes, PAL President Dante Santos came on the line and
said a plane would leave this afternoon for Beijing.
   Problem solved? Not quite. ``We will need 14 visas for our
crew,'' Santos said.
</TEXT>
