<SECOND>AM-Japan-Markets,0274</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Down, Share Prices Rise</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar moved up against the Japanese yen in
Tokyo Thursday, while stock prices gained moderately.
   The dollar closed at 143.05 yen, up 0.25 yen from Wednesday's
close of 142.80 yen. After opening higher at 142.98 yen, the U.S.
currency ranged between 142.73 and 143.10 yen during the day.
   On the Tokyo Stock Exchange, the Nikkei Stock Average of 225
selected issues, which rose 174.88 points Wednesday, added another
91.40 points, or 0.27 percent, closing at 33,718.29.
   Traders said Japanese investors' incentive to buy dollars was
weaker Thursday because of reports that the U.S. Federal Reserve
Board lowered its federal funds rate, a short-term interest rate.
   But Japan's central bank reportedly said it should keep a close
watch on the Fed's move to see if the decision really reflected a
U.S. policy toward easier money.
   Many investors still feel secure enough to invest in the dollar,
and bought the currency due to uncertainties over the Chinese
situation, said one dealer with a commercial bank in Tokyo speaking
on condition of anonymity.
   On the stock exchange, dealers said the index's rise followed
gains in the Dow Jones industrial average in New York overnight,
although trading was still directionless due to remaining
uncertainties over China.
   Nomura Securities' analyst Masahiro Umemori said, however, that
news about the Chinese turmoil has a less negative impact on Tokyo
trading than previously.
   ``Japanese investors have little feeling of insecurity about
developments in China. Plus, the foreign exchange rates have also
become stabilized and made market players feel reassured,'' he added.
</TEXT>
