<FIRST>u i PM-Japan-Markets     06-08 0326</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Japan-Markets,0337</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Gains In Tokyo</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar gained against the Japanese yen in Tokyo
today, while stock prices rose moderately despite continuing
uncertainties in China.
   The dollar ended trading at 143.10 yen, up 0.25 yen from
Wednesday's 142.80-yen finish. After opening higher at 142.98 yen,
the U.S. currency ranged between 142.73 and 143.10 yen.
   Masafumi Koyama with the Bank of Tokyo said dollar-buying
incentives were stronger than selling incentives, despite an
expectation that the United States may ease its monetary policy.
   ``Recent developments in China have a stronger impact, because
speculation over a relaxation of U.S. monetary policy has been an
issue for quite a while and is no longer fresh news,'' he said.
   Theoretically, he said, the market could shift to dollar selling
because of the narrowing interest-rate gap between Japan and the
United States.
   ``But investors are still buying the dollar, which shows how
strong their demand for the U.S. currency is,'' Koyama said.
   On the Tokyo Stock Exchange, the 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average
closed the day at 33,718.29, gaining 91.40 points, or 0.27 percent.
The index rose 174.88 points the previous day.
   Stocks moved higher almost across the board.
   Dealers attributed the gains to an uptrend begun the previous
day, as well as to overnight rises on overseas markets.
   Kazuyuki Suzuki, a dealer with Daiwa Securities in Tokyo, said
the Nikkei gained despite turmoil in China mainly because Japanese
investors' buying interest was strong.
   ``Trading was thin and directionless because of the uncertainties
in China, but many investors bought cheaper issues following the
four consecutive days of losses which ended Tuesday,'' he said.
   Other dealers said the market's expectation that the United
States would relax its monetary policy also prompted buying. Low
interest rates are generally good news for stock investors.
   The volume traded on the market's first section was estimated at
650 million shares, up from Wednesday's 600 million. Among the
winners were construction and automobile issues.
</TEXT>
