<FIRST>r i PM-Thailand-China     06-08 0404</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Thailand-China,0415</SECOND>
<HEAD>Thailand Says China Turmoil May Affect Cambodia Issue</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-China, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BANGKOK, Thailand (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Thailand is concerned that the turmoil
in China may delay the settlement of the Cambodian conflict, a
Foreign Ministry official said today.
   China is a principal player in Cambodia as the main backer of the
Khmer Rouge, the strongest of the three-party guerrilla coalition
opposing the pro-Vietnamese government in Phnom Penh.
   Foreign Ministry spokesman Jete Sucharitkhul said the Thai
government was ``very concerned'' about developments in Beijing,
where pro-democracy protests since mid-April escalated until troops
shot to death hundreds of people last weekend.
   ``Usually the (Chinese) government follows the party line, if
there is a power struggle you can imagine that they will be very
busy internally and not be able to pay as much attention to the
(Cambodian) issue as they have in the past,'' he said.
   But Jete said he did not think that apparant divisions in the
Chinese leadership would change China's policy on Cambodia.
   ``I don't think there will be a shift, just that they will be
able to pay less attention to the issue. But nobody can tell at the
moment as we don't know the extent of the infighting,'' he said.
   Recent peace talks have brought the various Cambodia factions
closer to a solution to the 10-year war. Vietnam, which invaded
Cambodia in 1978, has pledged to withdraw all its troops stationed
there by Sept. 30.
   But the major stumbling block to a peace settlement has been the
Khmer Rouge, who were ousted from power by the Vietnamese invasion.
   The Khmer Rouge killed as many as 1 million Cambodians from 1975
to 1978 as it violently tried to turn the country into a radical
agrarian commune.
   Recent peace talks have focused on whether the Khmer Rouge should
be allowed to participate in a future coalition government.
   The Khmer Rouge announced last week that Pol Pot, the man who
presided over their rule, wished to resign his last official post in
the organization.
   Diplomats dismissed the move as a ploy to present a more
acceptable face in future negotiations. The government in Phnom Penh
has insisted that Pol Pot and other leaders be removed before the
Khmer Rouge is allowed any share of power.
   There are unconfirmed reports from Western diplomats in Bangkok
that the shadowy leader, believed to be in his early 60's, is
currently in Beijing for medical treatment.
</TEXT>
