<FIRST>r a PM-RockyFlats     06-08 0545</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Rocky Flats,0563</SECOND>
<HEAD>Colorado Health Department Cites Rocky Flats For 25 Violations</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JULIA RUBIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DENVER (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A plant that makes triggers for nuclear bombs was
slapped with 25 state health violations the day after federal agents
launched an inquiry into illegal dumping and burning of hazardous
wastes at the facility.
   The state's action Wednesday against the Rocky Flats nuclear
plant was independent of the federal investigation and the timing of
the two announcements was ``coincidence,'' said Tom Looby, assistant
director of the Colorado Department of Health.
   The state accused the Department of Energy and Rockwell
International Corp., which operates Rocky Flats for DOE, of
improperly storing wastes, failing to monitor groundwater adequately
and storing hazardous wastes in leaking drums.
   ``The violations involved raised some serious questions in our
mind about the overall ability of the Department of Energy and
Rockwell to manage the plant,'' said Looby.
   Rockwell International spokesman Ed Heintz said he had not seen
the health department allegations.
   ``But I would be surprised if there are any new violations and it
is just a matter of interpretation whether or not the deficiencies
are cleared up or in the process of being cleared up,'' Heintz said.
   The plant 16 miles northwest of Denver makes plutonium triggers
for nuclear bombs.
   Agents from the FBI, the U.S. Environmental Protection Agency and
DOE carried out search warrants there Wednesday for the second day
in a row.
   The Justice Department said plant employees allegedly concealed
contamination and illegally treated, stored and disposed of
hazardous and radioactive waste.
   Looby said the state's order included a total of 24 citations for
violation of rules for monitoring hazardous waste in groundwater;
unapproved storage of hazardous and mixed wastes; leaking hazardous
waste drums; inadequate record-keeping and personnel training, and
failure to maintain proper aisle space in waste storage areas.
   ``No individual instance is a terribly nasty violation,'' said
Dave Shelton, director of the health department's Hazardous
Materials and Waste Management Division.
   ``The concern is that in the aggregate, it shows that the
facility has a good deal of difficulty in managing its hazardous
waste ... in order to stay in compliance with state standards,''
Shelton said.
   The order gives DOE and Rockwell 10 days to request a meeting to
discuss the order. The state then has a month to finalize the order
and to set a compliance deadline for each violation. The maximum
penalty for noncompliance is $25,000 per violation per day,
officials said.
   Rocky Flats has been dogged by safety and environmental problems
since it began operations in 1953, but particularly in recent years.
   Last year, the Energy Department identified it as the most
environmentally hazardous site in the nuclear weapons industry
because toxic chemicals contaminate an underground reservoir and
threaten nearby city water supplies.
   In October, the agency closed Rocky Flats' main plutonium
reprocessing building for safety violations. Two months later, the
agency reported 32 new safety problems at the plant.
   The Energy Department has announced plans to close Rocky Flats in
the next 20 years in a consolidation of America's nuclear weapons
plants.
   In a previous federal probe of a nuclear weapons complex in 1986,
the EPA examined Energy Department handling of hazardous waste at
its Hanford, Wash., reservation. No criminal prosecution resulted.
</TEXT>
