<FIRST>r a PM-D'Amato-Audit     06-08 0481</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-D'Amato-Audit,0498</SECOND>
<HEAD>HUD Audit: Village Officials Gave Preferential Treatment</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Officials in a predominately white Long Island
village that is home to U.S. Sen. Alfonse M. D'Amato, distributed
federally subsidized homes to politically connected people and
excluded blacks, according to a report published today.
   One person who received such preferential treatment was D'Amato's
cousin, Anthony Ciccimarro, who was selected to buy a $40,000 HUD
house in Island Park, The New York Times reported, citing a 1984
audit by the federal Department of Housing and Urban Development.
   D'Amato was supervisor of the town of Hempstead, which includes
Island Park, at the time and was elected to the U.S. Senate shortly
thereafter, the Times said.
   D'Amato denied any favoritism was involved, and said he had no
role in the selection process, the Times said.
   ``There's no reason to believe anything was inappropriate,'' said
a statement released by D'Amato's office.
   Preferential treatment also was accorded to Geraldine McGann, a
village board member and high-ranking HUD administrator, whose son,
Daniel, received a $44,500 house, the Times said, citing the audit.
   Mrs. McGann, a friend of D'Amato, also denied any favoritism took
place.
   Under a federal program to build affordable housing for
minorities, Nassau County in the early 1980s received money to build
285 houses for lower-income families.
   Island Park, population 4,200 and 97 percent white, received
enough money to build 44 homes to be sold at $40,000 to $64,000. HUD
proposed that 17 of the 22 houses to be built during the project's
second phase be sold to blacks from nearby areas, but none were.
   Twelve of the 44 HUD houses have since been resold at large
profit; one went for $270,000, the Times said.
   The audit did not say whether those selected for the HUD houses
met the program's eligibility requirements. The buyers included the
niece of the village clerk, the niece of a village trustee, two
village supervisors, a lawyer who is soon to become a village
justice and the daughter of a village employee, the Times said.
   The HUD houses were supposed to be advertised in local newspapers
to reach lower-income buyers, especially minorities.
   But some residents were tipped off, and by the time the ads
appeared, 22 buyers had been selected, the Times said.
   The 1984 audit recommended disciplinary action against Mrs.
McGann and the village, but neither was penalized.
   Mrs. McGann last year was promoted to regional HUD administrator
after D'Amato lobbied Congress and the White House on her behalf,
the Times said.
   A copy of the audit was mailed anonymously to the Times, which
said it then requested and received a copy from HUD to verify its
authenticity.
   ``This program was a mockery,'' said Jeff Pless, who did the
audit and later quit in disgust that no action was taken. ``It took
everyone's tax money and gave it to the people who didn't need it.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
