<FIRST>r a PM-WeatherpageWeather     06-08 0582</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Weatherpage Weather,0599</SECOND>
<HEAD>Tornadoes, High Winds and Heavy Rains Plague South</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   High winds and a tornado ripped through southeast Louisiana early
today, tearing down trees and power lines and demolishing a brick
home, as menacing thunderstorms rumbled through the South.
   Thunderstorms accompanied by damaging winds and torrential rains
hit northeast Texas, across Louisiana, and into southern Mississippi
on Wednesday night and early today.
   In central Louisiana, a tornado struck Marksville early today,
destroying a brick home and injuring a woman trapped inside. High
winds toppled a chimney and downed trees in eastern Baton Rouge
Parish.
   The thunderstorms also brought heavy rain across portions of
northern Louisiana. Homes and streets in Bossier City were flooded
when more than 5{ inches of rain fell in three hours.
   In Texas, four people were injured Wednesday night when a twister
destroyed several homes in Gary on the Texas-Louisiana border.
   ``We heard the noise and decided to get out of the house,'' said
mobile home resident Mark White. ``We were sitting in the car on the
highway, looking back, and saw trees flying in the air and our
trailer rolling along _ over and over.''
   Western and central Nevada also were hit by strong thunderstorms
Wednesday afternoon. A tornado touched down near Carson City. Reno
was pelted by 1-inch sized hail. Heavy rain flooded streets in Reno
and produced a mud slide that closed a highway near Hawthorne.
   Other showers and thunderstorms moved ahead of cold front from
eastern Kansas into northeast Iowa. An upper air disturbance
triggered showers and thunderstorms across much of New England.
Showers were widely scattered from northern California into central
Colorado.
   Today's forecast called for showers and thunderstorms from the
lower Mississippi Valley across the Gulf coastal states to the mid
and south Atlantic coastal states; severe thunderstorms from eastern
Mississippi across Alabama and Georgia into western South Carolina;
showers and thunderstorms in the Great Lakes region; scattered
showers and thunderstorms over eastern Texas, the upper Mississippi
Valley and much of the Plateau; widely scattered thunderstorms over
the mountains and eastern sections of Colorado; and showers over New
England and eastern New York.
   Temperatures were forecast in the 60s over eastern New England
and North Dakota; in the 50s and 60s over the upper Great Lakes and
Minnesota; in the 90s from south Texas across southern Arizona to
interior sections of central and southern California; between 100
and 105 over parts of the lower Rio Grande Valley and southeast
California; and in the 70s and 80s throughout the rest of the nation.
   Temperatures around the nation at 3 a.m. EDT ranged from 40
degrees at Williston, N.D., and Duluth, Minn., to 87 degrees at
Phoenix, Ariz.
   Other reports:
   _East: Atlanta 70 fair; Boston 57 rain; Buffalo 64 partly cloudy;
Charleston, S.C. 75 foggy; Cincinnati 60 fair; Cleveland 62 fair;
Detroit 68 partly cloudy; Miami 78 fair; New York 66 foggy;
Philadelphia 66 foggy; Pittsburgh 62 fair; Portland, Maine, 56 rain;
Washington 67 fog.
   _Central: Bismarck 49 cloudy; Chicago 72 partly cloudy;
Dallas-Fort Worth 65 fair; Denver 55 partly cloudy; Des Moines 63
showery; Indianapolis 65 fair; Kansas City 66 rain; Minneapolis-St.
Paul 56 cloudy; Nashville 65 fair; New Orleans 80 cloudy; St. Louis
69 partly cloudy.
   _West: Albuquerque 72 windy; Anchorage 50 cloudy; Las Vegas 77
fair; Los Angeles 60 cloudy; Phoenix 87 fair; Salt Lake City 65
cloudy; San Diego 62 cloudy; San Francisco 54 cloudy; Seattle 58
fair.
   _Canada: Montreal 63 fair; Toronto 63 fair.
</TEXT>
