<FIRST>r a PM-FootballReunion     06-08 0387</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Football Reunion,0398</SECOND>
<HEAD>Football Game Canceled By Kennedy Assassination Finally Played</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HOLDEN LEWIS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>EL PASO, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   More than 25 years after their game was
canceled because of President Kennedy's assassination, alumni from
two rival high schools took to the gridiron to complete their last
football season.
   Bowie and Jefferson high schools have long had the hottest
scholastic rivalry in El Paso. On the morning of Nov. 22, 1963, the
schools were holding pep rallies and preparing to cap their seasons
with the annual double homecoming. But an assassin's bullet in
Dallas prompted officials to cancel the game.
   ``If you beat Jefferson, that was it. That was your season _
nothing else mattered,'' said Felipe Peralta, who played wide
receiver as a Bowie senior in 1963 and coached Wednesday night's
game.
   ``I think at the time most of us thought it was important to play
the game. You don't actually complete your high-school season when
you can't play your main rival.''
   Alumni from the schools settled the score Wednesday night with a
spirited game of seven-man touch football before 400 spectators at
Bowie Stadium. The home team won, 20-8.
   The contest wasn't pretty. The Bowie Bears threw bombs on almost
every play and the Jefferson Silver Foxes threw so many laterals
that it resembled a volleyball game. But that didn't bother the
players.
   ``It was a lot of fun,'' said Bowie's Rudy Molinar. ``It was just
friends against friends.''
   The contest brought back memories of that fateful day.
   ``I was excited,'' Jefferson alumnus Oscar Gomez recalled about
the week leading to the canceled 1963 game. ``Then our dear
president passed away, which was terrible. It was nice to get to
play again.''
   ``The whole country was down because of the shooting, but we were
down because of the game,'' said Gomez' teammate, Manny Florez.
``It's a game you look forward to all year.''
   Or look forward to for a quarter century. Alumni from both
schools had talked for years about playing the canceled game. Last
week, Bowie's Class of '64 _ which is celebrating its 25th reunion
this week _ decided to stage the game. Those who took part were glad
they did.
   ``There was a piece missing from our lives when we didn't get to
play that game,'' Peralta said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
