<FIRST>u i PM-Dollar-Gold     06-08 0268</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Dollar-Gold,0284</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Firmer, Gold Little Changed</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. dollar was mostly firmer in quiet European
trading today. Gold prices were little changed.
   Foreign currency dealers said the market was waiting for Friday's
scheduled release of the U.S. producer price index for May.
   They said they're expecting a quiet day, with little movement in
either direction. Next week's release of U.s. merchandise trade data
for the first quarter is also adding to the market's caution, they
said.
   ``It's very quiet today,'' said a trader at Deutsche Bank in
Frankfurt. ``There's almost no turnover. Everyone's waiting for the
numbers from the U.S.''
   In Tokyo, where trading ends before Europe's business day begins,
the dollar rose 0.25 yen to a closing 143.05 yen. Later, in London,
it was quoted at 142.95 yen.
   Other dollar rates at midmorning compared with late Wednesday:
   _1.9730 West German marks, up from 1.9610
   _1.7100 Swiss francs, up from 1.6965
   _6.6962 French francs, up from 6.6600
   _2.2243 Dutch guilders, up from 2.2138
   _1,437.50 Italian lire, down from 1,441.00
   _1.1968 Canadian dollars, up from 1.1967
   In London, the dollar rose against the British pound. It cost
$1.5753 to buy one pound, compared with $1.5815 late Wednesday.
   Gold opened in London at $375 a troy ounce, down from late
Wednesday's $375.65. At midmorning, the city's five major bullion
dealers fixed a recommended price of $374.60.
   In Zurich, the bid price was $374.50, unchanged from late
Wednesday.
   Silver was quoted in London at $5.45 a troy ounce, up from
Wednesday's $5.38.
   Financial institutions were closed today in Hong Kong for the
Chinese Dragon Boat festival.
</TEXT>
