<FIRST>r a PM-Duke-Nazism     06-08 0331</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Duke-Nazism,0345</SECOND>
<HEAD>Researcher: Duke Still Promoting Neo-Nazism</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LINDA ASHTON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BATON ROUGE, La. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Books that advocate Nazism and question
whether the Holocaust occurred were on sale last week at state Rep.
David Duke's house, says a researcher concerned that fellow
legislators are not challenging Duke.
   ``No one is speaking out against the ideas of David Duke. He has
not changed his views even though he says he has,'' Elizabeth
Rickey, a Tulane University graduate student and member of the
Republican State Central Committee, said Wednesday.
   Duke, a former grand wizard of the Ku Klux Klan, was elected to
the state legislature from a nearly all-white district in February.
He still heads the National Association for the Advancement of White
People, which promotes the civil rights of whites. His house serves
as headquarters for the organization.
   Rickey said she was upset that some Louisiana Republicans had
accepted Duke.
   ``They honestly don't know what to do with him,'' she said.
``They think if you ignore him, he'll go away.''
   Rickey said she and other researchers purchased anti-Jewish and
extremist material from Duke's house in Metairie as recently as
Saturday.
   Among the materials Rickey said she bought were:
   _ ``The Turner Diaries,'' described as the bible of the Order, a
white supremacist organization founded by members of the National
Alliance and the Aryan Nations.
   _ ``Imperium,'' which argues for the preservation of Western
culture through the practice of Nazi racist policies.
   _ ``Did Six Million Really Die? The Truth at Last,'' which argues
that the Holocaust was grossly exaggerated to gain sympathy for a
Jewish homeland.
   Also available were books on breeding a master race, Rickey said.
   Duke denied that he was selling the books. Asked how Rickey and
her associates could buy them, he said, ``It might have been some
old stock.''
   ``This is nothing new,'' Duke said. ``I've sold a wide range of
books. I think people have a right to read all points of view.''
</TEXT>
