<DOCNO> AP890608-0061 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-08-89 0717EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-LandlordSuit     06-08 0380</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Landlord Suit,0390</SECOND>
<HEAD>Judge Assesses More Than $1,000 For Marital Status Discrimination</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAULA FROKE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MINNEAPOLIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A landlord who agreed to rent a house to an
unmarried couple and then reneged, citing his Christian values, has
been ordered to pay more than $1,000 in damages and penalties.
   A judge refused to treble the damages, however, as the law
allows, because he said the landlord acted out of ``sincerely held
religious beliefs.''
   Administrative law Judge Peter Erickson ruled Wednesday that
Layle French must pay $368.50 in compensatory damages and $400 for
mental anguish to Susan Parsons Jenson, as well as $300 in civil
penalties to the state.
   The judge ruled in March that French violated a state law
prohibiting discrimination based on marital status by refusing to
rent a house to Jenson and her then-fiance.
   French ``reflected upon his action prior to engaging in the
discriminatory conduct and weighed his duties under the law against
his religious beliefs,'' Erickson said.
   French's argument that the discrimination statute should take a
back seat to his Christian values had attracted wide support in
Minnesota and elsewhere in the country. French is a member of the
Marshall Evangelical Free Church.
   His attorney, James Anderson, said Wednesday he plans to take the
case to the state Court of Appeals.
   Anderson said he is ``saddened about a man who is fighting a
trend, and that is a general moral decay of the country, and the
state has seen fit not to promote what he's doing but rather to
promote the moral decay.''
   Anderson said he was especially distressed at the civil penalty
because he claimed French was upholding the state law banning
fornication. He said he had not been able to reach French to inform
him of the ruling.
   Erickson noted in his decision that when French first agreed to
rent to Jenson and her then-fiance on Feb. 22, 1988, he knew that
the couple was not married. Two days later, Erickson noted, French
called Jenson ``and informed her that he could not rent the property
to her because cohabitation by two adults of the opposite sex was
not in accord with his religious beliefs.''
   By that time, Jenson had given up her rental mobile home. She
later married her fiance.
</TEXT>
