<FIRST>r a PM-DairyShootings     06-08 0341</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Dairy Shootings,0351</SECOND>
<HEAD>Four Die in Dairy Farm Shooting</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GRAHAM, Wash. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man who went looking for his estranged
wife in violation of a court order shot and killed three people at a
dairy farm, then turned the gun on himself after failing to find
her, police said.
   The killer, Kenneth Gehring, died at a hospital a few hours after
the shootings Wednesday.
   The victims were the couple who owned the farm, Nellie Rutheda
LaCrosse and Tom LaCrosse, both 63, and Kirby Hull, 43, a dairy
truck driver.
   Gehring's wife, Eileen May Gehring, was visiting the farm Tuesday
evening when her husband arrived and drove off in her car. Deputies
arrived and drove the woman to her apartment in nearby Puyallup,
said Capt. Steve Poythress of the Pierce County sheriff's department.
   Gehring, apparently believing his wife was still at the house,
arrived the next morning armed with a .22-caliber rifle. He shot
Hull, who had arrived to pick up a load of milk, then went into the
house and shot and killed the LaCrosse couple.
   He then shot himself in the head, said Sgt. Prentis Hunsinger of
the Pierce County sheriff's department.
   Friends and authorities said the LaCrosses did not know Gehring.
   Gehring, a 35-year-old sawyer at a local wood mill, was under a
court order to stay away from his wife of 18 years. Mrs. Gehring had
told authorities that her husband was threatening to kill her.
   Neighbors said the LaCrosses had operated the 400-cow dairy for
23 years and were well-known in the rural community south of Tacoma.
   ``They were such good neighbors, they would help anyone,'' said
Laura Schelbert, who lived across from the LaCrosse farm for 20
years. ``When we had a sick animal, he would come out and help us.
...This couple has touched a lot of lives.''
   Hull left a wife and four children, authorities said.
   ``This type of thing is unheard of in our rural community. You
try to look for reasons,'' said Marilyn Rasmussen, a state
representative and dairy farmer.
</TEXT>
