<FIRST>d a PM-BRF--MayorImpersonator     06-08 0160</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-BRF--Mayor Impersonator,0162</SECOND>
<HEAD>Court Upholds Firing of Producer Who Aired Mayor Impersonator</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An appeals court has upheld the firing of a radio
station producer for airing an impersonation of then-Mayor Kevin
White in 1982.
   The state court said that the incident ``was not exactly `The War
of the Worlds''' but that WRKO-AM had every right to fire Paul
Yovino for inviting an impersonator on air to take calls from the
audience as ``His Honor.''
   ``He pretended to be the mayor, although greatly exaggerating the
mannerisms of the persona of the real mayor,'' Judge Rudolph Kass
said Wednesday. ``Broad as the caricature may have been, the
impersonator induced a flurry of phone calls to City Hall in which
the callers made unflattering observations about what the `mayor'
was saying on the air.''
   Upholding a lower-court ruling, the judge said Yovino's failure
to ensure that the audience knew the ``mayor'' was an impersonator
amounted to a serious error.
