<SECOND>PM-Armored Car Spill,0284</SECOND>
<HEAD>Armored Car Spills Money on Highway During Rush Hour; People Enriched</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HOLDEN LEWIS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>EL PASO, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A blizzard of $20 bills on a highway
stopped rush-hour traffic cold and sorely tempted a man who returned
$440,000 after staring for hours at a 45-pound sack of cash on his
kitchen table.
   More than $500,000 fell out the back of a Loomis Armored Inc.
truck about 9 a.m. Wednesday on Interstate 10 near downtown, police
said. One sack broke, and $20 bills littered the four-lane highway.
   FBI spokesman Terry Kincaid said at least $100,000 was still
missing.
   ``With the turbulence of the traffic, the money was flying in the
air like a Toyota commercial,'' said police shift supervisor Hank
DiMatteo. He said at least 20 motorists stopped to grab cash,
causing a half-mile traffic jam.
   Rudy Vega grabbed a canvas sack of money, threw it in his car and
drove home, where he stacked the cash on the table and counted it.
   He turned in the money to the FBI five hours later.
   ``It was $440,000, and I said this was too much money,'' Vega
said. ``My conscience would have really bothered me.''
   Others weren't quite so honest. Police charged two men with theft
for allegedly grabbing $3,840. In addition, police got license plate
numbers of about 20 other suspected cash-grabbers and planned to
pursue them.
   ``This is an education in greed in people,'' Campos said.
   Police said the driver of the truck apparently didn't secure the
back doors before setting out from the Federal Reserve Bank in El
Paso to the one in Dallas.
</TEXT>
