<FILEID>AP-NR-06-08-89 0848EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u w PM-BusinessInvestment     06-08 0440</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Business Investment,430</SECOND>
<HEAD>Businesses Plan to Increase Spending on Plants and Equipment by 6.5
Percent</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN D. McCLAIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government reported today that American
businesses plan to increase spending on plants and equipment by a
solid 6.5 percent in 1989, despite growing evidence that economic
growth is slowing.
   Businesses responding to the Commerce Department survey said they
expected to spend $451.43 billion for expansion and modernization
this year. That is up from a record $423.69 billion spent on
business investment in 1988, the department said. All of the numbers
are adjusted for inflation.
   The survey, completed in May, indicated that businesses have
stepped up slightly their capital spending plans since a similar
survey completed in March found plans to increase spending by 6.3
percent this year.
   In an even earlier survey of 1989 business investment plans,
conducted last December, companies had estimated their capital
spending would increase 5.9 percent this year.
   The economy grew at a 4.3 percent annual rate during the first
quarter of 1989, but growth in the gross national product was a
sluggish 1.8 percent discounting a statistical bounceback from last
summer's drought. That compares with GNP growth of 3.9 percent for
all of 1988.
   The slower growth is attributed to the Federal Reserve's upward
pressure on interest rates for 15 months as it attempted to slow the
economy to ease inflation.
   The projected growth in business spending would spell good news
for the economy, providing part of the momentum needed to guide it
to a slower growth path without sliding into a recession.
   It also could help stem inflation by boosting production, and
thus avoiding shortages and increasing the amount of goods available
to American consumers.
   Capital spending grew 10.1 percent in 1988 as companies rushed to
expand production to meet rising export demand. It was the sharpest
increase since a 16.6 percent jump in 1984, when businesses were
still recovering from the 1981-82 recession.
   Spending climbed just 2.3 percent in 1987 and dropped 3.9 percent
in 1986.
   In the latest survey, manufacturing companies said they planned a
3.6 percent increase in capital outlays to $170.54 billion, compared
to 12.8 percent in 1988. This includes a 1.4 percent rise in plants
that produce durable goods, items expected to last three years or
more, and a 5.7 percent increase in companies producing non-durable
goods.
   Companies engaged in mining, transportation and other
non-manufacturing ventures are expected to increase spending by 8.4
percent to $280.89 billion.
   Before adjusting for inflation, 1989 plant and equipment spending
is expected to rise by 9.9 percent to $472.08 billion, down from
10.3 percent in 1988.
</TEXT>
