<FIRST>r p PM-PepperElection     06-08 0344</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Pepper Election,0357</SECOND>
<HEAD>Two Cuban-Born Republicans Enter Race for Pepper's Seat</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAN SEWELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The race is on for the U.S. House seat left vacant
by the death of Claude Pepper, with early expectations that the Aug.
29 special election will produce the first Cuban-born member of
Congress.
   In bilingual news conferences Wednesday, two Cuban-born
Republicans, state Sen. Ileana Ros-Lehtinen and conservative
businessman Carlos Perez, announced they will seek the nomination
for the seat held 26 years by Pepper, a liberal Democrat in a
district that came to be dominated by conservative Hispanics.
   Democrats vowed to hold onto the seat and turn the tide of GOP
victories in the South.
   ``The perception that we are flat on our backs in the region is
false,'' National Democratic Chairman Ron Brown said in Washington.
   The Miami area is home to many of the 1 million Cubans who have
come to the United States since Fidel Castro came to power 30 years
ago. Cuban-Americans tend to be more conservative and more ardently
anti-communist than other Hispanic-Americans.
   Ros-Lehtinen is an educator elected in 1982 to the Legislature.
She is married to U.S. Attorney Dexter Lehtinen.
   Perez, a once-destitute immigrant who built a multimillion-dollar
banana importing business and raised money for former Marine Lt.
Col. Oliver North, was once hailed by President Reagan as an example
of the American dream.
   State Sen. Jack Gordon is the most prominent name in a long list
of potential Democratic candidates. He said he will announce his
decision by Friday.
   His opposition to aid to the Nicaraguan Contras angered many
Cuban and Nicaraguan exiles.
   Registration in Florida's 18th district is 54 percent Democrat,
down from 72 percent a decade ago. The district ranges from
inner-city black areas and retirement enclaves to Little Havana and
upscale suburbs.
   Hispanis make up 40 percent to nearly half of the district.
   Pepper, who died at age 88 on May 30, was known as the last of
the New Deal liberals but took strong anti-communism stands,
including support of Contra aid.
</TEXT>
