<HEAD>Colleagues Wish Happy Birthday to British Hostage</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Iran</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A city newspaper published a belated
birthday wish to Terry Waite from colleagues in Britain today, eight
days after he turned 50 and nearly 15 months since he was taken
hostage.
   The short, paid advertisement included a telephone number in
England, an apparent effort to initiate contact with Waite's
kidnappers.
   The message, wishing Waite a ``belated happy birthday'' from
colleagues in London, appeared on page three of the independent
An-Nahar daily.
   Waite, a Church of England envoy, was on his fifth Beirut mission
to seek freedom for hostages when he disappeared Jan. 20, 1987.
   He had left his hotel in Moslem west Beirut for a rendezvous,
apparently with representatives of Islamic Jihad, or Islamic holy
war, which holds U.S. hostages Terry Anderson and Thomas Sutherland.
   Waite never returned, and no group has claimed responsibility for
taking him hostage. He is among 15 foreign hostages, including nine
Americans, held captive in Lebanon. Anderson, chief Middle East
correspondent for The Associated Press, is the longest held of the
foreign hostages in Lebanon. He was kidnapped March 16, 1985.
