<SECOND>PM-China-Dissident,0303</SECOND>
<HEAD>China Protests Over U.S. Sheltering of Dissident</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-China, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   China today accused the United States of violating
Chinese law and interfering in China's domestic affairs by giving
refuge to the nation's best-known dissident, Fang Lizhi.
   Vice Foreign Minister Zhu Qizhen, in a meeting with U.S.
Ambassador James Lilley, criticized the United States for ``wanton
interference in China's internal affairs,'' the official Xinhua News
Agency reported.
   ``We hereby express our profound regret and lodge a strong
protest and will closely follow further developments,'' Zhu was
quoted as saying.
   Fang took refuge in the U.S. Embassy on Sunday, hours after the
military moved into the city to crush pro-democracy protests.
   The dissident had earlier told The Associated Press he feared
arrest as hardliners in the government moved to stamp out the
democratic movement.
   Zhu said the United States had violated international and Chinese
law by giving shelter to the dissident.
   The State Department in Washington said Fang and his wife have
sought refuge but have not requested political asylum.
   Fang, a 53-year-old astrophysicist, gained international
prominence when the government accused him of provoking
pro-democracy student demonstrations in December 1986-January 1987.
   He was expelled from the Communist Party and lost his position as
vice president of the Science and Technology University in Anhui. He
was reassigned to work at an obversatory in Beijing.
   Fang has led Chinese intellectuals in calling for release of
political prisoners and asserting that economic and scientific
progress is impossible without protections for free thought. He has
also angered the Chinese by saying that Marxism is dead.
   He was at the hub of a dispute in February when Chinese police
stopped him from attending a dinner attended by President Bush
during a visit to Beijing.
