<FIRST>r w PM-Bush-Nixon     06-08 0207</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Bush-Nixon,200</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bush Spoke with Nixon Before Announcing China Response</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush spoke by telephone with former
President Nixon before making his announcement of action in response
to the current crackdown on dissidents in China, a spokesman for
Nixon said today.
   John Taylor, speaking by telephone from Nixon's office in New
Jersey, said Bush telephoned the former president about an hour and
a half before making his announcement on Monday.
   Taylor said he had no information on the content of the telephone
call, which he said lasted about 10 minutes. He said it is Nixon's
policy not to discuss his conversations with presidents.
   Bush annnounced on Monday that he was suspending U.S. arms sales
to China to protest the Chinese military's bloody weekend crackdown.
He said he was not taking action toward severing diplomatic ties or
imposing economic sanctions that could hurt ``the Chinese people.''
   Nixon is associated with China because of steps he took to
improve U.S.-Chinese relations during his administration.
   Taylor said the former president has not expressed his views on
the current turmoil in China, but may do so soon in written form.
   Nixon spoke several times in person and by telephone with former
President Reagan during his two terms.
</TEXT>
