<HEAD>People in the News</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY44</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MALIBU, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Actor Martin Sheen can remain honorary
mayor of this exclusive beachfront community despite the impromptu
welcome he gave to the homeless, the Chamber of Commerce decided.
   Sheen created a hubbub last month when, shortly after his
appointment, he declared Malibu a ``nuclear-free zone, a sanctuary
for aliens and the homeless and a protected environment for all
life, wild and tame.''
   A syndicated radio talk show host took Sheen up on his
declaration, offering to bus hundreds of homeless people to Malibu.
Some local business leaders urged the chamber to take back Sheen's
ceremonial title.
   Late Wednesday, the chamber met behind closed doors to take up
the matter.
   ``We unanimously voted to support him as honorary mayor for
1989,'' announced Olivia Thornton, the group's president.
   Chamber members praised the veteran actor, a longtime supporter
of liberal causes who has been arrested several times at various
protests.
   ``Sheen possesses and is entitled to his own points of view and I
think he is truly trying to do good,'' said former chamber President
Peter Arnold. The honorary mayor appears at community functions and
promotes Malibu shopping.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Barbara Bush has written to English schoolchildren
about her dyslexic son, Neil, to cheer on their efforts to overcome
the learning disability.
   Officials at Edington School at Burtle Hill in Somerset, which
specializes in education of dyslexics, said Wednesday that pupils
received a reply from the American first lady after writing to
congratulate her on her husband's inauguration.
   Mrs. Bush's letter said her son had ``special remediation, just
as you are having. Today, Neil has a graduate degree and runs his
own business. The president and I are enormously proud to have such
a wonderful, successful son.''
   Dyslexics have difficulty in reading and spelling.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>ELLISTON, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Actor Robert Duvall spent the day at an
elementary school where he sat on the floor, ate lunch, answered
questions and surprised the principal who did not believe he would
accept an invitation.
   The star of the hit miniseries ``Lonesome Dove'' wore a Western
hat, jeans and cowboy boots when he visited the 220-student
Elliston-Lafayette Elementary School in rural Montgomery County.
   ``We had no idea that a person so famous would come,'' Principal
Lois Hinkle said after the actor had climbed into his pickup and
headed back to his farm in northern Virginia.
   Duvall told the children his age, 58, ate turkey and dressing,
and sat on the floor with the students.
   The children decided to write the actor after a visiting artist
drew a picture of Duvall, in his role in ``Lonesome Dove,'' as part
of a demonstration to an art class. The children suggested he might
want to visit them for a ``Lonesome Dove Day,'' with everyone
dressed in Western garb.
   ``It only took me 20 or 30 seconds to decide to come down here,
after reading their letters,'' said Duvall, who accepted the
portrait during an assembly. ``They touched me. It's an honor and
I'm really glad I came.''
   ``He was an absolutely fantastic person. He went around to all
the tables at lunchtime,'' said Ms. Hinkle, who wore cowboy boots
for the occasion.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WOODLAND HILLS, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sondra Locke's palimony suit
against actor Clint Eastwood likely will go to trial because
attorneys for the separated couple failed to reach a settlement,
according to a published report.
   Eastwood, 58, and Locke, 42, split after being together for 13
years. Locke's lawsuit, filed in April, alleges Eastwood persuaded
her to have two abortions and to be sterilized during their
relationship.
   Their attorneys failed to work out a settlement during a closed
session this week with Los Angeles Superior Court Judge William
Hogoboom, the Los Angeles Daily News reported Wednesday.
   Unless further talks are successful, the lawsuit is expected to
go to trial sometime this fall or early next year.
   Eastwood and Locke met on the set of ``The Outlaw Josey Wales.''
They have appeared together in several films, including ``The
Gauntlet.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>BEVERLY HILLS, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Jane Fonda, embraced by a former
Soviet prisoner she helped free, accepted an award for social
concern amid tributes to her activism.
   ``She was as a sister to me. She was there when I needed her,''
said Ida Nudel, known as the ``guardian angel'' of the Soviet
refusenik movement.
   Miss Fonda, who championed the dissident's cause before she was
allowed to immigrate to Israel in 1987, appeared stunned by Ms.
Nudel's presence at Wednesday night's banquet. She was flown in as a
surprise presenter of the award from the American Jewish Committee.
   ``When we have a chance to rub shoulders with someone truly
courageous, we're never the same again,'' the Academy Award-winning
actress said of Ms. Nudel. ``I'm so grateful to her.''
   Wednesday night's banquet also featured tributes to Miss Fonda
from the co-stars of her new movie, ``Old Gringo,'' and filmed
greetings from such luminaries as South African Archbishop Desmond
Tutu, Israeli leader Shimon Peres, feminist Gloria Steinem and labor
leader Caesar Chavez.
   Miss Fonda, who often has received brickbats rather than plaudits
for her liberal activism, said, ``I feel so lucky tonight because
there are so many friendly eyes here. I feel so surrounded by love.''
   She added with a laugh, ``My kids would say, `Lighten up,
Fonda.'''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   In front of a huge Solidarity banner, folk
singer Joan Baez sang at a Warsaw factory to honor the union's
election victory and speak out for those people still struggling for
