<FIRST>u a PM-UnlicensedDropout     06-08 0277</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Unlicensed Dropout,0293</SECOND>
<HEAD>W.Va. Youth Files Lawsuit to Regain License</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID WILKISON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHARLESTON, W.Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A teen-age father-to-be who lost his
license for dropping out of school is mounting the first court
challenge to the law.
   Michael Means, 17, sued on Wednesday to have West Virginia's
first-in-the-nation anti-truancy law declared unconstitutional.
   Under the law passed last summer, students under 18 who miss more
than 10 consecutive days of school or have 15 unexcused absences
lose their driving privileges.
   ``I think the law is ignorant. It shouldn't have had to go this
far,'' said the teen-ager's father, William Means.
   The younger Means dropped out a year ago in the ninth grade. On
May 30, the license was revoked.
   Means, whose 16-year-old wife, Tonya, is expecting the couple's
first child in September, has argued that he can't get a job without
a license and that he is entitled to an exception under a hardship
clause in the law.
   However, school officials have said that Means is not entitled to
an exemption because he could work and still complete his education.
   Tom Madden, a Department of Motor Vehicles attorney, said the
agency had not seen the lawsuit and could not comment. Schools
notify the DMV of students who drop out and are also responsible for
deciding hardship cases.
   Wisconsin has a similar law. California passed one, but Gov.
George Deukmejian vetoed it.
   In West Virginia, 353 students lost their license through
December, and about 100 of them returned to class, the DMV said.
   Means' attorney, Chris Butch, said today that the dropout law
contradicts another law that allows students to quit school at 16.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
