<FIRST>r a AM-Hiker     06-08 0302</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Hiker,0310</SECOND>
<HEAD>Hiker Struggles For Survival With Two Broken Legs</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PINE, Colo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A hiker who suffered a fall that left her with
two broken legs and injured wrists crawled on her elbows for two
days and drank water from rain and hail before being rescued.
   Nancy Kruhmin was found Wednesday, bloodied and fatigued, by two
hikers and a Jefferson County sheriff's deputy. She had almost made
her way several miles back to her car through the rugged mountainous
terrain of Pike National Forest.
   ``This is a person who performed her own amazing rescue,'' said
sheriff's spokesman Bob Deutsch.
   Kruhmin, 26, fell 10 to 15 feet from a steep rock ledge during a
day's outing on Monday, Deutsch said.
   ``That incapacitated her from using her arms or legs, so she
hiked back out, crawling inch by inch,'' Deutsch said. ``She toughed
it out ... She endured the pain and kept crawling out on her elbows.
It is just amazing.
   ``To keep herself alive, she caught rain water and hail in her
mouth while lying on her back. The pain was so severe that she
wrapped her legs in her day pack and zipped it around her feet to
try to immobilize her broken bones.''
   Kruhmin was taken to St. Anthony Hospital Central where she
underwent surgery Thursday and was listed in serious condition.
   She was found about a quarter-mile from her car. Authorities are
uncertain just how far she was from her car when she fell, but
believe she had crawled several miles.
   Kruhmin carried some trail snacks and was wearing sweat pants, a
cotton shirt and a light jacket, said David Bailly of the North Fork
Volunteer Fire Department, who assisted with the rescue.
   ``She really impressed us with her instincts for survival and her
personal strength,'' Deutsch said.
</TEXT>
