<FIRST>u w PM-Bush 1stLd-Writethru a0451 06-08 0724</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Bush, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0451,700</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bush Promises New Clean-Air Legislation</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Top 7 grafs embargoed for release at 1:10 p.m. EDT. Picks up
3rd graf pvs, We have urged.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TERENCE HUNT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP White House Correspondent</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush, who is making his debut in
prime-time television tonight with an East Room news conference,
talked with industry leaders today about the environment and
promised new clean-air legislation to ``significantly improve'' the
quality of life in America.
   Bush conferred with industry officials during the morning and
arranged an afternoon session with environmentalists to talk about
proposed changes in the 1970 Clean Air Act.
   At 8 p.m. EDT, he planned to meet with reporters to answer
questions.
   In a speech for Ducks Unlimited, a conservation group, Bush said
that on Monday he will unveil ``the most sweeping changes to the
Clean Air Act since it was last amended 12 years ago.
   ``It will allow us to recover and restore precious forests, lakes
and streams,'' he said. ``And whether Americans live near factories,
in cities or in high woodland country, it will significantly improve
every North American's quality of life.''
   Bush told the industry leaders he was still working on his
proposal. He promised in February to fix a date certain for reducing
smokestack emissions that cause acid rain, which is blamed for
killing waterways and forests, particularly in Northeastern America
and Canada.
   Bush's news conference tonight coincides with the start of the
evacuation from China of all dependents of U.S. government employees
and non-essential personnel.
   ``We have urged all other Americans in China to leave at once,''
White House press secretary Marlin Fitzwater said Wednesday. He said
U.S. Embassy personnel were trying to arrange safe transportation to
the airport from Beijing hotels and other locations.
   Tonight's news conference marks Bush's first question-and-answer
session in the stately, chandeliered East Room of the White House.
He has met with reporters on numerous occasions in the first 4{
months of his presidency, but always during the day and never in the
formal setting of the East Room.
   By scheduling the session in television's prime-time hours, Bush
assures himself of the largest possible audience.
   Fitzwater said Bush has held 16 to 23 news conferences so far,
depending on how you define a news conference. On Monday, for
example, Bush fielded questions for 20 minutes in the White House
briefing room.
   Bush also has held question and answer sessions in Ottawa, Tokyo,
Brussels, Bonn and London. They have ranged in length from a few
minutes to about a half hour.
   Fitzwater said the White House has been looking for an
opportunity for the past two months to have a full-blown East Room
news conference. He said Bush decided to go ahead now, given the
developments in China and his success at the NATO summit in
Brussels, where he defused a crisis over short-range nuclear
missiles and proposed a cutback in Soviet and American combat troops.
   Traditionally, presidential news conferences run for a half hour
but Bush may ignore that, Fitzwater said. He described his boss as
``a president who has trouble confining himself to 30 minutes.''
   Fitzwater said Bush would open with a prepared statement but
likely would not make any announcements, as he did Monday in ending
military sales to China.
   Fitzwater said Bush was not making any special preparations for
the news conference, although his Wednesday afternoon schedule was
largely clear of appointments. The spokesman said Bush would meet
sometime today with his staff to discuss areas of questions.
   In another development, Fitzwater said Bush will visit
Yellowstone National Park and the Grand Tetons in Wyoming on Monday
after proposing legislation to overhaul the Clean Air Act.
   The press spokesman said Bush would stop in Lincoln, Neb., on the
way home Tuesday to deliver a speech on alternative fuels, also part
of the environmental package to be unveiled Monday.
   While at Yellowstone, the president will visit some of the areas
charred from the fires last summer that are now undergoing
revegetation, Fitzwater said.
   He will spend the night in a lodge near Jackson Hole, Wyo., and
speak Tuesday morning at the Teton Science School.
   His clean air proposal, still in the final stages of preparation,
is expected to call for tighter standards for emissions that cause
acid rain and for more strictly controlling auto exhaust emissions.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
