<FIRST>r a AM-LibraryBooking     06-08 0209</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Library Booking,0213</SECOND>
<HEAD>Overdue Book Lands Woman in Jail</HEAD>
<DATELINE>EAST DETROIT, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Wanda Suhr beat a speeding ticket, but
a speed-reading course might have helped her stay out of jail. She
said she was held for 15 minutes because she hadn't paid a $36 fine
to the city library.
   The Sterling Heights woman said she checked out a biography of
Clark Gable last June and returned it in October without paying the
fine. A warrant was issued but nothing happened until Monday, when
she went to court in Roseville to pay a speeding ticket.
   The ticket was dismissed, Suhr said, but then she was arrested on
the library warrant.
   Suhr, 20, said Roseville officers drove her to the border of East
Detroit, where two officers picked her up and drove her to the city
jail. She said she spent 15 minutes alone in a cell, then appeared
before a judge who released her on $100 personal bond.
   ``The judge told me if I pay the $36 and bring him the receipt he
would dismiss the case,'' Suhr said. ``You can believe that I will
pay the late fee before Monday.
   ``I liked the book. ... I like Clark Gable,'' she said. ``But
he's not worth $36.''
</TEXT>
