<DOCNO> AP890608-0095 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-08-89 1309EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u a PM-SchoolSuit 2ndLd-Writethru a0556 06-08 0488</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-School Suit, 2nd Ld - Writethru, a0556,0497</SECOND>
<HEAD>Kentucky Supreme Court Strikes Down School Spending System</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS grafs 5-7 bgng `A frequent ...' with 3 grafs to ADD that
most states use a similar setup; INSERTS one graf after 9th graf pvs, `This
obligation ...' with quote from chief justice; SUBS last two grafs with
one graf to CORRECT that chief justice wrote the majority, sted minority,
opinion.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHARLES WOLFE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>FRANKFORT, Ky. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The state Supreme Court ruled today that
Kentucky's school system is unconstitutional because of the spending
gap between rich and poor districts, and it ordered the Legislature
to develop a new setup.
   The ruling has no immediate effect on the 600,000 students; the
court, ruling 5-1 with a seventh justice partly concurring and
partly dissenting, gave the Legislature until the end of its 1990
session to come up with a system to even out spending.
   ``We do not direct the General Assembly to raise taxes. It is
their decision how best to achieve efficiency,'' the court said.
   However, the court said the Legislature _ in what would be a
major departure _ must make local tax rates uniform.
   The ruling was prompted by a lawsuit filed in 1985 by 66
``property-poor'' districts. They charged that the school-finance
system, which depends on property taxes, is not fair in a state
where wealth varies widely, from the Appalachian coalfields in
eastern Kentucky to the affluent Cincinnati suburbs.
   Most states have similar setups in which state spending on
education is supplemented by revenue raised locally through property
taxes.
   In 1988, a judge agreed with the plaintiffs that the Legislature
had failed to meet its obligation under the Kentucky Constitution to
establish an equitable system of public, or common, schools in
either spending or quality.
   The Supreme Court largely upheld the judge's finding, saying that
Kentucky children, including those who ``by accident of birth and
residence'' live in poor areas, are entitled to the same educational
opportunities.
   ``This obligation cannot be shifted to local counties and local
school districts,'' the court said.
   Chief Justice Robert Stephens, writing for the court, said,
``Lest there be any doubt, the result of our decision is that
Kentucky's entire system of common schools is unconstitutional,''
including its financing regulations.
   The court said the Legislature has a chance to launch an ``era of
educational opportunity which will ensure a strong economic,
cultural and political future.''
   Gov. Wallace Wilkinson lauded the ruling. ``We have the
opportunity to rebuild, to redefine education in Kentucky. And if we
fail, we will have failed ourselves, our fellow Kentuckians and
particularly our children,'' he said.
   Schools Superintendent John Brock said today was ``the happiest
day of my professional life.''
   ``Today the court has propelled us from the 19th century to the
21st,'' he said.
   Justice Charles Leibson, in a dissent, said the ruling was
confusing, over-reaching and destined to spawn worrisome lawsuits.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
