<FILEID>AP-NR-06-08-89 1313EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-China-Scene     06-08 0689</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-China-Scene,0712</SECOND>
<HEAD>City Seems Normal; Students Say It Won't Last</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-China, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KATHY WILHELM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hammers pounded at building sites, table tennis
resumed on campuses and soldiers cleaned up the debris. Beijing was
calm Thursday, almost normal, but students in the pro-democracy
movement say it won't last.
   ``The calm is just superficial,'' said a senior at Beijing Normal
University, whose students helped lead the seven weeks of
demonstrations. ``With so many people killed, there cannot be real
calm. It's just a matter of time before the movement peaks again.''
   The government said nearly 300 people were killed, but Chinese
and foreign diplomats estimate as many as 3,000 died when soldiers
with tanks and automatic weapons rolled into the city on Saturday
and retook Tiananmen Square from the students occupying it.
   Soldiers still fired into the air and at some bystanders
Thursday, but far less often than before.
   Dozens of small restaurants and shops reopened because of the
relative quiet, along with a few post offices. Banks remained closed.
   The Beijing Daily and Beijing Evening News were on sale for the
first time since Saturday and people formed long lines to buy them.
Both were filled with articles denying heavy casualties among
civilians and reporting the reopening of businesses.
   ``There's no news,'' one reader said in disgust.
   Most residents still stayed away from their jobs. Thousands took
bicycle tours of the city, stopping to gape at bullet holes in
buildings and bloodstains on walls.
   Curiosity-seekers clambered over the hulks of tanks burned by
citizens. They crowded around hospital morgues, watching families
carry out bodies.
   People walked boldly up to soldiers ringing Tiananmen Square,
which has been sealed since Sunday. The troopers politely but firmly
refused to answer questions.
   Residents of the area insisted they were not the same soldiers
who stormed the square Saturday night.
   The evening television news Thursday showed soldiers crouching,
using pieces of metal and their hands to clear away ashes and debris.
   Others hauled the wrecks of buses and tanks off Beijing's main
streets, put twisted road dividers back in place and swept the
curbs. A dozen troopers walked west along Changan Avenue, the main
street, trimming tree branches away from telephone lines.
   Whatever the soldiers did, dozens of curious residents watched
and commented.
   ``If we sit around inside, we get too nervous, so we go out to
have a look,'' said a restaurant cook who spent the day cycling
around the city, exchanging stories with other residents.
   Minzu Hotel employees said all their guests had left, but several
said they reported for work ``to protect the property.'' There have
been no reports of looting.
   ``Life is normal when we go home. We cook, eat,'' said a woman
clerk who sat on a pile of wool rugs in a souvenir shop reading a
week-old newspaper.
   ``I spend the day listening to the radio and worrying,'' said a
middle-aged professor strolling near his home.
   Few students still live on Beijing campuses, and said they rarely
venture out of their dormitories. At Beijing Normal, some played
table tennis while others snacked, read or napped.
   The Education Commission ordered Thursday that schools take steps
to resume classes, but the word at Beijing Normal was that too few
students and teachers remained.
   ``We don't know what to do,'' one student said. ``We are waiting
for orders, but our leaders are all gone.''
   Rumors have circulated that some student leaders were killed, but
an activist in hiding told The Associated Press all were alive.
   ``Maybe new leaders will have to emerge,'' another said. ``The
movement hasn't ended. Things may be calm for awhile, but the army
can't stay forever. When it goes, we students will protest again.''
   He and others said they still seek the resignations of senior
leader Deng Xiaoping and other hard liners who ordered the crackdown.
   ``I have no regrets,'' one said. ``No one thought things would
come to this, but it would not have if the local citizens hadn't
supported us. We students have great responsibility, and maybe we
should apologize to the citizens, but they are responsible too.''
</TEXT>
