<DOCNO> AP890608-0098 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-08-89 1317EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-China-Provinces     06-08 0456</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-China-Provinces,0468</SECOND>
<HEAD>Provincial Leaders Ask for Harsh Action in Other Chinese Cities</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-China, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JIM ABRAMS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Provincial leaders recommended harsh action
Thursday against disruption of their cities by demonstrators
protesting the military crackdown on the pro-democracy movement in
Beijing.
   Demonstrations, some violent, have occurred in nearly all major
cities since soldiers stormed Beijing last weekend to drive students
from Tiananmen Square. U.S. intelligence reports estimate 3,000
people were killed.
   ``The present conditions in many enterprises in Lanzhou are
critical and the situation is grim,'' the official radio in the
western city quoted Gansu provincial Gov. Jia Zhijie as saying.
   Jia said ``the dregs of society'' had forcibly occupied ``vital
communications lines and important bridges'' and stopped trains.
Some students went to factories to force workers to strike and
``forcibly order factory directors to halt production,'' he said.
   ``It is necessary to form a deterrent force against them and
develop a situation whereby, when a rat runs across the street,
everybody cries `Kill it!''' the governor declared.
   Government leaders in Shanghai broadcast similar news: ``Vast
numbers of workers are unable to report to work, and industrial
production as well as the citizens lives are being disrupted.''
   Shanghai Mayor Zhu Rongji later said in a half-hour television
broadcast that he could not guarantee the safety of city residents,
but did not explain what he meant.
   He said he had received many requests to call in the army, but
added, ``The municipal party committee, the municipal government and
I myself have never considered the use of the army.''
   About half the work force in Shanghai, China's largest city,
remained off the job after days of protest in which crowds paralyzed
traffic with street barricades, a Chinese source said.
   The government leaders said action should be taken to
``resolutely stop the conspiracy of a few people with ulterior
motives of disrupting transport and throwing Shanghai into chaos.''
   Soldiers were called into Chengdu on Wednesday night after days
of violence, but were gone Thursday, a Chinese source said.
Unconfirmed reports said police shotand killed 20 people crowds
stormed a government building Sunday in Chengdu, capital of Sichuan
province.
   A foreign teacher in Changsha, a southern city, said several
thousand people held a funeral march to the railroad station
Thursday, and on Wednesday students visited factories to tell
workers about the killing of unarmed civilians in Beijing.
   Students also went to the workers in the northeast city of
Shenyang, a foreign source said. Among them was a woman from
Beijing's Qinghua University who saw the military attack on
Tiananmen Square.
   The source reported ``heavy rumors of a military presence'' on
the city's outskirts. She said Liaoning University students held a
large demonstration Thursday.
