<FIRST>r a AM-AirplaneThreat     06-08 0212</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Airplane Threat,0219</SECOND>
<HEAD>Man Handcuffed, Removed From Plane in Groundless Threat</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   One man was handcuffed and all passengers were
removed from a Continental airplane awaiting takeoff from LaGuardia
Airport on Thursday in what turned out to be a groundless threat,
authorities said.
   ``He says it was all a misunderstanding,'' said Allen Morrison, a
spokesman for the Port Authority of New York and New Jersey.
   A 55-year-old man was questioned by authorities, including the
FBI, about the incident aboard Flight 883, a Boeing 727 to New
Orleans and Cancun, Mexico, Morrison said.
   After the man was handcuffed and taken to a police car, all
passengers and their luggage were taken off the plane and the plane
was searched, officials said.
   The handcuffed man had been carrying a large radio-cassette
player, the type often called a boom box.
   ``The stewardess said he said there was a bomb in his boom box he
had carried on board,'' Morrison said.
   ``He claims he said, `They X-rayed it so much, what do they
think, there's a bomb in it?'''
   The man's radio and luggage were X-rayed and no bomb was found,
Morrison said.
   The plane was allowed to take off about 2{ hours late, said Ned
Walker, a Continental spokesman in Houston.
