<FIRST>u a PM-LouisianaTornados 4thLd-Writethru a0573 06-08 0467</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Louisiana Tornados, 4th Ld - Writethru, a0573,0475</SECOND>
<HEAD>Tornadoes Hit Louisiana Towns; At Least Two Killed</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: UPDATES throughout with utility service out, woman rescued,
one found dead in trailer home. No pickup.</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhotos BT1, BT2</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALAN SAYRE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>GROSSE TETE, La. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A tornado wiped out nearly a square mile
of trailers and other buildings here early today, killing at least
two people, and twisters destroyed or damaged nearly 100 homes in
Baton Rouge, authorities said.
   The twisters were part of a storm system that also sent tornadoes
to numerous other towns overnight and knocked out power throughout
southeastern Louisiana.
   No serious injuries were reported 15 miles away in Baton Rouge,
where Fire Chief Ron Spillman said at least four twisters touched
down 19 times, destroying or damaging almost 70 mobile homes and 25
to 30 houses.
   Richard Zuschlag, co-owner of an ambulance service, said his
ambulances took at least two dozen people from the Grosse Tete and
Greensburg areas to the hospital. Two people were killed in the
Grosse Tete area, he said.
   Dan Lennie, an emergency worker in Grosse Tete, said 35 to 50
homes were damaged by the twister, which struck after 6 a.m.,
splintering 75-foot trees and knocking out virtually all
electricity, gas and telephone service in the town of 750.
   ``There's more devastation than I have seen in several years of
emergency work,'' said Lennie. ``Trailers have been devastated, nice
homes completely devastated. Also homes right in the middle of the
path have not been touched.''
   Police sealed off the area to non-residents while rescue workers
using dogs searched wrecked homes for dead or injured, he said. A
chainsaw was used to free a woman trapped in the wreckage of a home,
authorities said.
   Mayor Phillilp Sarullo said the twister struck without warning
and cut a wide swath of destruction. ``I'd say in 5 to 7 seconds it
was over with,'' he said.
   Flo Nereaux, manager of a truck stop where police set up a
command post, said authorities brought two bodies there and were
looking for others.
   ``It wiped out everything in its path. It's torn a body shop up,
torn a lot of trailers up,'' she said.
   ``We have the police out here right now. They're trying to gather
up the bodies. We're trying to get a refrigerated truck to put the
bodies in.''
   One woman apparently died when her trailer flipped over. Her body
was found when a bulldozer righted the home, authorities said.
   In Baton Rouge, Spillman said 400 to 600 people lived in the
destroyed or damaged residences. A shelter was set up at a high
school for those left homeless. At least six injuries were reported
in the Baton Rouge area, none serious.
   Two minor injuries were reported near Amite.
</TEXT>
