<HEAD>Bright &amp; Brief</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WATKINSVILLE, Ga. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Nearly 200 graduating high school
seniors refused to have their outdoor commencement postponed because
of rain. They demanded their diplomas so they could get on with
life, or at least go to the beach.
   All 206 graduating seniors at Oconee High School had signed a
petition requesting that alternate arrangements be made in case rain
threatened the ceremony Tuesday night on the northeast Georgia's
school's football field, said senior Tisha Layne.
   When a thunderstorm rolled in minutes before the ceremony,
Superintendent S.H. Sanders announced the commencement was postponed
for one day, and he left. But as many as 1,000 relatives and 197
students crowded into a gymnasium and chanted for Principal Tony
Dukes to hand out diplomas informally.
   ``Twice I tried to call it off,'' Dukes said, ``and then I
decided to hand out the diplomas.''
   Many of the students were scheduled to leave for Myrtle Beach,
S.C., early Wednesday.
   An official ceremony was held Wednesday night, with only 27
students in attendance.
   School board Chairman Jerry Studdard said Dukes did the right
thing. ``In my opinion, a very volatile situation was diffused,'' he
said.
</TEXT>
