<DOCNO> AP890608-0107 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-08-89 1403EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-CapitalGains     06-08 0771</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Capital Gains,750</SECOND>
<HEAD>Rostenkowski Signals Willingness to Discuss Tax Question with Bush</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JIM LUTHER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Tax Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Rep. Dan Rostenkowski, who traditionally has
viewed the capital-gains tax preference as the ultimate plaything of
the rich, is signaling a change of heart may be on the way _ if the
price is right.
   The price might require President Bush to back away from his
campaign pledge not to raise taxes. Even in that unlikely event,
some members of the House Ways and Means Committee, which
Rostenkowski chairs, said Thursday they would be reluctant to accept
any such bargain, even as part of a deficit-reduction measure.
   For the moment, however, Rostenkowski, D-Ill., is indicating a
willingness to at least discuss the question with Bush, a former
committee colleague.
   ``He doesn't like a lower tax rate for capital gains,'' an aide
to Rostenkowski insisted Thursday. ``But could it ever be
acceptable? The answer is yes _ if the president offered in return
something so attractive to Democrats that they couldn't turn it
down,'' added the aide, who spoke only on condition he not be
identified by name.
   The aide elaborated on Rostenkowski's position after the
chairman, in separate interviews Wednesday with The New York Times
and The Wall Street Journal, suggested some kind of capital-gains
cut could be acceptable as part of a deficit-reduction plan.
   The aide said he is not sure Rostenkowski's position has been
changed all that much. Despite a long record of criticizing the
capital-gains benefit _ ``I'm not about to tell the wage earners in
Chicago that they should pay a higher tax than stockbrokers,'' he
said in February, when Bush called for the change _ Rostenkowski
``never says never,'' the staff member explained.
   The staff of the Joint Committee on Taxation estimates that 80
percent of the tax cut under Bush's capital-gains proposal would go
to those with incomes over $100,000 a year. Those under $50,000
would get 8.6 percent.
   ``That's traditional Republican economics,'' said Rep. Byron
Dorgan, D-N.D., a Ways and Means member, who said he is not sure the
committee is anywhere near a consensus for a capital-gains cut.
   If the chairman has changed his stance, it apparently is because
of the budget deficit.
   The Ways and Means Committee has been directed by Congress to
raise $5.3 billion in extra revenues for the budget year that begins
next Oct. 1. If several expiring tax benefits are to be renewed, the
figure will go higher.
   Bush has proposed his own package of relatively minor revenue
raisers, including higher Social Security taxes on some state and
local government workers and renewal of the expiring tax on
telephone service.
   The president also has called for taxing capital gains _ profits
from the sale of stock and certain property _ at a lower rate than
applies to wages. Unlike most tax cuts, he insists, such a reduction
would raise revenue by encouraging more economic activity.
   A great number of economists don't buy that argument over the
long run, including some who advise Congress. However, Congress'
experts and Bush's experts agree that such a rate cut would raise
more money in the first year simply by encouraging people to unload
some investments they had been holding for a while.
   Rostenkowski has discussed the possibility of cutting the
capital-gains rate for one year, perhaps two. That would be followed
by restoring a higher rate but ``indexing'' capital gains so that in
the future, an investor would not be taxed on profits that were
caused solely by inflation.
   Congressional economists say such a plan would cost the
government revenues after the first year. Bush, presumably, would be
expected to go along with some kind of other tax increase to make up
that loss.
   ``I don't know if I am prepared to make a tradeoff on capital
gains,'' said Rep. Robert Matsui, D-Calif., saying it could cause a
return to the abusive tax shelters that were all but wiped out by
the 1986 tax overhaul. ``And a multiyear reduction would mean we
would be sacrificing future years' revenues for one year of deficit
reduction.''
   Dorgan also said good tax policy must not be sacrificed. ``We
just went through tax reform, where the tax system was so riddled
with loopholes for the rich, and we spent a lot of time correcting
that national disgrace,'' he said.
   Wiping out the special capital-gains benefit and the tax shelters
it fed is often cited as one of the major plusses of the 1986
overhaul. Rostenkowski has said on several occasions that restoring
the capital-gains break would open the door to junking the new law.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890608-0108 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-08-89 1433EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-BigPiSlice     06-08 0376</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Big Pi Slice,0389</SECOND>
<HEAD>Pi Reportedly Calculated to Record 480 Million Decimal Places</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MALCOLM RITTER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Science Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two researchers say they have cut themselves a
record slice of pi: 480 million decimal places of one of the most
famous numbers in mathematics.
   That exceeds the mark of about 201 million decimal places
produced last year in Japan, David Chudnovsky of Columbia University
said Thursday.
   Pi is the ratio of the circumference of a circle to its diameter.
The infinite string of digits begins with 3.14159, and contains no
obvious pattern.
   The newly calculated number would stretch for 600 miles if
printed, Columbia University said.
   Chudnovsky and his brother Gregory, associate research scientists
at Columbia, came up with the number after devising a new algorithm,
which is a series of mathematical steps.
   The algorithm lets researchers calculate more and more decimal
places for pi by simply adding to an existing string, rather than
having to start from scratch, Chudnovsky said.
   It also has a self-correcting feature that can check whether the
pi calculation is on the right track while the calculation is in
progress, he said.
   The researchers checked their calculation by running the
algorithm through two supercomputers with different hardware and
software, Chudnovsky said. When the results were compared,
``everything perfectly fitted together.''
   So what good is knowing this number?
   ``We can use it as a very stringent test for testing the
performance of hardware and software,'' said Chudnovsky, who called
pi calculations ``the ultimate stress test.''
   And by calculating pi out to great lengths, researchers can
investigate whether the string of digits is random or contains some
hidden pattern, he said.
   ``We sort of see more of the tail of the dragon,'' he said.
   The new work is to be presented next week at a conference on
computers and mathematics at the Massachusetts Institute of
Technology.
   Peter Borwein, associate professor of mathematics at Dalhousie
University in Halifax, Nova Scotia, Canada, said the new work
appears to be a record.
   Tackling the digits of pi ``has become something of a benchmark
in computational sophistication,'' he said in a telephone interview.
   ``It seems like since there have been computers, people have been
using them to compute the digits of pi.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890608-0109 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-08-89 1424EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u w PM-Baker-Gorbachev     06-08 0471</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Baker-Gorbachev,470</SECOND>
<HEAD>Baker Calls for Soviet Response on NATO Plan</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SUSANNE M. SCHAFER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Secretary of State James A. Baker III, saying
``the time is ripe,'' called on Soviet President Mikhail Gorbachev
today to respond to President Bush's proposals to slash conventional
military forces in Europe.
   Baker, in remarks to the National Press Club, said the United
States is looking for such a response when the Soviet leader visits
West Germany next week.
   At last week's NATO summit, Bush put forward an elaborate,
four-part plan for reducing East-West troop strength and non-nuclear
forces in Europe.
   ``We urged the Soviets to reduce unilaterally their short-range
nuclear systems to our levels. Next week, General Secretary
Gorbachev can sustain this new spirit by answering our call, by
announcing a real cut in Soviet SNF (Short-Range Nuclear) forces,''
Baker said.
   ``The time is ripe for Mr. Gorbachev to respond positively to the
opportunities presented by NATO's initiatives. Indeed, we look for
him to do so when he travels to the Federal Republic of Germany next
week,'' Baker added.
   The summit meeting of the North Atlantic Treaty Organization had
provided a major lift for Bush, who had been criticized for failing
to respond effectively to Gorbachev's much-publicized arms control
initiatives.
   The session also eased a major controversy between the United
States and West Germany. Bush was able to smooth over the rift
between the allies by agreeing to negotiations on the short-range
nuclear weapons, which are primarily based in Germany and, if used,
would probably explode on German soil.
   Under the compromise, the United States agreed to enter into the
negotiations to achieve a ``partial reduction'' of the weapons once
the implementation of the conventional arms agreement was ``under
way.''
   In the view of U.S. and British officials, that also meant that
the short-range weapons would not be eliminated, and would remain in
the NATO arsenal.
   Under Bush's proposal, the Western alliance would agree to a
ceiling of 275,000 on the number of Soviet and American troops on
foreign soil.
   That would amount to a reduction of some 30,000 U.S. troops and
325,000 Soviet troops.
   Besides his proposals on troop cuts, the president proposed that
the scope of the talks be broadened to include aircraft, a
longstanding Soviet suggestion.
   In speech to the United Nations last Dec. 7, Gorbachev said that
by the end of 1990, the Soviets would withdraw six tank divisions
from the Warsaw Pact nations of East Germany, Hungary and
Czechoslovakia and reduce Soviet troops in Eastern Europe by 50,000.
   The United States and Britain have insisted that NATO retain
short-range nuclear missiles in order to offset the Warsaw Pact's
far larger conventional forces.
   NATO has 88 short-range Lance launchers and their 700
nuclear-tipped missiles in West Germany, while the Warsaw Pact has
1,600 short-range launchers.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
