<FILEID>AP-NR-06-08-89 1430EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u w AM-Bush-Press Bjt   06-08 0656</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bush-Press, Bjt,650</SECOND>
<HEAD>Big Time Access but Small Potato News</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Analysis</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MIKE FEINSILBER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   He shows them movies. He feeds them popcorn. He
takes them on tours of the first family's living quarters. He knows
their first names.
   George Bush's relationship with reporters isn't a honeymoon, it's
a courtship _ or maybe a seduction.
   So far in his presidency, Bush has given reporters what they most
want: access. But he hasn't given them enough of what they want
almost as much: news.
   Before his first big-production, prime-time press conference on
Thursday night, Bush already was meeting often, usually once a week,
with reporters in brief daytime sessions.
   But because his administration hadn't framed its own policies on
most issues and because Bush was cautious in commenting on foreign
affairs, what the president had to say did not tend to generate big
headlines.
   ``For a while you had an awful lot of griping, `Yes, he's a nice
guy, he's given us access, but where are the stories?''' commented
Stephen Hess on Thursday. A senior fellow at the Brookings
Institution, Hess studies the relationship between press and
government and is the author of ``The Washington Reporters.''
   ``There was almost a slight longing for the bad old days under
Ronald Reagan, where he didn't see them much or respect them, but he
gave them lots of stories,'' Hess said.
   That changed with Bush's trip to Europe last month for a summit
with allied leaders and his dramatic proposals for cuts in the
standing armies of East and West.
   As he had promised he eventually would, Bush started making
presidential-size news.
   A Washington hand for three decades, Bush is comfortable with the
press. And, a master of detail, he tends to give more complete
answers than Reagan offered.
   Bush calls reporters who cover the White House by their first
names, has some in for off-the-record sessions, sometimes invites a
few upstairs for a not-yet-released movie and popcorn and soft
drinks.
   Hardly a week passes that he doesn't field their questions. On
Monday, when he called a news conference on 15 minutes notice to
announce sanctions against China, reporter David Hoffman of The
Washington Post arrived late and asked a question that ended,
``Could you explain what the point of doing that is?''
   Chided Bush: ``I already did, David. You missed it.'' Then he
went on to make his point again.
   That kind of relaxed relationship is the mark of an expert, Hess
said.
   ``The really good Washington politicians affect an easy-going
banter, a light humor, and the one who personified it best was
Franklin Roosevelt,'' he said. Such politicians, he said, ``know
that reporters are very easy to flatter.''
   Roosevelt mesmerized the press. He met with reporters in those
pre-television days nearly 1,000 times in his 13 years in office.
   Hess noted that Bush is following almost all the recommendations
of a report last October by the Harvard Commission on Presidential
News Conferences, composed of journalists and professors who spent a
year studying how to revive a 75-year-old institution.
   The commission said that under Reagan the press conference had
fallen into ``a serious state of disrepair.'' Reagan formally met
reporters infrequently. He let 5{ months, during the Iran-Contra
affair, slide by without a news conference.
   The commission's principal proposal: ``frequent, routine and
undramatic'' news conferences.
   The panel said presidents should meet with the media twice a
month, and do it during daylight hours ``to reduce the temperature
and encourage more substantive and useful exchanges.'' It called for
limiting prime-time news conferences to six a year.
   Hess said ``the massive news conference'' generally doesn't
generate much news.
   ``It isn't a very good way to get information out,'' he said.
``It's a way for the people to see a president in action, so it
serves him and it serves the egos of the press corps. But there are
better ways to make news.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890608-0112 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-08-89 1448EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Japan-Press     06-08 0571</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Japan-Press,0592</SECOND>
<HEAD>Japanese Magazine Breaks Precedence with Report on Prime Minister</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The respected magazine Sunday Mainichi broke with
Japanese journalism tradition this week by reporting Prime Minister
Sousuke Uno kept a highly paid geisha as his mistress three years
ago.
   Uno, who took office just a week ago, denied the report, but its
publication broke a long-held code of silence in the Japanese news
media about publishing or broadcasting reports on such liasons by
government officials.
   It is not unusual for Japanese men, especially if they are
wealthy, to keep mistresses, while their wives are expected to
remain faithful.
   Shuntaro Torigoe, the magazine's editor in chief, said he
published the article because he wanted to bring issues of social
ethics into the public arena.
   ``We also want Americans, who are critical of politicians, to
know that in Japan we are changing,'' he added.
   The story generated about 100 telephone calls to the magazine's
office in four days. Some 80 percent of the callers supported the
Mainichi's decision to publish the story, while the rest objected to
the story as a violation of Uno's privacy.
   Sunday Mainichi quoted the woman as saying Uno had paid her
300,000 yen ($2,100) a month over a four-month period in 1985. The
magazine said it did not identify her by name at her request. It
said she was 40 years old. Uno is 66.
   ``He is not a man of noble character,'' the article quoted the
woman as saying. ``I don't want him to use politics the same way he
treated me.''
   Geishas are women highly trained in music, dance and making
conversation. While they are not prostitutes, some develop intimate
relationships with customers who become their patrons.
   While most major newspapers and television networks avoided the
Uno-Geisha story, some of Japan's sensationalist tabloids compared
it to the sex scandal involving Democratic presidential aspirant
Gary Hart in the United States.
   ``If it happened in the United States he would have to go,'' the
Daily Gendai said of Uno.
   Uno was named prime minister June 2 after a long search for a
scandal-free politician to replace the tainted administration of
Noboru Takeshita, who resigned to take responsibility for a massive
Recruit bribery scandal.
   The geisha story is the only blemish so far in Uno's case.
   He denied the liason with the geisha.
   ``It's out of the question,'' Uno told the Tokyo Shimbun.
   Although the magazine is a Sunday publication it has been on
newsstands since Monday.
   Uno has not been asked about the article during question periods
in the Diet, Japan's parliament.
   Kuniko Inoguchi, a professor of political science at Sophia
University, said that in the past 15 years keeping mistresses has
come to be considered against the social ethic.
   ``If you are in a prestigious position in politics or business,
you have to be clean both with money and with sex,'' Ms. Inoguchi
said. ``It's now part of the general code of conduct.''
   But she added that the Recruit scandal, in which a conglomerate
allegedly sought to buy favors from politicians and bureaucrats with
cut-rate stocks and political donations, may have worn the Japanese
down.
   ``Now that the Recruit scandal has come to an end, people might
be a little tired of picking on politicians right now,'' she said.
   Takako Doi, the chairman of the opposition Japan Socialist Party
and the most powerful woman in politics, refused to comment on the
report.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890608-0113 </DOCNO>
