<FIRST>r w AM-Military-Housing     06-08 0464</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Military-Housing,440</SECOND>
<HEAD>Alaska Senator Criticizes Housing Allowance Policy</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DONNA CASSATA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Republican senator lashed out Thursday at the
Pentagon system of providing a housing allowance to military
personnel living outside installations, charging that the current
policy is unfair to residents of economically-depressed areas.
   ``I've never seen worse stupidity in my life,'' Sen. Ted Stevens,
R-Alaska, said at a Senate Appropriations defense subcommittee
hearing on military manpower.
   The object of Stevens' ire was the Variable Housing Allowance, a
stipend that military personnel forced to live off base during a
three-to-four year stint can use to help defray the cost of housing.
   The allowance is based on 80 percent of local housing costs and
changes annually depending on the housing market.
   For military personnel with mortgages or extended leases and
living in the Southwest and Alaska, two areas hardest hit by
problems in the oil industry, the allowance has decreased as housing
prices have dropped.
   Stevens was particularly angered by the Pentagon's recent
decision to distribute $77 million in surplus allowances equally
among all recipients rather than targeting those who have had their
allowance cut.
   ``This is the most unfair system I've ever seen,'' Stevens said.
   Dr. David J. Berteau, deputy assistant secretary of defense for
resource management and support, barely getting a word in, said the
effect of penalizing those in the Southwest and Alaska is ``the
exception rather than the rule.''
   Stevens also criticized the fiscal 1990 budget's proposed level
of $3.609 billion for stationing military personnel and their
dependents overseas, an increase of nearly 10 percent over the
$3.289 billion earmarked for fiscal 1989.
   He argued against upgrading housing facilities overseas at the
same time the Defense Department will be closing bases and troops
may be reduced if the NATO alliance reaches an agreement with the
Warsaw Pact to reduce manpower in Europe.
   What's more, he said, the number of military dependents is
expected to remain constant at about 473,000.
   But Berteau, responding to Stevens statement' that many military
personnel in Japan and West Germany employee servants, said:
   ``Those increases are targeted very specifically at a hugh chunk
of lower enlisted who don't have the kind of money that can support
their dependents in any manner that you described with servants and
maids,''
   Stevens replied:
   ``I think it's unreal to put us in a position of closing down
production lines for new systems ... and building new quarters
overseas.''
   Berteau then told the senator that ``many are in very sad shape''
and argued that better facilities are necessary to maintain high
morale, attract recruits and keep them in the services.
   But Stevens said ``they've been living in these quarters for 10
years and in this very tight budget year you decide to build new
ones.''
</TEXT>
