<FIRST>r a AM-HerculesMurals     06-08 0190</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Hercules Murals,0191</SECOND>
<HEAD>Long-Draped Murals Will Go on Display at State House</HEAD>
<DATELINE>OLYMPIA, Wash. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Murals at the Capitol depicting the
``Twelve Labors of Hercules,'' which so offended legislators that
they were covered with drapes, will be displayed for the summer and
then removed, an official said.
   The murals in the state House of Representatives, which is in
recess, will be uncovered June 16 through Sept. 29 before crews
remove, crate and store the panels, said Ron McQueen, assistant
director of the state Department of General Administration.
   The state paid $100,000 to have the murals created in 1981, but
some lawmakers found them inappropriate for the building or were
offended by the murals' nudity. The artwork represents the 12 tasks
performed by the mythological figure Hercules to obtain immortality.
   The state has spent another $100,000 to cover the murals with
gold drapes and to fight a lawsuit that sought to bar their removal.
King County Superior Court Judge Terrence Carroll ruled in December
that if the murals could be removed without damage, the state was
within its legal rights to take them down and display them elsewhere.
</TEXT>
