<FIRST>r a AM-People-Martin-Lewis     06-08 0291</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-People-Martin-Lewis,0301</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dean and Jerry Reunite on Las Vegas Stage</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto VG1</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT MACY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LAS VEGAS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Dean Martin and Jerry Lewis, America's most
famous duo in the 1940s and 1950s before they split up, had a rare
and poignant reunion on a Las Vegas stage.
   ``Here's to 72 years of joy you've given the world, and why we
broke up, I'll never know,'' Lewis told Martin when he presented him
with a birthday cake Wednesday night.
   ``You surprised me,'' said Martin, who was obviously overwhelmed.
``I love you, and I mean it.''
   The two made entertainment history beginning in 1946, with singer
Martin playing straight man to comic Lewis, but they split in 1956
and have rarely appeared together since then.
   Lewis paid the surprise visit at the end of Martin's performance
at Bally's Hotel and Casino on the Las Vegas Strip. Both Martin and
Lewis perform regularly at the resort, although not together. Martin
appears solo and Lewis appears with Sammy Davis Jr.
   Martin was speechless when Lewis walked onto the stage, wheeling
a giant birthday cake and complaining about the singer's act running
too long.
   The two embraced, traded banter, then hugged again.
   The last time the two appeared together was in 1976, when Frank
Sinatra surprised Lewis by bringing Martin on the nationally
televised Labor Day Muscular Dystrophy telethon that Lewis holds
here annually.
   The reunion brought a standing ovation from a near-capacity crowd
in the Celebrity showroom.
   ``Jerry knew that it was Dean's birthday and wanted to wish him
happy birthday,'' said Joe Stabile, Lewis' long-time manager. ``Dean
knew nothing about it. It's just something Jerry wanted to do.''
   Martin lives in Los Angeles and Lewis lives in Las Vegas.
</TEXT>
