<FIRST>r a AM-HospitalWedding     06-08 0345</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Hospital Wedding,0354</SECOND>
<HEAD>Couple, Delayed 23 Years, Weds in Hospital Room</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   After 23 years, in which he and his wife-to-be
raised eight children and collected 19 grandchildren, George W.
Amerson finally got married. But it wasn't easy.
   The couple, stymied in 1966 by a now defunct Georgia law
prohibiting interracial marriages, were almost delayed again, this
time by health problems. But the wedding went on Wednesday, although
the setting was not quite what Amerson and his bride and longtime
companion, Shirley, had planned.
   The vows were spoken at Amerson's bedside in the coronary
intensive care unit at Grady Memorial Hospital, where Amerson had
been admitted Tuesday night after complaining of chest pains.
   A half-dozen hospital staffers looked on as Amerson and his
bride, both 48, tied the knot in a brief ceremony, standing before a
minister beside the bed.
   The bride, dressed in a pink and white print dress and white
jacket, glided into the room on the arm of registered nurse Rochelle
G. Hersch, who arranged the ceremony and also served as witness.
   The bride carried a bouquet of pink and white carnations; the
groom, who suffered a heart attack two years ago, wore pajamas and
was attached to a heart monitor.
   The Amersons had planned to be married at their home in southeast
Atlanta on Wednesday, their 23rd anniversary together.
   The Amersons met in 1965 and began living together a year later.
They would have wed then, he said, but Georgia law prohibited
interracial marriages until 1979. So they decided to change her name
legally, and she took his.
   ``We had always wanted a marriage license,'' Amerson said. ``So
this anniversary I planned to give her a license. I decided to make
her legal,'' he chuckled, winking at his bride as they sat on his
hospital bed. ``I decided to make an honest woman out of her.''
   ``And I decided to make an honest man out of you,'' she replied.
   ``We wanted it to come through on this day,'' Amerson said. ``The
Grady employees made our wish come true.''
</TEXT>
