<FIRST>r a PM-AnimalResearch     06-08 0154</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Animal Research,0158</SECOND>
<HEAD>University City Moves To Tighten Up on Animal Research</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CAMBRIDGE, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The City Council has endorsed the idea of
appointing a commissioner to oversee all experiments on animals and
make unannounced laboratory inspections.
   The council Monday also agreed that all animal experiments here
should be required to meet federal standards for care and testing of
animals. Currently, only those institutions getting federal funds
are subject to the standards.
   The proposals were drawn up by a panel consisting of a
veterinarian, a lawyer and a Harvard professor. City Manager Robert
W. Healy said the city solicitor has been asked to draft an
ordinance and a vote could come early next week.
   The animal-rights measure would affect Harvard and the
Massachusetts Institute of Technology along with 11 other businesses
and institutions.
   Most of the institutions, including Harvard and MIT, already are
subject to federal standards for humane care and experimentation.
