<FIRST>r w AM-VOA-China     06-08 0525</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-VOA-China,480</SECOND>
<HEAD>VOA Beaming TV Signal to Chinese Military Bases</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRYAN BRUMLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   In response to the Chinese crisis, the U.S.
government's Voice of America is beaming television signals to the
People's Republic, the first time it has ever taken such a step, the
director said Thursday.
   The signal is going directly to about 2,000 satellite dishes
operated largely by the People's Liberation Army, although there is
no way to tell whether the transmission is being watched by the
military or passed along other channels, said VOA director Richard
Carlson.
   The U.S. Embassy is receiving the signal ``loud and clear'' on a
satellite dish in Beijing, he said. The transmission began Tuesday.
   The broadcast of news to the military is significant because of
reports that units backing the pro-democracy demonstrators may have
exchanged fire with units supporting the crackdown.
   ``We are sending a television signal that is available to every
major military installation in China,'' Carlson told The Associated
Press in a telephone interview. The signal originates in the United
States and bounces off satellites over the Indian and Pacific
Oceans, covering all of China.
   ``It makes available to the Chinese military information about
what is going on in China, information that may not otherwise be
available to the Chinese military,'' he said.
   Television and radio sets are not built to receive direct
satellite signals. The transmissions must be received by satellite
dishes and re-broadcast in a signal accessible to individual
receivers, said Carlson.
   The VOA, which broadcasts radio programs in many languages around
the world, including transmissions targeted at communist nations,
has never used a television signal before, said Carlson.
   ``It seemed like the right thing to do,'' said Carlson, who made
the decision and informed a special State Department task force
monitoring events in China. ``The State Deparment is aware of it. No
one has objected.''
   The VOA normally beams eight hours of radio broadcasts daily in
Mandarin to China, but increased that to 11 hours in response to the
student demonstrations in Beijing.
   ``Chinese authorities have said that we have a regular listening
audience of 60 million. We believe that we are over 100 million now.
We are clearly the most pervasive non-Chinese source of news in the
country,'' said Carlson.
   VOA's television image shows a broadcaster reading the news, as
the Chinese-language script scrolls across the lower part of the
screen. VOA has not attempted to broadcast television images of the
demonstrations or the aftermath.
   During the unrest, said Carlson, Chinese authorities have tried
to jam VOA Chinese radio broadcasts. They have not tried to jam
VOA's English language broadcasts.
   VOA maintains a bureau with two correspondents in Beijing, and
uses other Western news services, which have been reporting a
different story than the official Chinese media.
   ``The Chinese media have been very dishonest about the student
demonstrations and the role of the military,'' said Carlson.
   ``Chinese media have said there were 300 dead, and that they were
mostly soldiers, which is not true. The Red Cross says 3,000 people
died,'' he said. Some Western sources in Beijing have estimated the
dead at 7,000.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890608-0124 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-08-89 1539EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u w AM-ToxicChemicals Bjt   06-08 0735</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Toxic Chemicals, Bjt,730</SECOND>
<HEAD>Disputed List Says Indistrial Plants Pose Cancer Risk</HEAD>
<BYLINE>Bly LARRY MARGASAK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A House panel chairman Thursday distributed
federal data identifying 205 industrial plants as increasing cancer
risks through release of airborne toxic chemicals. The Environmental
Protection Agency quickly disputed his interpretations.
   An EPA spokesman said the information was old and incomplete, and
complained it was ``highly irresponsible'' to use it as ``reflective
of risks in the real world.''
   However, Rep. Henry A. Waxman, chairman of the House Energy and
Commerce environment subcommittee, said that even potentially
inaccurate figures should be released because they ``indicate the
enormity of the problem'' and represent a ``stunning demonstration
of the urgency of the public health threat.''
   Waxman, D-Calif., said at a news conference that toxic chemicals
present a cancer risk near the plants at least a thousand-fold
greater than levels accepted by experts.
   The plants on the list, compiled by the EPA, pose at least a
1-in-1,000 cancer risk to people getting maximum exposure for a
lifetime, while the EPA deems a risk of more than 1-in-a-million as
unacceptable.
   ``It's public information,'' Rep. Guy V. Molinari, R-N.Y., told
the news conference in defending release of the data. ``The public
has a right to know,'' added Rep. Mickey Leland, D-Texas.
   Leland, Molinari, Waxman and Rep. Jerry Sikorski, D-Minn.,
combined release of the figures with an announcement that they have
introduced legislation to control airborne toxic chemical releases.
   The bill would limit emissions from industrial sources and motor
vehicles, attempt to prevent accidental releases, protect the Great
Lakes, which have been seriously damaged by airborne toxic
chemicals, and control emissions from small businesses. Waxman plans
to incorporate the legislation into a comprehensive clean air bill
that also would address urban pollution and acid rain.
   The Bush administration is expected to introduce its own clean
air proposals next week, including what EPA spokesman David Cohen
described as a ``strong air toxics component.''
   Cohen said the data on the individual facilities were complied to
develop computer models to compare health risks from one plant to
another.
   ``The figures ... were never used to reflect risks in the real
world,'' Cohen said, and ``any suggestion those data are reflective
of risks in the real world is an entirely erroneous interpretation
... a highly irresponsible interpretation.''
   The Chemical Manufacturers Association said, ``To imply that
these estimates depict the real risks of living near one of the
plants is not just exaggeration but an outright misuse of data to
deliberately alarm people.''
   The estimates assume a 70-year lifetime exposure to a chemical at
its maximum exposure level at a plant.
   The figures indicated that 205 facilities posed cancer risks for
the most exposed individuals that may exceed 1 in 1,000. Forty-five
of these facilities had maximum individual risks of greater than 1
in 100, and one had at least a 1-in-10 risk.
   The estimates represent evaluations of the maximum individual
cancer risk that might arise from the inhalation of a single toxic
air pollutant from an individual facility.
   For example, a risk estimate of 1 in 1,000 means that one person
out of 1,000 could be expected to contract cancer from maximum
exposure to a single pollutant.
   Waxman said that because of the potential inaccuracy of the data,
he didn't know whether the problems at individual plants should be
considered worse than the figures showed or, on the other hand,
``not serious.'' But he said there is a real possibility the problem
is worse than indicated because the data were limited.
   For instance, the information only measures cancer risks, but not
other potential hazards such as birth defects, nervous system damage
or respiratory disease.
   The figures also do not reflect the combined cancer risk of
different air toxics that might be released by a single plant.
   Also, only the cancer risk from direct inhalation of air toxics
is evaluated, although numerous studies indicate the potential
contamination of crops in nearby areas, or accumulation of toxics in
the food chain, can exceed the risk from breathing the chemicals.
   In addition, the EPA did not evaluate some toxics, including
benzene and coke oven emissions.
   The EPA said the worst plant on the list was the Texaco butadiene
plant in Port Neches, Texas, with at least a 1-in-10 risk of cancer.
   Texaco labeled the estimate ``totally unsupported by any
technical and scientific facts or by employee health records.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
