<FIRST>u i AM-US-PLO     06-08 0484</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-US-PLO,0503</SECOND>
<HEAD>U.S., PLO Delegates Split Over Peace Proposals</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL GOLDSMITH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TUNIS, Tunisia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The United States opened a new round of
talks with the PLO Thursday by urging it to support an Israeli
proposal for elections in the occupied lands, but the two sides
remained sharply at odds.
   For its part, Israel said the U.S-PLO talks were hindering the
peace process.
   After 4{ hours of private discussions in Tunis, negotiators for
Washington and the Palestine Liberation Organization expressed
satisfaction with progress. The head of the PLO delegation, Yasser
Abd-Rabbou, said more talks will be held ``in the near future.''
   However, a senior American official, speaking on condition of
anonymity, said, ``It was more of the same from the PLO.''
   Both Abd-Rabbou and the chief U.S. delegate, Robert Pelletreau
Jr., read statements after their meeting Thursday. They contained no
major shifts in position, however.
   ``The major focus of our dialogue today was the concept of
elections in the occupied territories to launch a political
negotiating process to deal with both transitional arrangements and
final status,'' said Pelletreau, who also serves as U.S. ambassador
to Tunisia.
   He stressed the U.S. government's view that the Israeli proposal
for elections in the occupied territories were ``constructive and
workable, deserving of a positive Palestinian response.''
   The plan calls for the 1.7 million Palestinians in the
Israeli-occupied territories to elect representatives to negotiate
with Israel for autonomy. Later talks would determine the final
status of the West Bank and Gaza Strip, but Israel has said an
independent Palestinian state is out of the question.
   The PLO, which has declared a Palestinian state, has rejected the
Israeli plan for elections. It says the Israelis must first withdraw
from the occupied territories and agree to an international observer
force.
   In his statement Thursday, Abd-Rabbou said the PLO delegation
urged the Bush administration to take ``clear and decisive measures
to stop the terrorist'' measures taken by Israel in the occupied
territories.
   ``These measures lead to more and more deaths, destruction and
deterioration of the condition in which the population has to
live,'' he said.
   More than 500 Palestinians have been killed in the 18-month-old
uprising against Israeli rule, most in clashes with Israeli
soldiers. Twenty-two Israelis also have died.
   Abd-Rabbou also called for an international conference on
bringing peace to the region.
   In his reaction to the talks Thursday, Israel Foreign Minister
Moshe Arens said the PLO is the obstacle to free elections.
   ``So contacts with them make things more difficult. They don't
help,'' he told Israel radio.
   ``Talking with them, which gives them a feeling of legitimacy and
recognition, only makes the peace process more difficult,'' Arens
said.
   Israel views the PLO as a terrorist group.
   The United States agreed to talk directly to the PLO last
December after PLO chief Yasser Arafat said his group was renouncing
terrorism. Thursday's discussions were the third round.
</TEXT>
