<FIRST>r a AM-UnlicensedDropout     06-08 0545</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Unlicensed Dropout,0559</SECOND>
<HEAD>Teen Loses Driver's License for Legally Dropping Out of School</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID WILKISON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHARLESTON, W.Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A lawyer for a teen-ager who had his
driver's license revoked for dropping out of school says the state's
anti-truancy law clashes with other state statutes, making the new
law unconstitutional.
   ``He dropped out of high school legally because there's a statute
that says when you're 16, you can drop out,'' attorney Chris Butch
said. ``The (new) law is in direct conflict of that. The one law
doesn't jibe with the other.''
   Under an education reform law passed by the West Virginia
Legislature last summer, students under age 18 who miss more than 10
consecutive days of school or have 15 unexcused absences must give
up their driving privileges.
   Proponents of the law, which is aimed at curbing truancy in a
state where the dropout rate hovers around 17 percent, point to
Department of Motor Vehicle figures that show 100 of the 353
students who lost their license through December returned to school.
   Michael Means, a 17-year-old ninth-grade dropout, took his case
to Kanawha County Circuit Court on Wednesday, marking the first time
the statute has been challenged in court. He filed a lawsuit against
DMV Commissioner George Sidiropolis and the agency, seeking to
declare the law unconstitutional.
   A trial was set for June 21.
   Means, whose 16-year-old wife, Tonya, is pregnant, says he can't
get a job without driving, and therefore, can't provide for his
family.
   ``What I'm try to accomplish with the lawsuit is to get his
license back so he can function as an adult,'' Butch said.
   Tom Madden, a Department of Motor Vehicles attorney, said the
agency had not seen the lawsuit and could not comment.
   Means dropped out of Roosevelt Junior High School in Charleston a
year ago. In October, Means misplaced his license and requested a
new one. The DMV wouldn't agree without the consent of the Kanawha
County Board of Education, which refused. On May 30, the license was
revoked.
   A hardship clause exists in the law that allows county board of
educations to make some exceptions. However, school officials have
said that Means could have worked and still completed his education.
   ``I think the law is ignorant,'' said Michael's father, William.
``It shouldn't have had to go this far. Hopefully, it will get his
license back and get the law declared unconstitutional.''
   Butch added that under a 1973 state attorney general's opinion,
if a person is married and under the age of 18, the state considers
that person to be freed from parental control.
   ``That has been the law in this state for a long period of
time,'' he said. ``It was for the kids who weren't too good in
school and who went to work on farms or in the mines.''
   However, Del. Pat Murphy, D-Berkeley, who introduced the
legislation in 1988, said his law is designed to keep kids in school
and help those who have to work get their educations.
   ``What I do not want to see is the bill turned into a law that
encourages young people to go out and get married so they can quit
school and fall into the category of an emancipated youth,'' Murphy
said.
</TEXT>
