<FIRST>r w AM-ChildMentalHealth     06-08 0359</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Child Mental Health,350</SECOND>
<HEAD>Mrs. Gore Urges More Be Done on Mental Health</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BARTON REPPERT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Much more needs to be done to develop
community-based services for the growing number of children with
mental health problems, Tipper Gore said Thursday.
   Mrs. Gore, wife of Sen. Albert Gore Jr., D-Tenn., said that ``at
a time when we have a great deal of education, talent, skills,
research ... we have a service delivery system that emphasizes
hospitalization. In fact, some kids are sent out of state to be
hospitalized, because there's a lack of community-based mental
health services.''
   ``The goal ought to be to keep the child in the family, in the
home, in the community, if possible,'' she said. ``So we need a
commitment to funding for community-based mental health services
that are child-centered.''
   She was interviewed during a Capitol Hill conference by the
National Mental Health Association and the Child Mental Health
Interest Group, an organization that involves the wives of several
members of Congress and is chaired by Mrs. Gore.
   An Institute of Medicine study reported Wednesday that mental
disorder among children is a problem costing society billions of
dollars and depriving the nation of productive citizens.
   The report gave a conservative estimate of 12 percent of
America's children being mentally disturbed, but it added that the
true number could be as high as 22 percent, or about 14 million.
   At the conference, Dr. Joseph Coyle, director of child psychiatry
at the Johns Hopkins School of Medicine and a member of the
committee that carried out the Institute of Medicine study, said it
was not ``presumptuous'' to recommend substantial increases for
funding of research into mental disorders of children at a time of
budget deficits and government program-tightening.
   Sen. Gore called the situation with child mental health ``a
problem that urgently needs attention.'' He said that in coping with
it, ``inevitably there's this tremendous inertia that society has to
get over with.''
   Mrs. Gore said that state government agencies across the country
need to take a more active role in coordinating the services and
funds available for assisting mentally disturbed children.
</TEXT>
