<FILEID>AP-NR-06-08-89 1626EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-AirShowCrash     06-08 0632</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Air Show Crash,0650</SECOND>
<HEAD>Soviet Fighter Jet Crashes After Dramatic Air Display</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SYDNEY RUBIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Soviet MiG-29 fighter crashed during an aerobatic
performance Thursday on the opening day of the Paris Air Show, and
the pilot was injured after bailing out of the jet.
   The aircraft was making its final pass over Le Bourget airfield
north of Paris after a dramatic demonstration flight when a part of
the aircraft appeared to break away.
   Pieces of the needle-nosed jet burst into flames while the
fuselage, in one piece, dropped like a stone in the center of the
airfield without injuring any of the thousands of exhibitors,
visitors and jouralists on hand for opening day.
   A water tanker and fire engines rushed to the scene to douse the
flames of the burning fuselage.
   The pilot, 37-year-old Anatoly Kvochur, was airlifted by
helicopter to hospital near the airstrip, then transferred to Begin
Military Hospital in a suburb east of the city. The Soviet Embassy
in Paris said he was in ``fairly good health.''
   Claude Martin, flight director of the show, said Kvochur's
parachute ``barely opened, but even so it broke the fall of the
pilot.''
   Air show spokesman Patrick Guerin said the pilot suffered serious
injuries, including injury to his stomach, but was conscious and
talked during the airlift to the military hospital.
   The Soviet news agency Tass carried a report on the incident and
videotape was shown on Soviet TV Thursday night.
   Alexander Batkov, Soviet department chief for the Ministry of
Aviation Industry, said in Paris that Kvochur is ``one of our best
pilots.''
   No immediate cause was given for the crash. Batkov said it was
only the second MiG-29 ever to crash.
   ``Specialists must analyze the situation,'' Batkov said. ``When
we see the film we'll know what happened. It is too early to ask
questions yet.''
   Guerin said the plane seemed to have ``a mechanical problem with
the left engine.'' He said the afterburner of the left engine failed
to fire during a low-speed turn at about 1,000 feet.
   One industry official said the pilot appeared to be pushing the
plane to its limits before the crash.
   John W. Wood Jr., president of Thermedics Inc. of Woburn, Mass.,
said the plane was making a ``very high performance routine,''
including vertical climbs straight up, solely on engine power
without relying on wing lift.
   John Klinghut, manager of operations for the U.S.A. National
Pavilion, who witnessed the crash, said the pilot ``apparently lost
an engine.''
   ``He was about 500 feet in the air. There was a big burst of
flames and a lot of smoke,'' Klinghut said.
   The accident occurred about two hours after President Francois
Mitterrand inaugurated the world's most prestigious aviation show,
which opens to the public on Friday.
   On display are a large number of Soviet aircraft, including the
new space shuttle Buran.
   The MiG-29, a twin-engine combat aircraft, has been used since
1985 and represents a clear effort by the Soviet Union to close the
technology gap with the West. Batkov said it was first displayed
last year at Britain's Farnborough air show, where it also was
piloted by Kvochur.
   The worst recent accident at the Paris Air Show was in 1973, when
a Soviet supersonic Tupolev 144 exploded in flight, killing the
six-man crew and seven people in the nearby village of
Goussainville, where it hit the ground.
   The last previous accident at the show, held every two years, was
in 1977 when an American single-seat twin-engine A-10 passed too low
while making a loop and hit the ground.
   On Aug. 28, 1988, 70 people died after three Italian Air Force
stunt jets collided at a Ramstein Air Base air show in West Germany.
One plane plowed into spectators at the event.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890608-0129 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-08-89 1649EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-Suriname-Crash     06-08 0458</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Suriname-Crash,0476</SECOND>
<HEAD>Pilot Error Seen As Likely Cause of Suriname Air Disaster</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Surinam is cq for name of airline</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ANTHONY CAPLAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PARAMARIBO, Suriname (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Pilot error appears the most likely
cause of the crash of a Surinamese jetliner that struck a tree and
tore to pieces trying to land in thick fog, a government spokesman
said Thursday.
   He said three Americans flying the plane, who all died in
Wednesday's crash, gave no radio warning of any problem before the
Surinam Airways jet went down near this capital's international
airport.
   The government-run Suriname News Agency said the death toll was
expected to reach 177. There were 11 known survivors who were
initially taken to a city hospital, but their condition was unclear.
   The airline gave no figure Thursday for the number of people
already known to be dead, saying families must first be notified.
   Rescue workers were searching Thursday for six bodies still in
the wreckage.
   Six investigators from the U.S. National Transportation Safety
Board arrived in Paramaribo at the request of the Surinamese
government to help investigate why the DC-8 crashed. It was leased
from an unidentified U.S. company to Surinam Airways.
   The cause of the accident was uncertain. However, government
spokesman Kenneth Schoon said: ``We think it was pilot error, but we
won't know for sure until the flight recorder is examined.''
   Commercial aircraft carry cockpit recorders that record in-flight
conversations and a flight data recorder that registers altitude,
wind speed and other data.
   The crash was the worst air disaster in the history of the former
Dutch colony on the northern coast of South America. The plane was
flying from the Netherlands.
   Schoon said the three Americans in the cockpit did not report an
emergency but circled the runway twice before asking the control
tower for more light on the runway.
   ``That was the last we heard of them,'' Schoon said.
   The airline identified the Americans as Capt. Will Rogers,
co-pilot Glyn Tobias and engineer Warren Rose. Their hometowns were
unavailable.
   Motilal Atta Mungra, the airline's director, said the company had
virtually ruled out technical problems because the 20-year-old plane
had a maintenance check just two weeks ago.
   He said the plane caught fire after hitting a tree and breaking
into pieces. Its mid-section landed upside-down, and debris was
strewn over 150 yards.
   Mungra said there were 188 people aboard.
   About 60 bodies of identified victims were being flown Thursday,
along with three badly burned survivors, to Amsterdam, Schoon said.
Other bodies were stored for identification in a temporary morgue at
the airport.
   The dead included three high-ranking Surinamese military officers
and three Dutch soccer players of Surinamese origin.
   Most passengers were people from Suriname living in the
Netherlands.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
