<FIRST>r w AM-Senate-State     06-08 0673</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Senate-State,650</SECOND>
<HEAD>Panel Sends State Department Authorization Bill to Senate</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LAWRENCE L. KNUTSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Senate Foreign Relations Committee,
permitted to act by the settlement of a partisan dispute within its
ranks, sent a $2.5 billion State Department authorization bill to
the Senate on Thursday but left some arguments over spending
priorities unresolved.
   The panel also recommended the Senate confirm four pending
diplomatic nominations, including that of former Sen. Chic Hecht,
R-Nev., to become ambassador to the Bahamas.
   The committee had been hamstrung by a Republican boycott of its
business meetings, reflecting GOP anger over a Democratic-led probe
into the past activities of Donald Gregg, named by President Bush to
be ambassador to South Korea.
   The Gregg controversy temporarily set aside, the committee faced
problems involving spending choices that must be made.
   Under a budget deal reached by the Bush administration and
Congress, combined foreign affairs spending for State Department
funding and foreign aid was set at $19 billion.
   But the administration requested total spending of nearly $19.8
billion.
   The crunch came when Sen. Jesse Helms, R-N.C., sought to fund
$192 million for new and powerful Voice of America transmitters in
Israel by stripping money from accounts set aside to pay past and
present U.S. dues to United Nations organizations.
   Chairman Claiborne Pell, D-R.I., contended it is important the
United States meet its U.N. obligations, especially when funds are
needed for vital international peacekeeping operations.
   Refusing to pay would brand the United States as ``an
international deadbeat,'' Pell said.
   But Helms said it was ``vastly more important to build these
transmitters than to ship a whole hat full of money up to that crowd
at the United Nations.''
   Other panel members contended spending for the transmitter
project could be slowed because the Soviet Union has stopped
electronic jamming of Voice of America broadcasts, jamming that the
new transmitters were designed to overcome.
   In the end, the panel decided not to decide, at least for the
moment.
   By voice vote, it approved full funding for the transmitters.
   Then it voted not to take the money out of U.S. dues to the
United Nations.
   It then sent the bill to the Senate floor for further action at a
funding level $792 million above the budget ceiling.
   ``We will have to wrestle this to the ground further down the
road,'' said Sen. Richard Lugar, R-Ind.
   He and other senators expressed hope the administration will set
priorities and make choices needed to get foreign affairs spending
into balance.
   The panel also voted to recommend the Senate approve Bush's
nominations of:
   _Bernard Aronson to be assistant secretary of State for Latin
American Affairs.
   _John Kelly to be assistant secretary for Middle Eastern and
South Asian Affairs.
   _John Negroponte to be ambassador to Mexico.
   _Hecht to be ambassador to the Bahamas.
   Sen. Mitch McConnell, R-Ky., said he organized the GOP boycott
because he feared a campaign of ``delays and leaks'' was being
mounted to prevent any action on the Gregg nomination.
   A committee investigation into Gregg's background was spurred by
Sen. Alan Cranston, D-Calif. Cranston said that Gregg _ while
national security adviser to then-Vice President Bush _ may have
helped in an illegal effort to resupply the Nicaraguan Contra rebels
with weapons and ammunition.
   McConnell and Cranston resolved the impasse on Wednesday after
administration officials promised to supply documents Cranston had
requested.
   Cranston will hold a second day of under-oath testimony on June
15. A guaranteed committee vote on Gregg now is set for June 20.
   Cranston told reporters he is satisfied with the result and
satisfied that the administration has made a ``good-faith
commitment'' to deliver the requested documents as promised.
   ``We're going to vote on the 20th,'' he said. ``If people aren't
satisfied with what we receive, they can vote `present' or `no.'''
   Cranston said he remains skeptical about Gregg's denials that he
had no involvement in Oliver L. North's attempts to resupply the
Contras.
   ``Up to this point I've found Mr. Gregg's version hard to
accept,'' Cranston said.
</TEXT>
