<FIRST>u i AM-Lebanon     06-08 0612</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Lebanon,0636</SECOND>
<HEAD>Syrians, Christian Resume Battle</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MOHAMMED SALAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Syrian gunners shelled the Christian
enclave north of Beirut on Thursday as three Arab foreign ministers
opened talks in Syria to try to end three months of fighting in
Lebanon.
   Police said two civilians were wounded during the sporadic
daylong hostilities.
   Syrian gunners, deployed in Moslem west Beirut, fired more than
100 howitzer shells in an apparent effort to prevent Christian army
commander Gen. Michel Aoun from receiving arms supplies by sea,
police said.
   A police spokesman, who cannot be named under standing rules,
said the shells exploded around the Christian ports of Jounieh and
Byblos.
   Aoun's gunners, entrenched in the 310-square-mile enclave,
unleashed a howitzer barrage at sundown aimed at Syrian gun
positions in west Beirut's seaside district, police reported.
   ``It's a limited retaliation aimed at the sources of Syrian
fire,'' said a communique from Aoun's headquarters.
   The police spokesman said gun battles broke out at nightfall
between Syrian and Christian units across Beirut's dividing Green
Line in the battle-scarred old commercial district straddling the
port.
   The latest round of fighting in Lebanon's 14-year civil war began
on March 8. Since then, 363 people have been killed and 1,432
wounded.
   In the Syrian capital, President Hafez Assad met with foreign
ministers Abdel Latif al-Filali of Morocco, Bouallam Bsayeh of
Algeria and Prince Saud al-Faisal of Saudi Arabia, who delivered a
message from their leaders on Lebanon. Syria has long considered
Lebanon within its sphere of influence.
   Al-Filali said in a statement:``We hope to find soon a final
solution to the Lebanese problem.''
   The three nations were chosen at an Arab summit conference in
Casablanca, Morocco, to come up with a peace plan within six months
to end the civil war.
   The foreign ministers are to travel later to Baghdad for talks
with Iraqi officials on the confrontation between Aoun's 20,000
troops and Syria's 40,000 soldiers.
   President Saddam Hussein of Iraq, Syria's main Arab foe, had
declared support for Aoun's ``war of liberation'' against the
Syrians.
   The current round of fighting began after Aoun ordered a blockade
of illegal ports run by Syrian-backed militias south of Beirut
because they deprive the state treasury of about $100 million in
customs dues annually.
   Syrian troops and allied militiamen of Druse warlord Walid
Jumblatt's Progressive Socialist Party retaliated by blockading the
Christian enclave, where about 1 million people live.
   The Arab League called a cease-fire on May 26 but it has not been
honored.
   Aoun on Wednesday called the confrontation ``a war for
sovereignty, nothing more, nothing less.''
   His remarks at a military graduation ceremony were published by
the independent daily newspaper An-Nahar.
   Aoun also called for the withdrawal of Israeli forces that
control, along with allied militias, a six- to 10-mile buffer zone
in southern Lebanon to prevent guerrilla attacks on northern Israeli
settlements.
   Syria troops are stationed across 70 percent of Lebanon under a
1976 Arab League peace-keeping mandate.
   Aoun and other Christian leaders accuse the Syrians of failing in
their mandate by siding with Moslems against Christians in the civil
war.
   The leftist daily newspaper As-Safir said Syrian vice president
Abdul Halim Khaddam Wednesday dismissed Aoun as ``not a man of
dialogue. ... He does not have a clear-cut political horizon.''
   It said Khaddam made the remarks in Damascus to a delegation from
Lebanon's Syrian-controlled northern province of Akkar.
   Khaddam said Syrian troops were ``prepared to remain in Lebanon
for another 14 years if need be to achieve justice.''
   He was referring to political reforms demanded by Syrian-backed
Moslem leaders who have been fighting fellow Christians since 1975
to achieve equality in running Lebanon's affairs.
</TEXT>
