<FIRST>r i AM-Japan-Vietnam     06-08 0399</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Japan-Vietnam,0415</SECOND>
<HEAD>Reports: Monk Says He Saw Up to Six U.S. POWs in Vietnam</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Japanese Buddhist monk recovering from 14 years of
imprisonment in Vietnam said he may have seen U.S. prisoners of war
at a re-education camp, according to news reports Thursday.
   Ganshin Yoshida, 65, told Japanese reporters there were ``five or
six'' prisoners of war who spoke English at the camp where he was
held for the last seven years. Vietnamese political prisoners called
them Americans, he said.
   An official of the Vietnamese Embassy in Tokyo called Yoshida's
remarks groundless.
   ``Our government has repeatedly discussed that issue in the past.
There are no more American POWs'' in Vietnam, the official told The
Associated Press on condition of anonymity.
   Kyodo News Service quoted Yoshida as saying he did not know what
the living conditions of the purported POWs were like because they
lived in a separate building. But he said they had been treated
horribly and had been tortured, Kyodo reported.
   The location of the camp was not disclosed.
   Yoshida said the prisoners were put to work in construction
projects, the news agency said.
   Hospitalized for ailments resulting from his confinement, Yoshida
has been too ill to talk until now, 4{ months after his return to
Japan, Nippon Televison said. He is hospitalized in Sapporo on
Hokkaido, Japan's northernmost island.
   Yoshida's daughter, Keiko Takatsuka, informed the U.S. Embassy of
her father's comments on Wednesday, Kyodo reported.
   An embassy official, who spoke on condition of anonymity,
confirmed the meeting took place but refused to elaborate.
   The AP was unable to contact Mrs. Takatsuka despite repeated
attempts.
   Yoshida, formerly a city councilman in Hokkaido, became a monk in
1966 and emigrated to Vietnam, where he set up a temple in Saigon,
now called Ho Chi Minh City.
   Yoshida was granted citizenship in 1973 by the former South
Vietnamese government. When communist forces took over in 1975,
however, he was arrested and detained without trial in re-education
camps and jails.
   Vietnam released Yoshida on Jan. 20 for humanitarian reasons
following appeals by Yoshida and international human rights groups
such as Amnesty International.
   A total of 1,730 Americans are still listed as missing in action
in Vietnam; 634 others are missing in Cambodia, Laos and China,
according to U.S. figures.
   The Indochina war ended in 1975 with communist victories over
U.S.-supported governments in Vietnam, Cambodia and Laos.
</TEXT>
