<FILEID>AP-NR-06-08-89 1710EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-Soviet-Politics     06-08 0714</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Soviet-Politics,0735</SECOND>
<HEAD>First Walkout Stuns Soviet Congress</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ANDREW KATELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   About two dozen Baltic parliamentarians angry about
central control of their republics stormed out of the Congress
Thursday in a dramatic demonstration that lawmakers are no longer
cogs in the Kremlin machinery.
   ``Comrades! Comrades! I ask you to be calm because this is not
all so simple,'' an exasperated President Mikhail S. Gorbachev cried
as the deputies left the Kremlin's Palace of Congresses.
   It was the first walkout of the raucous Congress of People's
Deputies session that began May 25 and is scheduled to end Friday,
and it underscored the increasingly unpredictable nature of Kremlin
politics.
   It also reflected the heated opposition by some deputies to the
Communist Party establishment that runs the session and nominates
committee members and other officials.
   In other tough talk Thursday, a radical economist said the
country should cut aid to the Kremlin's Latin American allies and
pay farmers foreign currency to help avert economic collapse.
Another deputy said the country was on the brink of ecological
disaster.
   Soviet television, which broadcast the session live to millions,
showed about 25 deputies storming out.
   The Baltic legislators made the dramatic move after objecting to
formation of a committee by the 2,250-member Congress that will
decide whether laws conform to the Soviet Constitution. They said
the committee could encroach on their republics' right to
self-determination and ability to veto laws passed by the central
government.
   ``Our electors ordered us to take care of the sovereignty of our
republics,'' said Romas V. Gudaitis, a writer and deputy from
Lithuania. ``We consider the elections of the Constitutional
Inspection Committee to be without purpose and we will not take part
in them.''
   Gudaitis called the committee a remnant of the ``Stalin empire''
and part of Moscow's attempts to ``control and oppress national
problems by an iron glove.''
   Lithuanian deputies, among the most vocal at the parliamentary
session, led the walkout, the Tass news agency reported. Tass said
representatives of the two other Baltic republics, Estonia and
Latvia, also objected to the committee. But it was not immediately
clear if they joined the Lithuanian walkout.
   The Congress voted overwhelmingly to form the committee on
Thursday, but 433 deputies were against and 61 abstained, including
Lithuania's delegation. Gorbachev said he would consult with the
deputies who objected and that the Congress would vote on the
committee membership Friday morning.
   The Baltic representatives contend the Soviet takeover of their
nations in 1940 went against the people's will and believe
Moscow-based ministries have ruined their environment and economy.
Many Baltic residents are demanding autonomy from Moscow in all but
defense and security.
   In a direct clash with the Kremlin, the legislatures of Estonia
and Lithuania have proclaimed the right to veto laws approved by the
central government in Moscow.
   Later Thursday, Gorbachev told reporters to leave the hall and
asked that TV cameras be turned off. The Congress then went into its
first closed session, its topic undisclosed.
   Alexei Yastrebov, a deputy from the Ural Mountains area of
Russia, said in a telephone interview the closed session involved
discussion of violence in Uzbekistan.
   At least 71 people have been killed in a five-day rampage
involving ethnic Uzbeks and the Meskhi Turk minority in the southern
Soviet republic. More than 9,000 Interior Ministry troops have been
sent in and a curfew was imposed.
   Yastrebov said the deputies were asked whether they believe
``more decisive measures'' are needed to end the unrest but that a
decision was postponed until Friday. He said he could not spell out
what other measures the deputies could approve.
   In earlier debate, economist Nikolai Shmelev said Premier Nikolai
I. Ryzhkov's call on Wednesday for extensive defense cuts and
government relief for almost 40 million Soviets living in poverty
will fall far short of solving the country's woes.
   Shmelev said Soviet farmers should be motivated to work harder by
offering them pay in foreign currency with which they could buy
hard-to-get goods.
   Shmelev also called for a cut in aid to Latin America. Quoting
U.S. estimates that the Soviet Union spends between $6 and $8
billion on activities there, especially in aid to Cuba, he said ``no
one understands what a significant portion of that money is spent
on.''
</TEXT>
