<FIRST>r w AM-BRF--AirliftRecord     06-08 0140</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-BRF--Airlift Record,120</SECOND>
<HEAD>Plane Sets World Record with Airdrop of 190,346 Pounds</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An Air Force C-5 cargo plane set a world
airdrop record by delivering four armed vehicles and 73 soldiers to
the ground by parachute, the service said Thursday.
   The drop on Wednesday during the international Airlift Rodeo 89
competition at Pope Air Force Base, N.C., involved four Sheridan
armed reconnaissance vehicles _ each weighing 42,000 pounds _ and 73
fully armed paratroopers.
   In all, the C-5 Galaxy was credited with an airdrop record of
190,346 pounds.
   ``Put in perspective, this would have taken five C-130s or C-141s
to drop the same men and equipment,'' said Col. John Fox, commander
of the Air Force Airlift Center.
   The C-5 was flown by a crew from the 436th Military Airlift Wing
at Dover Air Force Base, Del.
