<FIRST>r i AM-China-USAmbassador 1stLd-Writethru   06-08 0474</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-China-US Ambassador, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0639,0488</SECOND>
<HEAD>Ambassador Promises to Get Americans Out</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDS: SUBS 4th graf, `Chinese soldiers...' to ADD that government
says 300 died.</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-China, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TERRIL JONES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.S. Ambassador James Lilley promised Thursday his
embassy will get all Americans who want to leave out of the Chinese
capital.
   ``Starting from June 3, we were running very high risks staying
here,'' he told a news conference at the airport. ``We've been
planning since June 3 to move people out.''
   ``We will be able to handle the Americans leaving,'' Lilly said.
``One way or another we can do it, I can assure you.''
   Chinese soldiers were ordered into Beijing's central Tiananmen
Square on Saturday to crush a student-led movement for increased
democracy and an end to corruption. The government says nearly 300
people were killed, but Chinese and foreign diplomats say up to
3,000 died. Soldiers roamed the streets for days, shooting at random.
   Some Americans have complained that the U.S. mission was
unresponsive to the need for evacuation.
   ``They were not very helpful,'' said Stephanie Tom of Sausalito,
Calif., a student at Beijing Teacher's College who called the
embassy for a ride to the airport. ``They were very disorganized.
Those people are so exasperatingly noncommittal.''
   She eventually got a ride in a van sent by the West German
Embassy.
   ``I asked the embassy to come and get me, but they wouldn't,''
said Terese James of Liberty City, Texas, who was teaching at
Beijing Forestry University.
   ``They said I'd have to get to the airport myself,'' Miss James
said after she arrived in Tokyo on Wednesday.
   ``We've helped thousands and hundreds of Americans to get out of
here, we've been out to the universities again and again to bring
them in,'' Lilley said.
   ``They went through barricades, we got machine-gunned in our
apartments yesterday, it's a very dicey situation,'' he said.
   He said there were contingency plans to evacuate people from
China through Shanghai or Canton if escape via Beijing proved
impossible.
   ``We're not comfortable,'' Lilley said. ``Security is not a
finite thing. We've taken an awful lot of moves to improve our
security, and the biggest one was putting those people on that plane
and pulling them out of town.''
   Lilley said that, ``With the troops in town, with the shooting
going on, with your apartments being raked, surrounded, it's just
not a wise thing to keep people here at this point.''
   Chinese soldiers sprayed a diplomatic residential compound with
bullets Wednesday.
   Lilley noted that Thursday was relatively quiet compared to the
previous four days, but said, ``We aren't hearing shots, but can you
tell me we won't hear them tonight?
   Can you tell me this thing won't get unstuck tomorrow?''
   He said he was relieved that no Americans had been killed in the
violence.
</TEXT>
