<FILEID>AP-NR-06-08-89 2020EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-IndianInvestigation     06-08 0462</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Indian Investigation,450</SECOND>
<HEAD>Senate Panel Asks Lujan for Action to Help Indians</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DIANE DUSTON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Members of a special Senate investigating
committee told Interior Secretary Manuel Lujan on Thursday to take
aggressive action at his department to improve what they said were
deficient programs for Indians.
   Lujan said he would.
   Sen. Thomas Daschle, D-S.D., said he was worried that
shortcomings discovered by the special unit of the Senate Select
Committee on Indian Affairs would go uncorrected.
   Daschle told Lujan, whose department oversees nearly all federal
programs for Indians, ``Someone has to do something ... shake them
up. Someone has to say it is no longer going to be like it was.''
   The special committee, chaired by Sen. Dennis DeConcini, D-Ariz.,
has asked President Bush to appoint a staff member at the White
House whose only responsiblity would be to make sure federal
responsibilities to American Indians are met.
   Lujan objected to that, saying the responsibility belonged to the
Interior Department and he saw no need for an outside coordinator.
   DeConcini responded by saying it might be easier to get action if
someone at the White House were helping.
   During investigative work covering most of a year and weeks of
hearings spanning six months, the committee has uncovered what
members consider gross mismanagement in numerous federal agencies
dealing with Indian interests.
   As an example, DeConcini reminded Lujan that in just a few
months, investigators working for the committee exposed millions of
dollars in thefts of Indian oil which the federal Bureau of Land
Management was supposed to be protecting.
   He asked Lujan what he would do about it?
   ``We'll do what Sen. Daschle suggested. We'll do some kicking
around,'' Lujan said.
   The committee hearings, which began in January, also have
revealed evidence of:
   _Corruption in contracting for federal projects on Indian
reservations.
   _Child abuse in Bureau of Indian Affairs schools.
   _Organized crime involvement in legal Indian gambling operations.
   _Poor management at the Indian Health Service.
   _Failure by the government to protect land granted Indians by
treaty from encroachment by non-Indians.
   _Federal projects for non-Indians that have depleted resources
such as water on reservations.
   _Corruption among some tribal leaders.
   DeConcini said the committee will have a report on its findings
by September or October.
   ``I have concluded that the secretary of interior and the
Interior Department are not meeting the trust responsibility,'' he
said. He praised Lujan for being sensitive to the problem.
   ``But you need to translate it into action,'' he said.
   ``The report we are going to issue is not going to be extremely
complimentary. It is going to single out areas where the trust
responsibility was not met.''
   Lujan said the department was already starting to make changes
based on findings of the committee.
</TEXT>
