<FIRST>u i AM-Iran 1stLd-Writethru   06-08 0785</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Iran, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0647,0808</SECOND>
<BYLINE>Parliament Speaker Scoffs at Reports of Political Turmoil ^EDS:
SUBS 22nd graf, `He also...' with 2 grafs to UPDATE with Baker statement.
Pick up 23rd, ``The United...' ^By ALEX EFTY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TEHRAN, Iran (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Parliament speaker Hashemi Rafsanjani on
Thursday denied reports of a power struggle after the death of
Ayatollah Ruhollah Khomeini.
   Rafsanjani also said the post-Khomeini regime in Iran will not
help free Western hostages held in Lebanon unless the United States
releases frozen Iranian assets and helps locate four missing
Iranians.
   Rafsanjani also signaled his intention of playing a bigger
political role, telling foreign reporters during a news conference
that he wants more executive power for the presidency.
   Rafsanjani, 55, is the only candidate running in the Aug. 18
presidential election.
   He is considered a moderate who seeks to end the country's
international isolation and boost private enterprise in opposition
to radical hardliners who favor a self-reliant fundamentalist Iran.
   Rafsanjani, who is also acting commander in chief of the armed
forces, dismissed reports that Iran was plunged into turmoil by
Khomeini's death as ``nothing but shooting in the dark by people who
know nothing about the internal situation in our country.''
   Rafsanjani stressed that President Ali Khamenei's appointment to
succeed Khomeini as supreme leader was permanent.
   Khomeini, 86, died Saturday of a heart attack, 11 days after
undergoing surgery for internal bleeding.
   Khamenei, 49, was named his successor on Sunday amid speculation
he would serve as a caretaker leader until constitutional reforms
ordered by Khomeini are approved in a referendum to be held
simultaneously with the presidential election.
   Khamenei, considered a moderate and a Rafsanjani ally, has served
as Iran's head of state since 1981. He is barred by the constitution
from running for a third four-year term.
   Rafsanjani said the constitutional reforms will reinforce the new
president's executive power at the expense of the prime minister.
   That will prevent rival power centers from stalling the
decision-making process, which has often happened in the past.
   Rafsanjani claimed that Western countries and not Iran were
responsible for the country's isolation, saying ``the West should
give up its former spirit that Iran is a satellite belonging to
them.''
   He said the country will remain faithful to Khomeini's policy of
``neither East nor West,'' but added that relations with the Soviet
Union had improved and that he plans to visit Moscow shortly.
   The Soviet Union was Iraq's main arms supplier during the 8-year
war with Iran which ended with a U.N.-sponsored cease-fire in August.
   ``If the Westerners change their policy and treat us as the
Soviet Union did, they will see the same position on our part,''
Rafsanjani said, speaking Farsi through an interpreter.
   But he charged that ``the United States and Western Europe follow
hostile policies toward Iran ...The United States practically
entered the war against us.''
   Asked about an appeal by President Bush for help in freeing
American hostages in Lebanon, he said the United States must use its
influence on the right-wing Christian Lebanese Forces militia
believed to have kidnapped four Iranian government employees.
   ``Then you can expect us to do what we can for the release of the
other hostages, although we have no responsibility in Lebanon.''
   There are 15 Western hostages in Lebanon, including nine
Americans, who are believed held by pro-Iranian Shiite Moslem
extremists.
   The four Iranians, last seen at a Lebanese Forces checkpoint
north of Beirut in 1982, are believed to be dead.
   In Washington, Secretary of State James A. Baker III said the
United States provided Iran with information on Iranians held by
Christian forces in Lebanon in 1982. He reiterated the U.S. position
that Iran should help bring about the immediate and safe release of
the American hostages in Lebanon.
   Rafsanjani also said Iran could not help on the hostage issue
while Iranian assets are frozen in the United States.
   ``The United States has acted like a pirate ... If the Iranian
assets are released as a sign of goodwill, we in return will do
whatever we can,'' he added.
   The United States broke relations with Iran, froze billions of
dollars in Iranian assets in American banks and impounded military
equipment ordered by deposed Shah Mohammad Reza Pahlavi after
radicals seized the U.S. Embassy and held 52 Americans hostage in
1979.
   Commenting on the break in relations with Britain over the novel
``The Satanic Verses,'' by British novelist Salman Rushdie,
Rafsanjani said the issue had been ``created by the West.''
   ``You allowed the book to be published despite warnings,'' he
said.
   Rafsanjani said Khomeini's Feb. 14 religious ruling condemning
Rushdie to death for blaspheming Islam in the book was decreed by
Islamic law and could not be evaded.
</TEXT>
