<FIRST>r a AM-MaraudingMink     06-08 0186</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Marauding Mink,0190</SECOND>
<HEAD>Wild Mink Kills Illegally Imported Rare Bird</HEAD>
<DATELINE>EVANSVILLE, Ind. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A black palm cockatoo, a bird on the
endangered species list, was killed by a wild mink at a zoo where it
was taken after being seized in an illegal bird shipment from Asia.
   The bird, worth $10,000, was one of three sent to Mesker Park Zoo
before a transfer to other zoos in about three weeks.
   The cockatoos, which were not in good health, were sent to Mesker
because Zoo Director Ron Young is regional coordinator of the Palm
Cockatoo Consortium, a group that monitors and establishes breeding
programs at zoos.
   Only 3,000 pairs of the birds are left in the wild, Young said.
   Young said the bird was killed Sunday by a mink that entered the
bird's cage through a narrow slit.
   ``We've seen the minks, and besides when you've been working
around a zoo as long as us here, you know by how something's been
killed what did it,'' Young said. ``The mink, they kill for the fun
of killing. They are devious creatures. They're a killing machine.''
</TEXT>
