<DOCNO> AP890608-0146 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-08-89 1751EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-China-Evacuations 1stLd-Writethru   06-08 0759</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-China-Evacuations, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0637,0780</SECOND>
<HEAD>Planeloads of Foreigners Flee China</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS grafs 9-10 ``So many...shoot again'' with 7 grafs to ADD
phone lines jammed with calls to China by worried Chinese, other quotes,
background. Pickup 11th graf `Jean Ashbey...'</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-China Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ELAINE KURTENBACH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Foreigners fleeing China left lovers and friends
behind and came home with dark experiences instead of fond memories.
   Evacuees arrived in Asia, Europe and the United States on
Thursday with tales of children shot down by soldiers and of
acquaintances slain in the army assault on pro-democracy
demonstrators in Beijing.
   Joanne Smith, 20, of Leeds University in England, said students
strapped the bullet-riddled body of a 9-year-old boy to a truck and
paraded it through Beijing to illustrate the horror.
   ``From the moment I saw that, I realized just how inhuman the
army had been and what they had done,'' she said. ``I will never
forget the sight of that little boy as long as I live.''
   In Tokyo, U.S. Embassy and airline personnel arranged for medical
care, connecting flights and hotel rooms for hundreds arriving on
evacuation flights chartered by the State Department.
   The tearful Chinese wife of a U.S. diplomat, who did not give her
name, said: ``It was dreadful. `We were talking with the student
leaders in the square, and two days later they were dead.''
   ``I had to leave my Chinese fiance behind, I hope she'll be all
right,'' said Ted Pritikin, 20, a Chinese-language student from Los
Angeles.
   He said they parted at the Beijing train station Saturday night,
then the violence began and he was caught up in the rush to leave
China.
   Worried friends and family tried desperately to get through to
China by phone. Zhifeng Shao, a 37-year-old scholar in Chicago, said
he spent hours trying to call his relatives who live minutes from
Tienanmen Square, where troops beat and shot demonstrators over the
weekend to end a three-week sit-in.
   He says he has nightmares that his mother would be killed.
   ``I have trouble sleeping these days,'' he said in an interview
Wednesday. ``I wake up every few hours.''
   American Telephone &amp; Telegraph Co. reported demand has been
``tremendous'' on a limited number of circuits between the two
countries.
   ``So many children were killed,'' said Terese James, 24, of
Liberty City, Texas, who arrived with her Chinese husband, Wu Wei.
   ``Students came back to the university with wounds all over,''
she said. ``Soldiers were shooting to kill. If they heard someone
cry out, they'd shoot again.''
   Isabel Marcus, a law professor who returned home to Buffalo,
N.Y., said she still has vivid images of ``frail, terrified,
peaceful, idealistic young people who were going to be killed for
nothing. ... I just keep seeing the numb terror on their faces.''
   Jean Ashbey of Surrey, England, said she was in Beijing to study
Chinese painting at Beijing's Central Academy of Fine Art.
   ``We saw students running out (of Tiananmen Square) injured, with
blood pouring down,'' she said. ``We saw smoke and heard gunfire.
There were volleys of machine gun fire all the time and helicopters
were constantly in and out of the square.
   ``We heard stories of old women being killed, men, women and
children and of students, begging not to be shot, who were simply
mowed down.''
   Mrs. Ashbey and her husband, Roy, arrived in London via Hong Kong.
   Roy Ashbey said: ``I am sickened and angry by what has happened.
We had grown to really like the Chinese people, who were happy and
friendly. The atmosphere before the carnage was wonderful. Now I am
terribly worried for the people there. I just can't understand how
the soldiers could do what they did.''
   Serena Carden, 20, of East Sussex, England, said an American
friend was near Tiananmen Square, ``walking along with his back to
the square and they just opened fire. Someone beside him was hit and
fell down at his side. He just ran.''
   Lucy Rapaport, a British tour operator, said in Tokyo the danger
in Beijing was brought home by a Chinese government announcement
that the safety of foreigners could not be guaranteed.
   She described the situation in Beijing's antiquated airport,
already disorganized by renovations, as ``chaotic, with people
sleeping on the floor and lining up at check-in counters.''
   Donna Anderson, an American journalist, said: ``Anyone going into
Beijing now must be crazy. No one's sure who's in charge. It's
dangerous.'' She left the Chinese capital Wednesday and was flying
from Tokyo to the United States on Thursday.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
