<FIRST>u w AM-Lucas     06-08 0607</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Lucas,580</SECOND>
<HEAD>Senate Committee Said to Request Large Number of Documents</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CAROLYN SKORNECK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Senate committee reviewing the
controversial nomination of William Lucas to head the Justice
Department's civil rights division has asked him to provide some
200,000 pages of documents, a Justice Department spokesman said
Thursday.
   A committee source denied that that many documents were requested.
   The spokesman, David Runkel, declined to criticize the Senate
Judiciary Committee for last week's demand by its staff, saying only
that the amount of paperwork requested was ``unusual.''
   ``It seems to me it would take years for the Senate staff to
review all this material,'' he said.
   However, a committee source said, ``We have not asked for
something broad, but for something pretty narrow ... but apparently
the way the records are kept, they're in a much broader category.''
   The source, who spoke on condition of anonymity said some
documents ``may involve privacy matters and we don't even want to
look at the stuff, much less sort through it.''
   Attorney General Dick Thornburgh questioned Judiciary Committee
Chairman Joseph R. Biden Jr., D-Del., about the request Wednesday
night when Thornburgh spoke to the Delaware State Bar Association.
   ``He said something like, `They're asking for a lot of stuff,'''
Runkel said.
   Thornburgh urged Biden to schedule Lucas' confirmation hearings
as soon as possible, and the senator said he hoped they could be
held before the July 4 holiday.
   The committee source declined to reveal what kinds of documents
the committee is seeking ``because we don't to be unfair to the
nominee by raising unfair implications about what we're looking at.''
   But Runkel said the committee wanted such things as employment
records and court documents ``on cases that may have been filed in
which he, as a public official, may have been a defendant.''
   Lucas, who is working for the Justice Department as a $284-a-day
consultant while awaiting Senate confirmation, seems ``somewhat
amazed by the request'' for the documents, Runkel said.
   The nominee did not respond to phone calls seeking comment.
   Lucas, who had been in private legal practice in Detroit for two
years before being nominated for the assistant attorney general's
post by President Bush in April, had served as sheriff and chief
executive of Wayne County, Mich., which includes Detroit.
   A black Republican who ran unsuccessfully for Michigan governor
in 1986, Lucas had been a lifelong Democrat before joining the GOP
in 1985.
   Lucas' nomination is opposed by some civil rights groups on the
grounds he lacks legal experience, particularly in civil rights. On
his Senate questionnaire, Lucas said he has never tried a case in
court since he entered private legal practice in Detroit two years
ago.
   In one notable case, Lucas was found legally responsible for
injuries suffered by a prisoner who was beaten while in the custody
of Wayne County sheriffs' deputies.
   The 1976 beating of Salvatore Marchese by an unidentified person
who was admitted to his locked holding cell was the subject of a
strongly worded 1985 ruling by the 6th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals.
   The court cited Lucas' ``failure to provide a trained and
disciplined county law enforcement agency'' or to investigate the
beating incident.
   Lucas had testified that he did not know about the incident and
therefore would not have been able to investigate it.
   But the appellate court said he remained legally liable and that
his failure to order and direct an investigation and to punish those
responsible ``served to confirm the existence of an unstated
`policy' of toleration of illegal brutality toward any county
prisoner who had threatened the life of a sheriff's deputy.''
</TEXT>
