<FILEID>AP-NR-06-08-89 2040EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-NATO     06-08 0607</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-NATO,0630</SECOND>
<HEAD>NATO Commander Questions Timetable for East-West Arms Deal</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT J. WIELAARD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An aide to U.S. Defense Secretary Dick
Cheney said Thursday the one-year timeframe President Bush set for
an East-West accord on cutting conventional forces and arms in
Europe was more a goal than a deadline.
   West German Gen. Wolfgang Altenburg, head of NATO's panel of
allied commanders, had questioned the timetable as Cheney and his
colleagues held their spring meeting at NATO headquarters.
   ``It's a real challenge,'' Altenburg told reporters. ``It's
optimistic, indeed! Unrealistic? I don't know. ... If we make it in
12 months, I do not know.''
   At a NATO summit in Brussels last week, the allies agreed to a
proposal advanced by Bush on specific cuts in troops and combat
aircraft. His new plan came in response to a flurry of recent arms
control initiatives by Soviet President Mikhail S. Gorbachev.
   Bush wants accord reached within six to 12 months at East-West
talks in Vienna to cut U.S. and Soviet troops in Europe to 275,000
each and cut about 750 combat planes from NATO forces and 3,000 from
the seven-nation Warsaw Pact.
   The president said that if Washington withdraws 30,000 troops
from Europe and Moscow withdraws 325,000, each side then would have
275,000 troops remaining.
   Cheney discussed the timetable with the defense ministers. A
Cheney aide, briefing reporters, agreed it was ``ambitious'' to
expect a conventional arms accord within a year.
   But, said the official, who spoke on condition of anonymity:
``The United States put it up as a goal, not a deadline.''
   He said success at the Vienna talks hinged on Soviet willingness
to reach an accord. ``It's up to the Soviets, now.''
   The aide pointed to an improved East-West disarmament climate and
said, ``We are moving already much faster than before.''
   The ministers will end their two-day meeting Friday by
reaffirming the goal for all North Atlantic Treaty Organization
nations to increase annual defense budgets by 3 percent after
inflation.
   The Cheney aide said that although most members _ including the
United States _ will not achieve that goal this year, the defense
chiefs agreed it would be unwise to drop 3 percent as an objective.
   This week, NATO officials held their first talks on how to
implement Bush's aircraft proposal: how and where to cut 750 combat
aircraft from NATO air forces and which aircraft should be scrapped.
   East and West are already negotiating cuts in such armaments as
tanks and artillery throughout Europe at the Vienna talks that began
this year.
   Bush added troops and combat aircraft in response to a flurry of
recent arms control initiatives by Soviet President Mikhail S.
Gorbachev.
   Officials said the NATO panel considering aircraft cuts will meet
weekly until September to beat what Altenburg termed the ``very
severe time factor'' Bush put on his proposals.
   ``For instance, how is this to be broken down among the different
nations? We have to consider the role each nation has.''
   U.S. officials said there was ``general agreement'' among the
ministers not to reduce British and French planes that can carry
conventional or nuclear bombs.
   Also excluded, they said, must be the 72 U.S. Air Force F-16 jets
NATO will be moving from Torrejon Air Base near Madrid to a base in
southern Italy.
   The move follows Spain's decision to end a basing accord with the
United States.
   The ministers reviewed on Thursday their efforts to maintain an
equitable sharing of NATO's defense costs _ an issue that has
generated criticism in the U.S. Congress that many NATO allies do
not pull their weight in NATO.
</TEXT>
