<FIRST>u w AM-Bush-CleanAir 2ndLd-Writethru a0628 06-08 0884</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bush-Clean Air, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0628,810</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bush Indicates He Plans Hard-Line Approach on Air Standards</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: INSERTS one graf after 12th graf pvs, These standards, with
comment from Senate Democratic Leader Mitchell; picks up 13th graf, Speaking
to</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Bush, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TOM RAUM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush indicated Thursday he plans a
hard-line approach on new clean-air standards that will
``significantly improve'' the quality of life of all North Americans.
   Bush, who will unveil his clean-air package Monday, met with
industry leaders who said they pleaded against coming up with
standards too tough to be affordable.
   ``We urged him to make certain that, when the dust settles on
clean air, that we have a healthy economy left,'' said William D.
Fay, administrator of the Clean Air Working Group, a business
coalition.
   ``We'll have to wait until Monday to see whether or not the point
got through,'' Fay said after he and other industry officials met
with Bush at the White House.
   Later, at a session with environmental leaders, Bush indicated he
was ready to move ahead with strong measures, participants said.
   ``He said that he agreed this is a freight train coming down the
track,'' said George Frampton, president of the Wilderness Society.
``He felt that he strongly personally wanted to be out front on
this.''
   Ruth Caplan, executive director of Environmental Action, said
``We are calling on him to again do a NATO. It is time for him to
exercise leadership and call for strong measures to protect the
health of the American people.'' She was referring to Bush's
dramatic call last month for unilateral troop cuts in Europe.
   She said Bush was given information on air quality in
Kennebunkport, Maine, where he has a vacation home. ``He was shocked
to know that last summer, there were many days in which there were
serious health problems from ozone smog,'' she said.
   White House aides, as well as participants at both the industry
and environmental meetings, insisted Bush has not made up his mind
on many aspects of the package, the first major overhaul of the 1970
Clean Air Act in 12 years.
   Administration aides, speaking on the condition of anonymity,
said, however, that Bush had already decided on many key parts of
the legislation _ including tough new standards for cleaning up
smokestack emissions that cause acid rain, changes that would prove
costly to industry.
   The president has also decided on rigid new standards to prevent
chemical contamination of the air.
   These standards will be far-reaching, extending to hundreds of
categories of businesses, ranging from paint factories to bakeries,
the sources said.
   Such suggestions prompted praise from congressional Democrats
even before Bush submitted his proposal. ``He has wholly reversed
the position of the Reagan administration on this subject,'' said
Senate Majority Leader George Mitchell of Maine.
   Speaking to a hunters' conservation group, Bush reinforced the
contention that his proposals would prove costly to industry and be
wide-ranging.
   ``For too long, we've focused on cleanup and penalties after the
damage is already done. It's time to reorient ourselves using
technologies and processes that reduce or prevent pollution _ to
stop it before it starts. In the 1990s, pollution prevention will go
right to the sources,'' Bush said.
   Power plants and other industries that burn coal in the Midwest,
many of which disperse their pollutants through tall smokestacks
without technological controls, will be a key target of Bush's
clean-air attack, the sources said.
   These emissions have been cited as a major cause in the acid-rain
pollution that afflicts lakes and wildlife in Canada and the
Northeastern United States.
   In his remarks to Ducks Unlimited, a conservation group of
waterfowl hunters that seeks to protect and preserve wetlands, Bush
declared: ``I will unveil the most sweeping changes to the Clean Air
Act since it was last amended 12 years ago.''
   ``It will allow us to recover and restore precious forests, lakes
and streams. And whether Americans live near factories, in cities,
or in high woodland country, it will significantly improve every
North American's quality of life.''
   Roger B. Smith, chairman of General Motors, said the industry
leaders who met with Bush ``asked the president for a flexible
solution that would be cost effective. And he said he hadn't made up
his mind on a lot of factors yet.''
   ``He didn't make any commitments on anything. We need to have a
bill that's on an economically sound basis,'' he said.
   Smith voiced some skepticism toward one feature that Bush has
said will be in the legislation _ a program to encourage alternate
motor fuels such as alcohol blends.
   ``We need more studies on alternate fuels,'' Smith said. He said
that car engines that can accept alcohol blends use greater volumes
of fuel than gasoline-only engines _ suggesting either larger fuel
tanks in vehicles or the building of more service stations.
   Richard Lesher, president of the U.S. Chamber of Commerce, said
Bush left little doubt that he will submit a tough bill.
   ``We hope this bill will reflect flexibility,'' he said. ``It
will be a strong bill. But this is a starting point rather than an
ending point.''
   Lesher said that much would happen to the bill when it gets to
Congress, where rival clean-air measures are already advancing
through both chambers.
</TEXT>
