<FILEID>AP-NR-06-08-89 2045EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-MilitaryRecruiting     06-08 0494</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Military Recruiting,480</SECOND>
<HEAD>Studies Say Services Can Save Money If They Rely on Ads</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By NORMAN BLACK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Military Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The armed forces can save money if they rely on
advertising to obtain recruits instead of more recruiters or cash
bonuses, according to studies released Thursday.
   And at least in the case of the Army, they said the advertising
should be placed in national magazines and local newspapers first,
with television the next priority and local radio last.
   The report on military advertising was issued by the Rand Corp.,
a Pentagon-supported think tank based in Santa Monica, Calif. It was
asked to study the issue by the Defense Department's manpower office.
   Rand issued two studies, one focusing on Army advertising efforts
and the other assessing whether the services should do their own ads
or whether ``joint'' ads with the other armed forces work as well.
   The studies, focusing on military advertising campaigns from 1981
to 1984, were done by researchers James N. Dertouzos and J. Michael
Polich.
   The research dealing with the Army found advertising does make a
difference in an era of the all-volunteer military and cuts in the
ad budget will hurt.
   ``The empirical results show that, in general, advertising
expenditures in a given month have a significant and immediate
effect on the number of high-quality enlistments in the Army,'' the
study said.
   ``We estimated the marginal cost of recruiting a high-quality
person through increased advertising to be between $5,000 and
$6,000. The marginal cost of achieving the same goal by increasing
the recruiting staff was about $5,700, and the cost of using cash
bonuses was much higher, about $16,000 per recruit.''
   There also appear to be significant differences among the media
in their cost effectiveness, at least for the Army, the study
continued.
   ``National magazine and local newspaper advertising are the most
cost effective in promoting short-run enlistment responses, costing
$2,000 and $3,400 per additional recruit. National broadcasting
purchases also have strong effects but ... appear to cost somewhat
more than the print media, $7,000 to $10,000 per marginal recruit.
   ``At the other extreme, local radio has no detectable effect on
short-run enlistments.''
   In 1984, the study said, the Army spent $45 million on recruiting
ads and used two-thirds of that money for TV spots.
   As for the issue of individual ``service'' advertisements as
opposed to ``joint'' ads, the second study concluded both types
``appear to be very powerful tools'' and in general can produce a
new recruit for roughly the same outlay of cash.
   The Army and Navy, however, do appear to benefit the most from
joint ads, while the Air Force and Marine Corps seem to do the best
with individual ads.
   ``But in general, ... the gains of any one branch do not seem to
come at the expense, in terms of lost recruits, of any othr,'' the
study said.
   ``Each branch gained recruits from the civilian population rather
than at the others' expense.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
