<HEAD>Navigation Satellite Launch Set For Friday</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CAPE CANAVERAL, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Air Force will try for a fifth
time Friday to launch an advanced navigation satellite plagued by
weather and technical problems.
   Liftoff of the Delta 2 rocket was scheduled in a nine-minute
period between 6:34 p.m. and 6:43 p.m.
   The first three launch attempts last month were halted by bad
weather. The fourth, on May 24, ended in a last-second abort when an
engine fuel valve failed to open. The valve has been replaced.
   The rocket is to boost into orbit a $65 million Navstar satellite
designed to enable U.S. and allied military units to fix their
locations anywhere in the world within 50 feet.
