<FIRST>r w AM-Bennett-Congress     06-08 0391</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bennett-Congress,380</SECOND>
<HEAD>Senator Threatens to Subpoena No-Show Drug Czar</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ANITA WOMACK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sen. John Glenn said he may subpoena drug czar
William J. Bennett after Bennett declined to testify Thursday before
a Senate committee on the drug problem in the nation's capital.
   ``We had hoped today to hear from William Bennett, the director
of National Drug Control Policy, about his plan for the District of
Columbia,'' said Glenn, chairman of the Senate Committee on
Governmental Affairs. ``Unfortunately ... Mr. Bennett refuses to
testify, at least until Sept. 8.''
   Don Hamilton, a spokesman for Bennett, said 74 different
congressional committees and subcommittes claim responsibility for
the federal anti-drug effort. ``The director can't satisfy everyone
and at the same time prepare the national strategy he's required by
law to prepare by Sept. 5,'' said Hamilton.
   At the hearing, the committee heard witnesses including District
of Columbia Mayor Marion Barry Jr. and FBI Deputy Assistant Director
Anthony Daniels on the district's drug trafficking problem, which
authorities have blamed for a record annual murder rate two years in
a row.
   Glenn, an Ohio Democrat, said his staff offered to change the
date of the hearing to fit Bennett's schedule, but he still declined.
   ``We're trying to work together with Mr. Bennett, trying to give
him support, trying to get funding for his programs ... and he can't
give us the time of day, anytime,'' said Glenn.
   Glenn said Bennett would appear before the committee if he had to
issue a subpoena to compel his testimony. He said he had a letter
delivered to Bennett's office early Thursday expressing his
concerns, but did not disclose details of the letter.
   Earlier this year, Bennett drafted a national anti-drug plan that
calls for construction of new pre-trial detention and prison
facilities, expansion of a local law enforcement task force, efforts
to rid public housing of drug users and dealers, expansion of drug
treatment facilities and an increase in job training programs.
   However, Bennett criticized the district government and said the
city would receive no direct funds from the estimated $70 million to
$80 million sought for the program.
   Washington led the nation in murders per capita last year with
372 slayings, most of them drug-related. This year, there have been
197 homicides, compared with 127 at the same time last year.
</TEXT>
