<HEAD>Red Cross Estimates 3,600 Died In Beijing Crackdown</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-China, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BONN, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Chinese Red Cross officials estimate
3,600 people were killed in the military assault on pro-democracy
demonstrators in Beijing, a Chinese students' organization said
Thursday.
   The Union of Chinese Students in the Federal Republic also urged
the West German government to impose sanctions on China for the
weekend killings.
   Hu Bo, a university student in Munich, said the union found out
through communications with friends in China that the Chinese Red
Cross estimates 3,600 people died and 60,000 were injured when
soldiers routed protesters from Tiananmen Square.
   The Chinese government says nearly 300 people, mostly soldiers,
were killed. Chinese and foreign diplomats say up to 3,000 died.
   At a news conference in Bonn, the union presented a young man who
the students said was a witness to the bloodshed in Beijing and had
just returned to West Germany.
   The Chinese man, who said he works for a company in West Germany,
said army troops in Beijing shot indiscriminately at civilians and
their homes.
   ``I still have not recovered from this. It disturbs me very
much,'' said the man, who would not give his name for fear of
possible retaliation against his relatives.
   ``A nurse I know went looking for her husband at a hospital.
Bodies there were stacked one on top of the other,'' said the man.
   The man said hospital officials told his nurse friend, ``How can
we look for him? There are so many bodies.''
