<FIRST>u a AM-TrumpShuttle     06-08 0612</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Trump Shuttle,0632</SECOND>
<HEAD>Trump's Northeast Shuttle Makes Glitzy Debut</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhotos WX10,12</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARCY GORDON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Fog delayed some flights and the painters hadn't
finished rehabbing Eastern's planes, but Donald Trump was greeted
like a conquering hero Thursday as he christened his new shuttle
with champagne, Mozart and glitz.
   The Trump Shuttle, newly acquired from strikebound Eastern
Airlines for $365 million, carried its billionaire boss from New
York to Washington and back, on to Boston and back to New York. At
every stop, he was met by ebullient crowds in airport terminals.
   In New York's crowded LaGuardia terminal, festooned with red and
white balloons, a string quartet played Mozart near a buffet laden
with mimosa cocktails of champagne and orange juice, muffins and
fresh fruit.
   ``I think this is fabulous,'' said one young businessman en route
to Boston.
   But Trump couldn't meet his advertised claim for getting the
flights off precisely on time. The 8 a.m. EDT flight from LaGuardia
to Washington National took off at about 8:17 a.m., while a flight
from Washington to New York was delayed by the weather and heavy
traffic.
   Trump personally greeted passengers boarding the flight from New
York to Washington, which was packed with reporters and regular
travelers. At one point during the flight, the billionaire grabbed
the public address microphone to announce, ``Ladies and gentlemen,
this is your flight attendant.''
   A crew member announced a slight detour as the flight entered
airspace over Atlantic City, N.J., where Trump owns several big
gambling hotels.
   Flight attendants, dressed in temporary navy-blue uniforms with
burgundy stripes on the sleeves, handed out miniature bottles of
champagne.
   ``The name `Trump' carries a lot of weight,'' said flight
attendant Denise McCain, 33, an 11-year Eastern veteran. ``We're all
very excited about it.''
   Most of the Northeast shuttle's employees worked for Eastern
before the crippling strike against the Miami-based carrier began
three months ago and pushed the airline into bankruptcy court.
   For many long-time Eastern employees, Trump's debut was
bittersweet. They were relieved to be working again but sad about
colleagues left behind on picket lines.
   ``Our hearts are with them, our thoughts are with them,'' flight
captain Ed Comer said. ``I wish them the best of luck.''
   Comer, an Eastern pilot for 25 years, now is chief pilot for
Trump Shuttle.
   The real estate tycoon signed the papers formally closing the
sale on Wednesday and staff worked through the night to clean planes
and put up new signs at the terminals.
   Some changes will take more time. Only four of Trump Shuttle's
fleet of 21 Boeing 727s had been repainted by opening day in the new
color scheme: white fuselage with red, black and gold stripes, the
word ``Trump'' above the stripes and a red ``T'' on the tail.
   Several aircraft sitting on the ramp looked like the hybrids they
were: ``Trump'' had been painted in red above the familiar Eastern
silver and blue.
   Inside, the planes still had the old brown-gold Eastern color
scheme. Trump plans to refurbish the interiors in burgundy and
saddle-brown tones, with chrome and maple wood veneer accents.
   Trump and the other passengers arriving at Washington National
were welcomed by a string and accordion quintet playing ``Casino
Royale'' and ``New York, New York.''
   A statuesque blond violinist, Janette Wilkinson, mugged with
Trump for photographers. And of course there was more champagne,
passed around by waiters in formal black-tie who also proffered
canapes.
   ``The enthusiasm of the people working for the airline is
unbelievable,'' Trump told a news conference at Washington airport.
He promised shuttle fares, $99 each way and $69 on weekends, will
remain unchanged for the near future.
</TEXT>
