<HEAD>Thatcher Rejects Request For Right Of Hong Kong Residents To Enter
Britain</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-China</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher on Thursday
rejected a request by Hong Kong's governor to grant 3.25 million
Chinese residents in the territory the right to emigrate to Britain.
   Hong Kong is due to be handed over to China in 1997, and fears
that China will not honor an agreement to preserve the colony's
capitalist system for 50 years increased after the violent crackdown
on pro-democracy demonstrations in Beijing.
   In a 90-minute emergency meeting, Governor Sir David Wilson said
he told Mrs. Thatcher that granting the right of entry to Chinese
carrying British passports ``would do an immense amount of good in
Hong Kong.''
   Wilson, speaking to reporters outside Mrs. Thatcher's 10 Downing
Street residence, said Mrs. Thatcher replied ``that would be a
matter of grave political difficulty,'' while reiterating promises
to be more flexible.
   Thousands of Hong Kong Chinese, usually the better off and best
educated, have already emigrated, mainly to Canada, Australia and
the United States.
   Mrs. Thatcher this week ruled out allowing large-scale
immigration from Hong Kong but promised to be more ``flexible''
about special categories, such as senior public servants and people
with private incomes.
