<FIRST>u w AM-D'Amato-HousingScheme 1stLd-Writethru a0665 06-08 0750</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-D'Amato-Housing Scheme, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0665,710</SECOND>
<HEAD>HUD To Reopen Investigation Into Long Island Housing Program</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: New throughout with Kemp ordering investigation reopened, McGann
taking administrative leave, other details; No pickup</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KIM I. MILLS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Department of Housing and Urban Development
will reopen a probe into an alleged scheme to rig the awarding of
federally subsidized housing in Island Park, N.Y., HUD Secretary
Jack Kemp announced Thursday.
   ``I have asked the inspector general to reopen his investigation
into the situation surrounding Geraldine McGann and the allocation
of federally subsidized housing in the village of Island Park,
N.Y.,'' Kemp said in a news release.
   Mrs. McGann, HUD's region II adminstrator, is at the center of
the controversy. Her son, Daniel McGann, was among those chosen to
purchase a $44,500 house in the program. Mrs. McGann is a village
board member and last year was appointed HUD's Region II
administrator.
   A cousin of Republican Sen. Alfonse D'Amato, a longtime resident
of Island Park, also benefitted from the program by buying a home
for $40,000, according to a HUD audit.
   Mrs. McGann asked for and was granted an administrative leave,
Kemp said Thursday. She will continue to collect her $68,500 annual
salary, according to HUD spokesman Robert E. Nipp.
   Mrs. McGann could not be reached for comment Thursday. A woman
answering the phone in her office said Mrs. McGann would not be at
work.
   The new investigation was triggered by a report in The New York
Times that officials in Island Park, a predominantly white Long
Island village, had distributed federally subsidized homes to
politically connected people and excluded blacks between 1980 and
1984. The Times based its story on a 1984 HUD audit of the program.
   Kemp also announced high-level HUD employees will no longer be
allowed to serve on state or local government boards, agencies or
panels, and no HUD employee at any level may serve on any such body
that does business with the department.
   In addition, Kemp said in the statement that HUD discretionary
funds will be targeted at ending homelessness, enforcing fair
housing and creating enterprise zones, for example.
   The Times report noted that D'Amato had persuaded former Housing
Secretary Samuel Piece to earmark $425,000 from the fund for a
swimming pool in the oceanfront community. The pool has not been
built because the project has been tied up in local politics.
   D'Amato's cousin, Anthony Ciccimarro, paid $40,000 for one of the
subsidized houses, according to the 1984 audit.
   On Thursday, D'Amato denied any involvement, and termed the
program ``excellent.''
   ``I know of no abuse and I know of no preferential treatment,''
D'Amato told a news conference. ``I wrote no applications nor made
any applications on (people's) behalf. Had they asked me I would
have. I thought the program was a good program.''
   Under the HUD program, Island Park, which has a population of
4,200 and is 97 percent white, received enough money to build 44
homes to be sold at $40,000 to $64,000 each. HUD proposed that 17 of
the 22 houses to be built during the project's second phase be sold
to blacks from nearby areas, but none were.
   The HUD houses were supposed to be advertised in local newspapers
to reach lower-income buyers, especially minorities. But some
residents were tipped off, and by the time the ads appeared, 22
buyers had been selected, the Times said.
   D'Amato said he did not believe there were tips or that no houses
were purchased by members of minority groups.
   He blamed the Times story on ``a disgruntled former employee,''
Harry Scully, who was Island Park's village clerk at the time.
   ``It's obvious that the former village clerk, Harry Scully, has
changed his story in order to attack his former associates on the
village board for whatever reasons, and that saddens me,'' D'Amato
said.
   Scully told the Times that he misled HUD officials probing the
program in 1984. He said Mrs. McGann had called him to inquire about
a HUD house for her son, and also said he had covered up for her.
   Scully did not immediately return a message left on his answering
machine.
   D'Amato said the story was based primarily on a 5-year-old
preliminary audit.
   ``I've been given to believe that the inspector general's final
report did not concur with that 5-year-old preliminary audit, and
found no evidence of wrongdoing,'' he said.
   HUD Inspector General Paul Adams said he did not know what final
report D'Amato was referring to.
</TEXT>
