<FIRST>r a AM-WellsFargo     06-08 0466</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Wells Fargo,0477</SECOND>
<HEAD>Puerto Rican Nationalists Get Maximum Sentence in $7.1 Million Robbery</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DEAN GOLEMBESKI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HARTFORD, Conn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Three Puerto Rican nationalists drew
maximum sentences of up to 15 years in prison Thursday for their
roles in a $7.1 million Wells Fargo robbery in 1983.
   But one of them, Roberto Maldonado Rivera, a civil rights
attorney from Puerto Rico, was released on $200,000 bond pending
appeal of his conviction on a conspiracy charge. Maldonado, 53, had
been free on the same bond prior to his sentencing.
   U.S. District Judge T. Emmet Clarie agreed to a bond after
expressing concern about Maldonado's high blood pressure and
acknowledging that grounds exist for an appeal to the 2nd U.S.
Circuit Court of Appeals. Earlier, the judge sentenced Maldonado to
five years in prison and fined him $100,000.
   ``I'm very happy that I can go back home,'' a jubilant Maldonado
said outside the courtroom.
   The defendant receiving the stiffest penalty was Antonio Camacho
Negron, a 45-year-old auto mechanic. He was given a 15-year prison
term and fined $150,000 on a conspiracy count and a charge of
assisting in the transfer of some of the stolen cash to Mexico.
   The third man, Norman Ramirez Talavera, a 32-year-old graphic
artist convicted on a conspiracy charge, received a five-year prison
term and was fined $50,000.
   Like Maldonado, Camacho and Ramirez told the court they will
appeal their cases.
   ``I struggled for the liberty of Puerto Rico,'' said Camacho, who
strode into the courtroom with his fist raised and wearing a red
carnation. His supporters, including his wife, also stood with
raised fists.
   The judge rejected the political argument, just as he had
throughout the trial. ``There is no right to rob money,'' Clarie
said. ``It is a crime throughout the world. No one has been charged
because of his political views.''
   Afterward, U.S. Attorney Stanley A. Twardy Jr. said only that the
defendants had received the maximum prison terms ``and that's what
the government asked.'' He declined to comment on Maldonado's
continued release.
   The three defendants, who were convicted April 10, were said to
be members of a militant Puerto Rican separatist group, Los
Macheteros. Members of the organization are accused of engineering
the Sept. 12, 1983, theft of a half-ton of money from a Wells Fargo
depot in West Hartford to finance their activities.
   A fourth defendant, Juan Segarra Palmer, had his sentencing
postponed to next week. The 39-year-old Segarra, a Harvard
University graduate, is accused of masterminding the robbery and
faces up to 165 years in prison.
   None is accused of taking part in the actual holdup. A former
Wells Fargo security guard, Victor Gerena, is accused of taking the
money, only $80,000 of which has been recovered. He is believed to
be in Cuba.
</TEXT>
