<FIRST>r i AM-Turkey-SovietDefector     06-08 0217</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Turkey-Soviet Defector,0223</SECOND>
<HEAD>Turkey Refuses to Extradite Soviet Military Defector Who Fled With
MiG-29</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ANKARA, Turkey (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government said Thursday it has
rejected a Soviet extradition request for a Soviet air force pilot
who defected in a MiG-29 jet fighter, and it indicated it was
willing to send him to the United States.
   Capt. Alexander Zuyev landed at the airport in the Black Sea city
of Trabzon May 20 and requested political asylum in the United
States.
   Turkish officials, appearing anxious to limit the damage to
Turkish-Soviet relations, sent the jet back a day after the incident.
   The Soviet Union also asked Turkish officials to extradite the
pilot, saying he stole the sophisticated plane after shooting and
wounding a guard at Tskhakaya airport.
   Turkey denied the request and gave Zuyev's asylum petition to the
U.S. Embassy, according to a Foreign Ministry announcement Thursday.
   The statement said a Turkish court ruled Tuesday that the
accusations against Zuyev were political and military, allowing him
to qualify for refugee status. Soviet authorities had been informed
of the decision, the announcement said.
   U.S. officials have criticized Turkey for denying American
representatives a chance to inspect the aircraft and learn more
about the latest Soviet technology. Turkish officials have said the
matter concerns only Turkey and the Soviet Union.
