<FIRST>r w AM-Quayle-Soviet     06-08 0233</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Quayle-Soviet,220</SECOND>
<HEAD>Quayle Discusses Soviet Crackdown with Dissident Editor</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Vice President Quayle stretched a 20-minute
appointment Thursday with the editor of a dissident Soviet journal
into a one-hour, 10-minute discussion of ethnic violence in the
Soviet Union, a spokesman said.
   Sergei Grigoryants, editor of the unofficial magazine
``Glasnost'' later told a news conference that he had discussed with
Quayle the killing of 22 Soviet Georgians in the city of Tbilisi on
April 9.
   Grigoryants said he believed the killings had been orchestrated
by the Kremlin to provide a pretext for cracking down on democratic
movements in the Soviet Union, especially those in the non-Russian
republics.
   The killings, however, provoked an outcry in the Soviet
parliament and there has been no nation-wide crackdown. Grigoryants
version of events differed sharply from official accounts. A
commission of the Soviet parliament is investigating the Tbilisi
incident.
   Grigoryants, who has been in and out of jail since Soviet
Communist Party General Secretary Mikhail S. Gorbachev rose to power
in March 1985, called the Soviet leader ``a hell of a criminal.''
   A spokesman for Quayle said the vice president ``really enjoyed
taking to this guy.''
   ``He found him a fascinating and courageous man,'' said David
Beckwith. The spokesman declined to offer a judgment on Grigoryants
views, but said that extending the meeting by 50 minutes was unusual
and ``it disrupted the vice president's afternoon schedule.''
</TEXT>
