<SECOND>AM-China-BBC,0213</SECOND>
<HEAD>BBC Says Reporter, Crew Beaten up In Beijing</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The British Broadcasting Corp.'s Asia correspondent
and his two-man camera crew were assaulted and interrogated by
Chinese police, the BBC said Thursday.
   Correspondent Brian Barron and the crew were filming civilians
next to a burned-out tank Wednesday night when six gun-wielding
secret policemen and several uniformed policemen set on them, the
BBC said.
   ``We ran into trouble while ignoring the martial law decree
banning all foreign television coverage of the unrest,'' Barron said
on BBC TV.
   ``All media coverage here is theoretically illegal. As we filmed
civilians beside a burned-out tank, we were assaulted by half a
dozen police brandishing loaded pistols.''
   Barron said half the crew's equipment was ``deliberately
smashed.''
   ``Then at gunpoint we were forced to kneel in the road for two
tense minutes. A pistol was put to the temple of our sound recordist
Steve Moss. After that, we were frog-marched with our hands up past
a silent crowd of civilians.''
   Barron said he was ``kicked and cussed'' on the march to a
factory complex where they were detained for another 30 minutes
before being ordered at gunpoint to leave.
   Their remaining equipment and videotape was confiscated, he said.
