<FIRST>u a AM-WeatherpageWeather     06-08 0468</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Weatherpage Weather,0480</SECOND>
<HEAD>Severe Thunderstorms Extend from Louisiana to Florida</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Abundant moisture on the Gulf Coast combined with unseasonably
strong winds to cause an outbreak of tornadoes and severe
thunderstorms Thursday from southeast Louisiana to the Florida
Panhandle.
   Tornadoes, rain and high wind from thunderstorms caused damage in
parts of Alabama, Florida, Louisiana and Mississippi.
   A tornado at Grosse Tete, La., west of Baton Rouge, killed at
least two people, destroyed at least 25 residences and injured at
least 15 people. Other damage was at Baton Rouge, Plaquemine,
Montpelier, and between Amite and Wilmer, La.
   Tornadoes and high wind also caused damage at Eglin Air Force
Base and Pensacola in Florida; coastal Lillian, Ala., and
Ellisville, in east-central Mississippi.
   Thunderstorm winds gusted to 67 mph at Biloxi, Miss., and to 60
mph at Mobile, Ala.
   Flash flood watches were posted for the southern half of
Mississippi, extreme southern Alabama and the Florida Panhandle.
Heavy rain washed out part of a major highway in Forrest County,
Miss. At least 6 inches of rain fell Thursday at Milton, Fla.
   Showers and thunderstorms developed in the southern Atlantic
Coast region from central Virginia across the Carolinas and Georgia
to central Florida.
   Hail fell at Belhaven, N.C. A thunderstorm brought a half-inch of
rain in 20 minutes at Jacksonville, Fla.
   Rain also fell in eastern New England and across parts of
Kentucky, Tennessee and Arkansas. Showers and thunderstorms were
scattered from Michigan to Missouri and over the central Rockies and
portions of Utah.
   Unseasonably cool weather prevailed in the northern Plains, with
afternoon temperatures in the 50s and 60s, and some readings in the
40s in northern Minnesota and Upper Michigan.
   In contrast, temperatures were over 100 degrees in extreme
southern Texas, with Brownsville reaching 102 degrees, a record for
the date. The desert Southwest had relatively moderate temperatures
in the 80s to lower 90s.
   Temperatures around the nation at 3 p.m. EDT ranged from 42
degrees at Hancock, Mich., to 98 degrees at Brownsville, Cotulla,
Laredo, McAllen and Beeville, Texas. The nation's low Thursday
morning was 33 degrees at Dickinson, N.D., and Williston, N.D.
   The Friday forecast was showers and thunderstorms across the East
Coast, Appalachians, Great Lakes, central Gulf Coast, western
portions of the central and southern Plains, and most of the Rockies
and the area westward toward the mountains of Nevada, Oregon and
Washington.
   High temperatures were forecast in the 70s and 80s for most of
the nation, but only 60s in eastern New England, near the upper
Great Lakes and along the Pacific Coast. High temperatures were
predicted in the 90s in Florida and from southern Texas across
southern Arizona to the interior valleys of California. Temperatures
should climb over 100 degrees along the Rio Grande in Texas and in
the desert Southwest.
</TEXT>
