<FIRST>r w AM-CapitolGarbage     06-08 0324</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Capitol Garbage,330</SECOND>
<HEAD>Senator's Experiment Could Lead To Recycling U.S. Capitol Garbage</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PHILIP BRASHER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An aide's suggestion to Minnesota Sen. Rudy
Boschwitz has prompted a proposal for a pilot program that could
lead Congress to recycle the 20,000 tons of garbage and trash
generated by Capitol buildings every year.
   Boschwitz asked the Senate Rules Committee to consider a
recycling program for the entire Capitol complex, which includes the
Supreme Court, Library of Congress and six congressional office
buildings.
   As a result of the request from Boschwitz and House members, the
office of the architect of the Capitol recently proposed to begin
recycling garbage from two congressional office buildings as a pilot
project.
   ``If we don't set the example certainly it won't be set
elsewhere,'' Boschwitz said Thursday during a news conference by the
newly formed Greenhouse Crisis Foundation.
   The foundation is dedicated to halt a global warming trend known
as the ``greenhouse effect.'' One of the group's goals is to slow
the cutting of forests.
   The Republican senator, who made a fortune in the plywood
business, became interested in recycling congressional garbage at
the suggestion of Linda Garczynski, a temporary staff member on loan
to his office from the Environmental Protection Agency, that it
might save money, said Boschwitz' press secretary, Tim Droogsma.
   The Capitol Architect's office has suggested the government begin
recycling garbage from the Russell Senate Office Building and the
Rayburn House Office Building, which together house about 5,000
workers, said Raymond Carroll, director of engineering.
   ``It will be interesting to see if people will cooperate, he said.
   Recycling programs require people to segregate items that can be
recycled, such as aluminum cans and paper, from items that cannot,
such as certain plastics or food waste.
   The pilot project would cost about $50,000, mostly to purchase
extra containers.
   The project will need the approval of the House and Senate
committees that requested the study.
</TEXT>
