<FILEID>AP-NR-06-08-89 2224EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-China-WorldReax     06-08 0421</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-China-World Reax,0432</SECOND>
<HEAD>Thailand Says Cambodia Talks Could Suffer; Thousands Mourn In Hong
Kong</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-China, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Thousands of Hong Kong residents bowed before a memorial of
bouquets and banners Thursday to mourn fellow ethnic Chinese killed
in Beijing, and a Thai official said the turmoil in China may delay
settlement of the Cambodian conflict.
   The East German government issued a statement supporting the
Chinese government's use of force to crush the protest movement.
Vietnam and Nepal expressed concern about the loss of life but said
the crackdown is an internal affair.
   In Hong Kong, nineteen long-robed Taoist mystics prayed and
thousands of people spent part of the Dragon Boat holiday Thursday,
bowing three times before the makeshift memorial set up outside the
Chinese government-run Xinhua News Agency. Many wiped away tears.
   Led by a band playing flutes, drums and cymbals, the mystics
beseeched the spirits of those killed by troops in China to rise
again from the netherworld. Eighteen men in saffron robes were led
by a white-robed priest.
   Xinhua functions as China's de facto embassy in Hong Kong, a
capitalist British colony filled with increasing fear over its
reversion to Chinese rule in 1997.
   Thai Foreign Ministry spokesman Jete Sucharitkhul said the Thai
government was ``very concerned'' about developments in Beijing,
where pro-democracy protests since mid-April escalated until troops
killed hundreds of people last weekend.
   China is a principal player in Cambodia as the main backer of the
Khmer Rouge, the strongest of the three-party guerrilla coalition
opposing the pro-Vietnamese government in Phnom Penh.
   ``Usually the (Chinese) government follows the party line, if
there is a power struggle you can imagine that they will be very
busy internally and not be able to pay as much attention to the
(Cambodian) issue as they have in the past,'' Jete said.
   But he said he did not think apparent divisions in the Chinese
leadership would change China's policy on Cambodia.
   Philippine President Corazon Aquino said Thursday that
Philippine-Chinese relations remain unaffected and her country's
embassy in Beijing will stay open despite plans to evacuate Filipino
civilians.
   But a Filipino senator said protesters in Beijing patterned their
protest on the ``People Power'' movement that swept Mrs. Aquino to
power in 1986 and that the Manila government should join others in
condemning the killings.
   Students in Malaysia and Indonesia staged demonstrations Thursday
against the Chinese government's crackdown, and Singapore's Chinese
Chamber of Commerce expressed shock at the bloodshed.
   In Central America, Guatemala and Costa Rica condemned the
killings.
</TEXT>
