<FIRST>r a AM-DrugTug     06-08 0321</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Drug Tug,0329</SECOND>
<HEAD>Hash, Pot Smuggler Gets Life Without Parole</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JACK SCHREIBMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A tugboat skipper convicted of trying to
smuggle 56 tons of hashish and marijuana through the Golden Gate was
sentenced Thursday to life in prison without parole.
   U.S. District Judge John Vukasin said Calvin Robinson is a
``criminal profiteer'' without any redeeming qualities who deserved
to be put behind bars for life in the toughest penitentiary the U.S.
Bureau of Prisons could find.
   Prior to the sentencing, a belligerent Robinson told the judge,
``When you put that chain around my ankle you'll be putting it
around your own neck.''
   Robinson, 47, who acted as his own lawyer during the trial,
received the maximum sentence, including a $4 million fine.
   In February, a jury found Robinson guilty of six charges
connected to his 1988 attempt to float hashish and marijuana valued
at $175 million into San Francisco Bay behind the welded panels of a
barge.
   Assistant U.S. Attorney Laurie Gray described the drug haul as
the largest of its kind in U.S. history _ ``enough dosage units for
a (drug) hit for every man, woman and child in the United States.''
   The prosecutor said Robinson deserved the maximum because of the
enormity of the drug haul, that he had brought eight members of his
family into his ``criminal enterprise, that he has a criminal record
going back to his teens, and that he tried twice to escape custody.''
   ``There are no drugs,'' shouted Robinson in reply. ``That's a
bunch of malarkey. I haven't been engaged in any criminal conduct.
... I didn't drag my family into this. ... I'm being persecuted.''
   Robinson told the judge he meant his earlier ``chain'' remark
figuratively in that he regarded the sentence as a miscarriage of
justice and both he and the judge were therefore victims. The judge
said he regarded it as a threat.
</TEXT>
