<FIRST>u w AM-Baker-Europe 1stLd-Writethru   06-08 0650</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Baker-Europe, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0669,630</SECOND>
<HEAD>Eds: Top 14 grafs new with Bush news conference; picks up graf 7
pvs: ``Our proposals,''</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE GEDDA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush on Thursday urged Soviet
President Mikhail S. Gorbachev demonstrate ``his desire for change''
by responding positively and quickly to U.S. proposals to cut
conventional forces in Europe.
   ``I think he has already demonstrated his commitment to change
and to reform,'' Bush told an evening news conference, declaring,
``I want to see perestroika succeed ... not fail.''
   Earlier in the day, Secretary of State James A. Baker III said
the administration hope Gorbachev will respond to the U.S. proposal
when he visits West Germany next week.
   Bush also extended a hand of friendship and congratulations to
the people Poland who, in the first democratic elections there since
World War II, gave a resounding vote of no confidence in the
Communist government.
   The president said that when he travels to Poland next month, he
will tell its leaders that, ``We want to work with you.''
   ``The quest for democracy in Poland ... if it goes forward, will
mean a much better relationship for Poland'' with the United States,
he said.
   Bush said the Soviet leader has already demonstrated that ``he is
interested in new thinking,'' one of the elements of Gorbachev's
perestroika, or restructuring.
   ``But there's ways now to solidify these changes,'' said the
president, urging Gorbachev to accept the U.S. offer to cut its
305,000 troops in Central Europe to 275,000 if the Soviets cut their
600,000 troops to that level as well.
   ``What is wrong with being equal?'' said Bush. ``So here's a test
now.''
   The president acknowledged that some disagreements remained
between the United States and West Germany over whether to modernize
Lance short-range nuclear missiles, but said a conventional forces
agreement could solve that problem.
   ``It is in our interests to quickly move forward, because if we
can get implemented within our time frame the agreement on
conventional forces, that will take a tremendous amount of pressure
off the Germans on short-range forces,'' said the president.
   Baker said that Soviet acceptance of the U.S. proposal to reduce
NATO and Warsaw Pact forces to the same level ``would substantially
reduce the threat of surprise military attack and the danger of
large-scale offensive operations against Western Europe.''
   ``The time is ripe for Mr. Gorbachev to respond positively to the
opportunities presented by NATO's initiatives,'' said Baker.
   The secretary of state said the U.S. proposals offer the Soviets
the opportunity both to channel resources from the military to the
civilian sector and to accelerate the process of political reform in
Eastern Europe.
   ``Our proposals point clearly to a long-term, dramatic
transformation in Europe's strategic and political landscape,'' he
said.
   Answering questions following his prepared remarks, Baker:
   _Said officials from the United States and the Palestine
Liberation Organization, meeting in Tunis Thursday, considered
``practical ways'' to achieve a comprehensive Middle East settlement
based on United Nations resolutions.
   _Called for a bipartisan agreement with the Congress on a new
policy aimed at hastening an end to South Africa's apartheid system.
He said a recent statement by South African Foreign Minister Pik
Botha that his party's platform for national elections will affirm
the need to abolish apartheid is a significant step.
   _Declared the administration is``very hopeful'' that Organization
of American States mediators will make progress towards bringing
about a democratic transfer of power in Panama.
   _Indicated he was not impressed by an Iranian proposal under
which Iran will help free American hostages in Lebanon if the United
States tries to win freedom for Iranians held by Christian forces in
Lebanon. Baker said the United States provided information on the
Iranian hostages to Iran in 1982. He urged Iran to help bring about
the immediate release of the American hostages.
