<FIRST>r a AM-AgentAttack     06-08 0310</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Agent Attack,0319</SECOND>
<HEAD>Secret Service Agent Convicted of Excessive Force</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Secret Service agent was convicted Thursday of
using excessive force in arresting a man near a presidential
candidate's New York City motorcade last year.
   The 12-member federal jury deliberated six hours before
convicting agent Kevin Schatzle, 28, of using unnecessary and
excessive force when he kicked and punched attorney Christopher
Gorayeb, 32, on April 10, 1988.
   Schatzle was acquitted of falsely arresting Gorayeb of New York
City near the motorcade of Sen. Albert Gore, D-Tenn.
   Neither Schatzle nor the 20 or so Secret Service agents who
crowded the tiny courtroom showed emotion as the verdict was read.
   Schatzle of Princeton, N.J., was in the security detail for Gore,
then campaigning for the Democratic presidential nomination in the
New York primary.
   The agent, who faces a maximum penalty of one year in prison and
a $100,000 fine, was released without bail by U.S. District Judge
Pierre Leval, who set sentencing for Sept. 13.
   During the seven-day trial, Schatzle testified that the lawyer
spit at him, but Gorayeb said he was attacked when he yelled an
obscenity at the passing motorcade because one of its cars almost
hit him as he legally crossed the street.
   ``I was kneed so hard in the groin that I was lifted off the
ground,'' Gorayeb testified, adding that after he fell to the
sidewalk, ``I was beaten, kicked and punched.''
   The agent maintained that he was only following standard
procedure for subduing a suspect. Seven witnesses testified that
they saw the agent beating Gorayeb, who said he suffered a broken
nose as well as eye, neck and shoulder injuries.
   Richard Ward, special agent-in-charge of the Secret Service's New
York field office, said Schatzle has not been suspended and his fate
with the agency will be decided at a later date.
</TEXT>
