<FIRST>u w AM-Bush 5thLd-Writethru 1stAdd 06-08 0789</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bush, 5th Ld - Writethru, 1st Add, a0779,760</SECOND>
<HEAD>WASHN: get through.''</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   But Bush was firm in his support for the students who are
agitating for democracy. ``They're not trying to flee China. They're
trying to change China,'' he said.
   Bush was asked whether Chinese leader Deng Xiaoping was still in
charge.
   ``I'm trying to say that I don't know. And you don't know, and he
doesn't know. She doesn't know,'' Bush said, pointing around the
room of reporters. ``Nobody knows, outside (China). That's the way
the Chinese system works ...
   ``I simply cannot tell you with authority who is calling the
shots.''
   The president was reluctant to directly blame any Chinese
official for the military crackdown and massacre of students,
saying, ``I don't want to pass judgement on individual leaders.''
   Pressed on whether the United States could have normal relations
with anyone responsible for the killings, Bush replied, ``It would
make it extraordinarily difficult.'' However, he said the question
was ``so hypothetical that I'm going to avoid answering it
directly.''
   Bush said he was disappointed in the course of events since he
visited China in February. ``Armed people don't shoot down unarmed
students,'' he said.
   Bush said he was satisfied with the military sanctions he
announced on Monday morning, but suggested that if the situation
does not improve he would take further steps ``at an appropriate
time.''
   Bush had a one-word description for the Republican National
Committee circular comparing Foley's voting record with that of Rep.
Barney Frank, a homosexual House member from Massachusetts _
``disgusting.''
   But he deflected a questioner who asked whether party chairman
Lee Atwater should be called to account.
   ``He looked me right in the eye,'' Bush said of his handpicked
GOP boss, ``and said he did not know about it.'' Bush noted that
Atwater ``moved promptly to remove the person who said he did know
about it and I respect that.'' RNC communications director Mark
Goodin announced his resignation on Wednesday after saying he had
written the material.
   Of Foley, the president said, ``He's the one who says the matter
should be closed, and he's right.''
   Bush seemed eager to drop the subject, and said it was time for
Congress to adopt tough ethics legislation.
   The White House said Bush, since taking office Jan. 20, has had
from 16 to 23 news conferences, depending on how you define a news
conference. The sessions have ranged in length from just a few
minutes to more than 45 minutes.
   All his previous news conferences were held during the day, and
none was conducted in the formal setting of the East Room.
   By holding a news conference in television's prime-time hours,
Bush assured himself of a large viewing audience; the major
commercial television networks were broadcasting the session.
   The president personally decided the arrangement of the East Room
for the news conference, changing the setting that Ronald Reagan
used.
   Reagan used to make a dramatic entrance, striding down the
red-carpeted, marble-columned Cross Hall to reach the East Room,
where reporters sat facing him across the length of the room.
   Bush opted for a less regal entrance, from an adjacent state
room, with reporters seated on his left as he came into the East
Room.
   Vice President Dan Quayle, who had lunch with the president, said
Bush was ready ``to knock it right out of the ballpark.''
   White House officials said Bush, unlike Reagan, did not make
extensive preparations for the news conference _ actually his second
one this week after Monday's announcement of a freeze in $600
million in military sales to China.
   Reagan used to study sample questions and hold dress rehearsals
at which his staff asked him questions.
   White House deputy press secretary B. Jay Cooper said Bush was
doing ``nothing special'' other than talking with chief of staff
John Sununu, press secretary Marlin Fitzwater and deputy national
security adviser Robert Gates.
   Cooper said national security adviser Brent Scowcroft was in Los
Angeles, giving Reagan a periodic briefing on national security
matters.
   Quayle, during a picture-taking session with visiting Soviet
editor Sergey Grigoryants, said Bush's actions against China _
including a suspension of all arms sales but not the imposition of
broad commercial sanctions _ ``has good support in the Congress''
and that the American people ``feel the president is acting in a
prudent and a wise manner.''
   In another development, a spokesman for former President Nixon
said Bush called Nixon on Monday and talked with him about 10
minutes before announcing the steps he was taking in retaliation for
China's crackdown on pro-democracy demonstrators.
   John Taylor, the spokesman, said he had no information on the
content of the call. Nixon renewed U.S. ties with Beijing in 1972
after years of diplomatic isolation.
