<FIRST>r i AM-EcologistFilm     06-08 0206</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Ecologist Film,0213</SECOND>
<HEAD>Film Rights on Slain Ecologist's Life Go to Brazilian Company</HEAD>
<DATELINE>RIO DE JANEIRO, Brazil (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Brazilian company JN Filmes has
bought the rights to make a movie about the life of slain Brazilian
ecologist Francisco ``Chico'' Mendes, producer Jofre Rodrigues
announced.
   Rodrigues told a news conference the firm won over such world
companies as Warner Bros. Inc. and United Artists in a two-month
competition.
   He said on Wednesday that JN Filmes signed a $1.76 million
contract with the Chico Mendes Foundation to lease exclusive rights
to an English-Portuguese film, TV series, autobiographical book and
videocassette on Mendes' life.
   A four-member panel from the Chico Mendes Foundation, an
organization made up of ecologists, rubber tappers and family
members, selected JN Filmes.
   Panel member Gilson Pescador said JN was picked because its offer
included making a TV series, a video and a book based on Mendes'
life.
   Mendes, 44, head of a rubber tappers union, won a United Nations
award for his struggle against ranchers out to clear the Amazon rain
forest for grazing.
   He was shot and killed in December outside his home in Xapuri,
Acre state, 2,700 miles northwest of Rio. A cattle rancher's son was
arrested in the case.
