<FILEID>AP-NR-06-08-89 2255EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-CentralAmerica-US     06-08 0213</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Central America-US,0217</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bush Advisers Says Soviets Continue Sending Weapons to Nicaragua</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MEXICO CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A special adviser to President Bush said
Thursday the Soviet Union is still sending weapons to Nicaragua's
leftist Sandinista regime, despite assurances given the United
States that such aid would stop.
   Soviet aid to the Sandinistas continues at the same level as
before, Edward L. Rowny, special adviser to Bush on arms control,
told a news conference in Mexico City.
   ``We have no evidence that the aid has slackened or lessened. On
the contrary, we have incontrovertible evidence that it continues,''
Rowny said.
   Rowny confirmed news reports that a high Soviet official had told
Secretary of State James Baker in Moscow last May that the Soviet
Union was cutting off military aid to Nicaragua.
   He refused to name the Soviet official other than calling him ``a
high authoritative source who knew what he was talking about,''
saying it would not be diplomatically proper for him to do so.
   Rowny was on a trip to Mexico and Brazil to brief leaders of the
countries and seek their reactions to Bush's latest proposals to the
Soviet Union for reducing armaments. He also was to brief them on
Bush's meeting with representatives of NATO nations in Brussels last
week.
</TEXT>
