<FIRST>u w AM-Bush-US-Iran 1stLd-Writethru   06-08 0339</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bush-US-Iran, 1st Ld - Writethru,a0764,300</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bush Sees No Change in Iran Policy</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS graf 7: ``We supplied,'' to restore dropped words, making
it read ``he said it would take more than.''</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush said Thursday he had seen no
change in Iran's terrorist policies since the death of Ayatollah
Ruhollah Khomeini, and repeated his offer to improve relations if
Iran helped free U.S. hostages held in Lebanon.
   The United States, he said, wants ``a change in relations ... We
like the Iranian people.''
   ``I stated the other day what it would take to have improved
relationships, and that would a reunciation of terror,'' he said at
a news conference, repeating a statement he made last Monday, two
days after Khomeini's death was announced.
   ``We can't have normalized relations with a state that is branded
a terrorist state,'' he said.
   ``And secondly they must facilitate the release of American
hostages. That is what it would take,'' he said.
   The president noted that the speaker of the Iranian Parliament,
Hashemi Rafsanjani, had said Iran would use its influence to help
free nine American hostages held by pro-Iranian Shiite Lebanese if
the United States helped free Shiites taken by Christian militiamen
in Beirut. Rafsanjani had made a similar offer months ago.
   ``We supplied them information,'' Bush said, without offering
details. But he said it would take more than a change in rhetoric to
improve U.S.-Iranian lessons.
   ``It is going to take a change in behaviour,'' he said. ``We
don't mind name calling. They keep calling us the Great Satan. That
doesn't bother us ... Performance is what we are looking for.''
   ``I don't see so far any sign of change,'' he said, adding that
he had ``held out the olive branch'' in his inaugural speech on Jan.
20.
   His message to Iranian leaders, then as now, was ``You want
better relations, do what's right. Do what's right by people by
people who are held against their will. We see no movement. I repeat
that offer tonight.''
</TEXT>
