<FIRST>r a AM-CultChildren 1stLd-Writethru a0758 06-08 0592</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Cult Children, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0758,0607</SECOND>
<HEAD>Father Reunited With Children After 9 Years</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS grafs 7, 9, 15 to fix spelling of mother's name to Frye,
sted Frey.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID GRAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIDDLESEX, Vt. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man who searched in 11 states for his two
sons was reunited with the boys Wednesday, 9{ years after their
mother took them to a Christmas party and never returned.
   Gerald Gromer said after meeting with his sons Mark, 14, and
Luke, 12, for the first time since 1979 that the boys were upset and
bewildered at being separated from the mother who police say
abducted them.
   The reunion was held Wednesday morning behind closed doors in a
state police barracks.
   Their father, a 34-year-old Moose Lodge manager from Bourbonnais,
Ill., described the reunion as ``not the happiest. We have lots of
things to work out in the next couple of months. But we're going to
make it.''
   After the boys were turned over to their father, a Superior Court
judge issued a temporary restraining order late Wednesday afternoon
saying the boys were to stay in Vermont until a court hearing
Thursday.
   But before the order could be served on Gromer, he and the boys
had boarded a flight from Burlington to Chicago.
   The boys' mother, Loretta Gromer Frey, allegedly took the two
boys and fled Illinois with a religious group in 1979 after their
father had been awarded custody by a divorce court.
   The group settled in Vermont several years ago but moved around
to several locations in the state, said Sgt. Jean Lessard of the
State Police.
   Ms. Frey was arrested in Woodbury on Tuesday on a warrant
charging her with child abduction, state police said.
   Gromer was told Tuesday that his children had been found, ending
a search in which he said he said he spent more than $20,000 and
traveled to 11 states.
   Gromer said his sons would not answer questions or comment
publicly. He said, ``They can't understand why they have to go back
to Illinois and why I can't come to Vermont to join their church.''
   Gromer described the church, which went by the name His Community
in Illinois but uses the name Christ Covenant Church in Vermont, as
a cult. He said his children had been ``somewhat brainwashed.''
   Lessard, in a separate interview, said police did not consider
the group a cult. ``We'd rather refer to it as a communal church,''
he said.
   Gromer's second wife, Sue, said they learned that the boys had
been found Tuesday morning. ``We've either been in police stations
or on planes or at home packing since then.''
   Ms. Frey, 34, faced a federal charge of unlawful flight to avoid
prosecution as well as the state charge, for which she was ordered
held under $75,000 bail pending extradition to Illinois.
   Gromer said that when his estranged wife abducted the chilren,
``the whole (church) group, about 100 people, up and left town on a
single day.''
   Lessard said the church group included some children, but that
Gromer's was the only case in which the children left against the
will of the person who had custody.
   His Community was founded by Roman Catholics in the Kankakee,
Ill., area as a Bible study group in the 1970s, said the Rev. James
McDermott, who worked with the group at its early meetings.
   Protestants joined in, and the group evolved into a cult with
strong leadership, said McDermott.
   ``They decided to leave. They were going to be the new exodus
from Egypt,'' McDermott said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
