<FIRST>a e PM-APonTV-StevenBanks Adv09   06-08 0793</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-AP on TV-Steven Banks, Adv 09,0809</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv09</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Friday PMs, June 9, and Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Steven Banks Brings Innovative One-Man Show to Showtime</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KATHRYN BAKER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Television Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Steven Banks is not easy to categorize. He's a
comedian, actor, rock musician and impressionist. He's very funny _
and he has something to say.
   His one-man tour-de-force, ``Steven Banks' Home Entertainment
Center,'' has been packing them in on the West Coast, and viewers of
the Showtime cable network get a look-see beginning Saturday.
   The hour-long show was taped on stage at Marines Memorial Theatre
in San Francisco. This month, Banks begins an extended run at the
Canon Theatre in Beverly Hills.
   Set in Banks' slovenly bachelor pad, the show is a series of
imaginative comic vignettes, but in a larger sense it's an inspiring
story about being stuck in life at thirtysomething and taking a risk
to get your dream.
   It opens with Banks coming home early from his dead-end job in
the corporate maze and donning his jammies so he can delve into his
fantasy life as a rock star. He cheers his own entrance with the
chant: ``Banks! Banks! Banks! Banks! ...''
   His telephone messages include repeated and increasingly
irritated calls from the office, but also a surprise call from
Lance, a high-school pal who's now a rock star.
   The eccentric Banks' kitchen shelves are lined with boxes of
Duncan Hines cookie mix, the sink is full of dirty dishes, and the
walls plastered with posters of his musical heroes. The slightest
task, be it talking on the phone or typing, turns into a performance.
   Banks is being hounded by his boss, Mr. Buttle, to finish writing
a speech that was due that afternoon. Though his intentions are
good, Banks constantly distracts himself by any means available to
avoid the mundane, and grown-up, job.
   At one point, he emerges from his closet in a tacky Vegas
jumpsuit, stuffs it with a pillow and launches into a homage to
Elvis, ``Who Killed the King of Rock 'n' Roll?'' Banks' childlike
imaginings turn bitingly satiric. ``It wasn't me, says Lisa Marie,''
goes one verse. ``I loved my dad and he loved me. ... When I get all
of his mon-ey, I'll give it to Scientology. ...''
   Banks is also being pressured by his girlfriend, Phoebe, who
intends to move in with him. Not only that, the landlord is
complaining about the noise from his drums and promises to toss
Banks out if there is one more drumbeat from his apartment.
   So Banks grabs up a guitar and gets so involved in his
impersonation of Bob Dylan, he answers the phone in a nasal,
``There's no one here by that name. This is the Dylan residence. ...
D-Y-L-A-N. ... Bob. ... B-O-B. ... Yes, it is. ... Why, thank you
very much!''
   When Lance calls back, Banks thinks he's being offered the chance
of a lifetime _ Lance's drummer has quit. But Banks' drum audition
over the phone only succeeds in costing him his apartment _ he's
already lost his girlfriend and is on the verge of losing his job.
So he does the only reasonable thing _ explodes into a punk-rock ode
to his own life:
   ``Twenty-two: degree! Twenty-three: McDonald's! Twenty-four:
Unemployment! Twenty-five: Buttle! Twenty-six: Buttle! Twenty-seven,
28, 29, 30, 31, 32! But now I'm 33, I'm tryin' to be cool, I'm
jumping around in my living room ...''
   The song fades as Banks realizes that's exactly what he's doing
and his life is a shambles.
   But this is a show with a happy ending, even in real life. The
theater audience gives Banks a standing ovation and provides an
authentic, ``Banks! Banks! Banks!''
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Elsewhere in television:
   AT HOME WITH MARTIN SCORSESE _ ``Italianamerican,'' an early
Martin Scorsese work, in which the director of ``Taxi Driver'' and
``The Last Temptation of Christ'' interviewed his Italian parents,
airs Sunday on The Learning Channel as part of the series ``Coming
to America.'' While he was a film-school student, Scorsese asked his
mother to let him film her making her spaghetti sauce. He he ended
up with a touching and intimate reminiscence of what it was like to
grow up the children of immigrants in a new land. The interviews are
intercut with still photos of Scorsese's grandparents and archival
footage of lower Manhattan. ...
   `MOLLY' RE-UPS _ The Lifetime cable network has ordered 26 more
episodes of ``The Days and Nights of Molly Dodd.'' The series,
starring Blair Brown, was canceled last year by NBC, but picked up
by the cable channel for 13 new episodes that began airing in April.
The 26 newest episodes will begin appearing in early 1990.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Fri PMs, June 9</NOTE>
</DOC>
