<FILEID>AP-NR-06-08-89 0147EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-Saudi-OilStrike     06-08 0297</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Saudi-Oil Strike,0307</SECOND>
<HEAD>Saudi Aramco Confirms Strike</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DHAHRAN, Saudi Arabia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Saudi Aramco, Saudi Arabia's
oil-producing firm, says it struck a large well that could yield
8,000 barrels a day of crude oil.
   The company, which operates the world's largest oil field in a
country with the world's largest reserves, said Wednesday the find
was made in the Hawtah region in central Saudi Arabia about 120
miles south of the capital Riyadh.
   Saudi Aramco said preliminary tests indicated the well could
yield 8,000 barrels a day of light crude containing only 0.06
percent sulphur.
   Sadad, I. Husseini, Saudi Aramco's vice president for exploration
and production, said the find ``confirms the potential for
substantial discoveries ... in rock formations recently studied by
Saudi Aramco and assessed to be highly prospective.''
   Oil industry executives and company sources reported the strike
Tuesday. But they said it was made in the nearby Khurais region and
gave no details.
   The find was made as part of a major exploration program launched
by Saudi Aramco in 1986 after the Saudi government expanded the
company's exploration concession.
   It was the first strike since Aramco was restructured in late
1988 and the first in a promising area only recently identifed. Most
of the company's oil field is located in the east part of the
country.
   Saudi Aramco announced earlier this year that its proven reserves
have gone up from 169 billion to 252 billion barrels, and could
reach 315 billion barrels.
   The company has discovered 52 oil fields and one commercial gas
field since it started exploration 55 years ago.
   Under its current Organization of Petroleum Exporting Countries
quota, Saudi Arabia exports 4.524 million barrels a day, but in the
oil boom years output peaked at more than 11 million barrels a day.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
