<FILEID>AP-NR-06-08-89 0148EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-WorldGrain     06-08 0271</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-World Grain,0280</SECOND>
<HEAD>New Season Production Outlook Better Than Forecast</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   New season world grain production may be larger
than forecast, with early signs of an 11.4 percent increase on the
current season's drought-hit yield, according to the International
Wheat Council.
   The council, one of the foremost grain forecasting bodies, now
puts world wheat output between July 1989 to June 1990 at 533
million metric tons, compared with 537 million forecast last month
and 504 million last season.
   Production of coarse grains _ principally maize, rye, oats,
barley and sorghum, is now forecast at 840 million tons, against 830
million previously and 728 million this season, the council said
Wednesday.
   The rise is attributed to improved prospects for the Soviet Union
and the United States, with forecasts of 112 million tons for the
Soviets, up from with 97.6 million in 1988-89, and 240 million for
the U.S., compared with 149.6 million.
   Bigger coarse grain crops are also foreseen for China at 95
million against 93.6 million this season and the European Community
at 90 million, compared with 89.3 million.
   The Indian harvest, however, is expected to fall 2.6 million tons
to 30 million.
   Forecasts of 1989-90 wheat production, with 1988-89 estimates in
brackets, include:
   Soviet Union 90.0 million (84.5 million); China 89 million (87
million); the EEC 86.7 million (85.3 million); the United States
56.5 million (49.3 million); and India 50 million (45.1 million).
   The council's first forecast of 1989-90 world coarse grain trade
is down eight million tons at 93 million, reflecting the prospect of
lower Soviet imports, which could drop by 9 million to 16 million.
</TEXT>
