<FIRST>r f PM-Time-Deals     06-08 0209</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Time-Deals,0221</SECOND>
<HEAD>Synopsis of Two Deals Facing Time Shareholders</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Time-Paramount, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Time Inc. shareholders are faced with two deals
involving their publishing and cable company _ a merger with Warner
Communications Inc. and a tender offer from Paramount Communications
Inc.
   Here is a capsule description on what is being proposed:
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>THE WARNER DEAL:</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Time and Warner have agreed on a merger that involves an exchange
of stock to create a company that would be the world's largest media
and entertainment concern.
   Under that plan, Time shareholders would get one share in the new
company for each share of Time stock they own. Warner shareholders
would get 0.465 shares of stock in the new company for each Warner
share they hold.
   The arrangement would leave Time shareholders with roughly 40
percent of the new company and Warner shareholders with the rest.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>THE PARAMOUNT DEAL:</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Paramount has launched a tender offer of $175 a share for all of
Time's stock. The offer expires at midnight July 5 unless extended.
   Under this plan, Time shareholders will get $175 in cash for each
share of Time's stock they hold, providing that at least a majority
of Time's shares are tendered and other conditions are met.
</TEXT>
