<FIRST>r f PM-Time-Stocks     06-08 0369</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Time-Stocks,0383</SECOND>
<HEAD>Paramount Bid For Time Inc. Boosts Other Media Stocks</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Time-Paramount, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Media and entertainment companies were in the
spotlight on Wall Street as news of Paramount Communications Inc.'s
$10.7 billion bid for Time Inc. revived speculation about possible
bids for other communications concerns.
   The stocks of several big media firms rose sharply Wednesday on
the New York Stock Exchange. MCA Inc. rose $1.87{ to close at
$56.62{; CBS Inc. surged $4.75 to $205.62{; Capital Cities-ABC
picked up $7.50 to $468; and Warner Communications Inc., whose
planned merger with Time was cast into doubt by the Paramount bid,
rose $1.75 to $53.50.
   Wednesday's advances were similar to gains chalked up earlier
this year when Time and Warner announced plans to merge and form the
world's largest media concern.
   News of a big takeover bid for a company often sparks interest in
other firms in that industry, but the activity in media and
entertainment stocks has had an added twist recently.
   The media, information and entertainment industries have
undergone a wave of consolidations in recent years, with large
companies snapping up other firms to create media giants.
   The buyers mainly have been foreign publishing and broadcasting
giants such as Rupert Murdoch's News Corp. and Maxwell Communication
Corp., and electronics behemoth Sony Corp. These companies have
scooped up U.S. media concerns in a torrent of deals made possible
in recent years by their own wealth and the weak U.S. dollar.
   The growth of media conglomerates was uppermost in the minds of
Time executives as they negotiated their agreement with Warner.
   Martin S. Davis, Paramount's chairman, apparently wants to be
part of the trend. If he succeeds in acquiring Time, his own
entertainment and publishing conglomerate would have a projected $7
billion in sales.
   A Time-Warner combination would have projected revenue of more
than $10 billion.
   Paramount, which changed its name from Gulf &amp; Western Inc. on
Monday, owns Paramount Pictures and Television, Simon &amp; Schuster and
Prentice Hall publishers, and a number of other broadcasting,
entertainment and publishing businesses.
   Time publishes magazines _ including Time, Life and Sports
Illustrated _ and books and also owns broadcast and cable television
properties including Home Box Office.
</TEXT>
