<FILEID>AP-NR-06-08-89 0212EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-Eastern Bjt   06-08 0627</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Eastern, Bjt,0654</SECOND>
<HEAD>Court Denies Eastern's Appeal on Pilots' Strike</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LAURAN NEERGAARD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A spokesman for the Air Lines Pilots' Association
says a federal appeals court ruling means Eastern Airlines' attempt
to expand its limited service may be stalled.
   But Eastern spokesman Jim Ashlock declined to comment on how the
ruling Wednesday by the 11th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals would
affect plans for Eastern's reorganization.
   A three-judge panel of the appeals court upheld a lower court
ruling denying Eastern's request for an injunction against the
pilots union to stop the strike.
   Ashlock said the Miami-based airline has no plans to appeal the
case further.
   In another setback for Eastern, the Justice Department said
Wednesday it plans to file an antitrust suit blocking Eastern's
proposed sale to USAir Group Inc. of its airport gates in
Philadelphia and its Philadelphia-Toronto route.
   The Justice Department said the $85 million proposal ``threatens
to lessen competition'' in airline service between Philadelphia and
other cities, said Michael Boudin, acting antitrust chief for the
department.
   The appeals court ruling was prompted by a lawsuit Eastern filed
in U.S. District Court after most of the airline's 3,600 pilots
honored picket lines set up by members of the Machinists union when
it went on strike March 4.
   The walkout, also supported by Eastern flight attendants,
virtually grounded the carrier and compelled it to seek bankruptcy
protection from creditors March 9.
   Kenny Thomas, a communications specialist with the Air Lines
Pilots' Association, said the ruling ``reaffirms the pilots'
solidarity in dealing with (Texas Air Corp. Chairman) Frank
Lorenzo.''
   He also said the ruling strengthens the union's backing of
Chicago commodities trader Joseph Ritchie, who is trying to buy the
carrier from Texas Air, Eastern's parent company.
   Thomas said that in light of the ruling, officials for Ritchie
will meet with U.S. Bankruptcy Court officials in Washington to
discuss the proposed buyout again.
   Eastern's creditors have rejected Ritchie's proposal.
   Chuck Kilian, a striking Eastern pilot in Atlanta, said the
ruling was not a surprise but was a morale booster.
   ``As time moves along, we get more and more little victories,''
he said. ``This is a good victory at a good time. It gives us that
much more resolve and enthusiasm.''
   Thomas said the ruling means Lorenzo will not have enough pilots
to carry through Lorenzo's plan to rebuild the airline as a smaller
carrier and sell about $1.8 billion of its assets.
   Eastern said Wednesday it is negotiating to sell its South
American routes, possibly to rival American Airlines.
   ``We have talked to American,'' Ashlock said from Miami.
   He said Eastern also has held talks on the routes with other
airlines.
   Ashlock declined to identify the other carriers interested in the
South American network, which served 10 cities before Eastern was
struck, or to disclose Eastern's asking price.
   Wall Street analysts have estimated the value of the network at
about $150 million.
   Any sale of Eastern assets must be approved by a federal
bankruptcy court judge in New York. The judge recently approved the
sale of Eastern's Northeast shuttle to developer Donald Trump for
$365 million.
   American spokesman Ed Stewart acknowledged American's general
interest in Eastern assets but would not confirm that talks had been
held on the South American routes.
   ``We're looking at things that might be for sale,'' Stewart said
from American's Fort Worth, Texas, headquarters.
   For American, the nation's largest airline, the South American
routes would bolster its strategy to expand overseas. American
recently added new flights to Western Europe and has expressed
interest in Eastern's Caribbean routes.
   Before the walkout, Eastern served Caracas, Venezuela; Asuncion,
Paraguay; Barranquilla and Cali, Colombia; Buenos Aires, Argentina;
Guayaquil and Quito, Ecuador; Lima, Peru; La Paz, Bolivia; and
Santiago, Chile.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890608-0229 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-08-89 0311EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-Eastern-FAA Bjt   06-08 0816</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Eastern-FAA, Bjt,0845</SECOND>
<HEAD>Lawmaker Warns FAA Chief on Eastern Maintenance</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARCY GORDON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Shortages of staff and spare parts could be
hampering strikebound Eastern Airlines' ability to properly maintain
its fleet, the head of a congressional panel has told the Federal
Aviation Administration.
   Rep. Cardiss Collins, D-Ill., chairwoman of the Government
Activities and Transportation Subcommittee of the House Committee on
Government Operations, expressed the concern in a letter to acting
FAA Administrator Robert E. Whittington.
   While it is clear Eastern has suffered staffing problems because
of the 3-month-old walkout by Machinists union members, pilots and
flight attendants, Collins' letter raised the question of whether
the few planes still flying are receiving proper care.
   The FAA recently concluded a special investigation of maintenance
at Eastern's facilities at its Miami base and at Atlanta, but has
not disclosed its findings.
   The transportation subcommittee's staff has reviewed internal
company documents indicating that ``manpower and parts shortages
continue to plague the maintenance function of Eastern,'' Collins
wrote the FAA chief last Thursday. A copy of the letter was obtained
by The Associated Press.
   The impact of maintenance on airline safety has been highlighted
by several accidents. In one case, the National Transportation
Safety Board largely blamed Aloha Airlines' maintenance program for
failing to detect fatigue damage to the fuselage of a 19-year-old
Boeing 737 that split open over Hawaii, killing a flight attendant.
   Collins said Eastern's maintenance shortcomings appear to persist
despite several FAA investigations of the carrier and
``substantial'' fines against the airline, as well as commitments by
management to correct the problems.
   Whittington hasn't yet responded to Collins' letter, FAA
spokesman Fred Farrar said Wednesday. He said the special
investigation was completed on May 12 but the report on it hasn't
yet been submitted to the FAA chief.
   ``Everything they (Eastern) do is being watched,'' Farrar said.
``We're going to keep a very close eye on Eastern until the strike
is over.''
   Eastern spokesman Jim Ashlock said he couldn't comment on
Collins' letter because he wasn't familiar with the documents to
which she referred.
   ``Eastern is under the most intensive scrutiny that any airline's
ever been subjected to,'' he said, adding that the adequacy of its
manpower and parts could easily be checked.
   Early last month, Eastern temporarily surrendered its repair
station certificate at New York's John F. Kennedy International
Airport after the FAA determined the carrier had failed to follow
its system for recording and inspecting maintenance work.
   The suspension was for actions that predated the March 4 start of
the strike, which pushed Eastern into bankruptcy court five days
later.
   Soon after the JFK certificate was pulled, the FAA sent nine
inspectors to Eastern's main base in Miami to determine if
violations of maintenance record-keeping rules, such as those found
in New York, existed in Miami and Atlanta.
   JFK, Miami International and Atlanta's Hartsfield International
are the sites of Eastern's three principal maintenance facilities.
   If the FAA ordered Eastern to temporarily relinquish its
certificates for the Miami and Atlanta facilities, that could
severely hamper the airline's ability to operate.
   When a maintenance certificate is suspended, the airline is
prohibited from doing work at the facility until deficiencies are
corrected. The work must be contracted out, or planes needing
repairs must be ferried elsewhere.
   In her letter, Collins called Eastern's surrendering of its JFK
certificate ``unprecedented.''
   ``I am concerned that this may not be an isolated case, and may
be in fact, an indication of systemic problems throughout Eastern's
maintenance department,'' the lawmaker told Whittington. She asked
him to advise her of the results of the latest investigation as soon
as possible.
   Collins' subcommittee previously held hearings on maintenance
practices at Eastern and their potential impact on passenger safety.
She has expressed concern about Eastern's decision to continue some
operations during the strike.
   The airline has faced a number of FAA investigations in recent
years, including one in 1986 that resulted in a $9.5 million fine
for safety infractions and a threatened suspension of Eastern's
overall operating license.
   Eastern's unions contend the maintenance problems are systemwide
and endanger safety. They accuse supervisors of ``pencil-whipping,''
or signing their names to documents on aircraft repairs that weren't
made.
   The unions also charge that management, in an effort to cut costs
and maintain flying schedules, has bullied mechanics and pilots who
complain about serious maintenance violations.
   Eastern countercharges that some machinists hid or destroyed
maintenance records at JFK and then told the FAA that company
supervisors neglected to have necessary work performed. Company
representatives discovered records hidden in file cabinets and
stuffed under sofa cushions in union areas at the airport, said
Eastern spokesman Robin Matell.
   ``We've never dispatched an unsafe plane; we have one of the best
safety records in the industry,'' Matell said. He called union
complaints ``a deliberate attempt to drive away our passengers and
weaken the company.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
