<FILEID>AP-NR-06-08-89 0228EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-Fed-Currency Bjt   06-08 0553</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Fed-Currency, Bjt,0581</SECOND>
<HEAD>Central Bank Reveals Active Dollar-Selling Last Winter</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By VIVIAN MARINO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The United States spent more than $2 billion to
temper the dollar's rise in foreign exchange last winter, as higher
interest rates and political uncertainty abroad bolstered the value
of the currency, a Federal Reserve report shows.
   The latest quarterly foreign-exchange report issued Wednesday by
the Federal Reserve Bank of New York showed the Fed and the Treasury
sold $2.14 billion for the equivalent West German marks and Japanese
yen during the three months ended April 30.
   The dollar sales, which were mostly for marks, were the largest
since the $2.93 billion sold during the May-July 1988 period, the
Fed said.
   In the previous November-January quarter, the United States
bought $2.4 billion against the mark and yen, then sold $1.88
billion against marks as market sentiment turned more bullish for
the dollar.
   Sam Y. Cross, an executive vice president of the New York Fed,
said the latest operations were designed to maintain market
stability and generally were coordinated with the central banks of
the ``Group of Seven'' industrial nations. Besides the United
States, the G-7 includes Japan, Britain, West Germany, France, Italy
and Canada.
   Cross said that some of the government's intervention operations
were done jointly with other central banks, but at other times the
United States acted alone after notifying its trading partners.
   Currency traders are often keenly aware of the activities of
central banks in the open markets, but the Fed's policy is to
comment only well after the fact. The Fed also does not provide any
data on intervention by foreign central banks.
   The government's dollar-selling operations during the
February-April period came amid strong foreign demand for the U.S.
currency.
   U.S. short-term interest rates were comparatively higher than
those abroad as a result of inflation-fighting efforts by the Fed.
That made dollar-denominated assets more attractive to foreigners,
thereby increasing the need to convert to dollars.
   Political developments abroad also weighed against several major
foreign currencies.
   In Japan, an insider-trading scandal brought the government of
Prime Minister Takeshita under increasing pressure, while in West
Germany, the imposition and subsequent removal of a controversial
withholding tax on interest income brought considerable confusion to
the market.
   Intervention involving marks took place from Feb. 2 to Feb. 6,
when the government sold $350 million, according to the Fed report.
The government also entered the market between March 8 and March 30,
when it sold $1.419 billion; on April 10 and April 11, when it sold
$170 million; and on April 30, when it sold $50 million, the report
said.
   Sales of dollars for yen were made during the March 8-30 period,
amounting to $100 million, and on April 30, amounting to $50
million, it said.
   During the February-April period the dollar reached a high of
1.9025 marks and 133.50 yen. The dollar has risen even further
lately, trading around 1.98 marks and 142 yen.
   The dollar reached its highest point of the decade in February
1985. It declined slightly until September 1985, when G-7 leaders
agreed to lower its value to help narrow the U.S. trade gap and
stave off protectionist sentiment in Congress.
   The dollar touched bottom in the final days of 1987 before
rebounding sharply at the beginning of 1988.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
