<FIRST>r f PM-TW-Coniston     06-08 0658</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-TW-Coniston,0685</SECOND>
<HEAD>Coniston Wins TW Services Fight With $1.65 Billion Bid</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOYCE M. ROSENBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Coniston Partners, which won TW Services Inc.
after a bitter 9-month-long fight, said it will retain the company's
core food service segments but sell off some of its other businesses.
   TW, which had repeatedly rejected Coniston's advances and tried
to thwart the investor group with a variety of defenses, said
Wednesday it had accepted the partnership's sweetened $1.65 billion
offer.
   ``I think that in the end they realized we were determined to buy
the company or at least determined to see it (the takeover battle)
to the end,'' said Augustus Oliver, a Coniston principal.
   The $34-per-share agreement marks the latest victory for
Coniston, which has reaped big profits by acquiring stakes in
companies, mounting or threatening to mount a takeover bid and later
selling its shares back to the company or a rival bidder.
   TW stock rose 25 cents a share to $33 in New York Stock Exchange
composite trading Wednesday.
   Management of TW Services _ whose holdings include thousands of
Denny's and Hardee's restaurants _ was reticent about the deal,
which suggested their decision to accept Coniston's latest offer was
a reluctant one.
   ``The only comment is that management and their directors have
worked hard to bring shareholders value and feel that shareholders
are getting a fair price for our stock,'' said James Ryan, a TW
spokesman.
   Coniston also said it planned to replace TW Chairman and Chief
Executive Officer Frank Salizzoni. Oliver said Jerome Richardson,
now TW's president, was expected to become the new chief executive.
   Salizzoni was not in his office Wednesday when a reporter called
for comment.
   Oliver said Coniston would retain the 1,220-restaurant Denny's
chain; Spartan Food Systems Inc., the largest franchisee of Hardee's
fast-food restaurants; and Canteen, which provides food services to
such corporations and clients as the National Park Service and
Yankee Stadium.
   However, Oliver said in a telephone interview, American Medical
Services, TW's nursing home business, and other minor divisions
would be sold.
   Under the sweetened offer, scheduled to expire July 5, Coniston
affiliate SWT Associates LP will pay $34 in cash for 61 percent of
TW's 48.5 million outstanding shares.
   That would give Coniston, which owns 19 percent of TW's stock, 80
percent of the company's shares. After the offer expires, holders of
the remaining 20 percent of TW stock would be given the choice of
receiving $34 in cash, or $30 and one share of stock in the
surviving company.
   Coniston had offered $29 a share, or about $1.4 billion, for TW.
   Oliver said Coniston had financing commitments from Citibank and
Donaldson Lufkin &amp; Jenrette Securities Corp. to complete the tender
offer.
   Coniston first approached TW last September. TW consistently
rejected the bid as inadequate and said it would deploy its ``poison
pill'' takeover defense against Coniston.
   Poison pills drive up the cost of hostile takeovers by allowing
target companies to issue additional stock.
   Coniston sought unsuccessfully to have the pill invalidated by
state courts in Delaware, where TW is incorporated.
   Coniston also planned to wage a proxy fight to elect three
candidates to TW's 11-member board, a move the company attempted to
thwart by postponing its annual meeting.
   Despite the obstacles thrown up by TW, Coniston refused to back
down.
   On Tuesday, TW said its board was reviewing proposals to buy the
company or its units. Ryan, the TW spokesman, said the board would
not reveal who the other bidders may have been or the amount of
their offers.
   TW had earnings of $66.9 million in 1988 on revenue of $3.6
billion.
   Coniston failed to win a proxy fight to force a sale of Gillette
Co. last year, although the company later agreed to a stock buyback.
In 1987, the firm helped force the restructuring of Allegis Corp.,
which was renamed UAL Inc., by acquiring a large stake and
threatening to mount a takeover.
</TEXT>
