<FILEID>AP-NR-06-08-89 0737EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-Rostenkowski-CapitalGains     06-08 0478</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Rostenkowski-Capital Gains,0492</SECOND>
<HEAD>Appears Willingness to Compromise on Capital Gains Tax Reduction</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: also on general news wires.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The chairman of the House Ways and Means
Committee said he would consider accepting lower capital gains tax
rates as a revenue-raising measure.
   ``I haven't seen a way'' to raise revenue in the next fiscal year
without a capital gains rate cut, Rep. Dan Rostenkowski, D-Ill.,
told The New York Times in an interview published today.
   He said that with President Bush's opposition to new taxes, ``The
only thing that seems negotiable is capital gains.''
   Rostenkowski has long opposed Bush's proposal to reduce the
capital gains rate _ currently the same as the income tax rate on
ordinary income _ to 15 percent.
   In Washington, a committee aide who spoke on condition of
anonymity said Wednesday night that Rostenkowski had not changed his
opposition to a reduction.
   But in an interview published today in The Wall Street Journal,
Rostenkowski said: ``Let the process begin. ... Everything is on the
table.''
   Rostenskowski recognizes that Bush, who campaigned on a slogan of
``read my lips _ no new taxes,'' and a majority of committee
Republicans are going to have to accept any revenue compromise, the
aide said.
   ``Proponents of capital gains reduction have a real leg up'' in
such a situation, the aide said, because of the recognition on all
sides that any change, up or down, in capital gains rates yields a
revenue increase in the first year.
   Capital gains are the increases in value of any assets, such as
stocks. A tax rate increase captures a bigger slice of the proceeds
of asset sales that would be made in any case; a rate decrease
stimulates more sales and brings in more government revenue that way.
   Economists disagree over what happens after the first year. Bush
argues that there are permanently more transactions with lower rates
than they would otherwise be; Rostenkowski and others argue that
this is not so and people selling stock would get an unjustified tax
break.
   Additionally, opponents of lower rates say that stock trading is
done by people of high incomes and benefits of those rates are not
available to those living on modest salaries.
   The Ways and Means Committee is under instructions from the
Budget Committee to come up with an additional $5.3 billion in
revenue for the fiscal year beginning Oct. 1. The Joint Taxation
Committee estimated that a cut in rates to 15 percent as proposed by
Bush would yield $3.5 billion in the first year though it would
reduce revenue after that; the Office of Management and Budget
estimated the first-year gain at $4.2 billion.
   Though often in recent years capital gains have been taxed a
separately stated rates, currently gains are treated like all other
income. The top current federal income tax rate is 33 percent.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
