<FILEID>AP-NR-06-08-89 0931EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-Stock-Taxes     06-08 0250</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Stock-Taxes,0260</SECOND>
<HEAD>Rostenkowski Asking Congress to Kill Tax Break</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: also on general news wires.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Rep. Dan Rostenkowski, chairman of the House
Ways and Means Committee, is asking Congress to kill a tax break for
Employee Stock Ownership Plans on grounds it has been abused by
lenders.
   Rostenkowski, D-Ill., introduced a bill Wednesday to repeal a
1984 provision that allows banks and other lenders to escape taxes
on half the income from loans made to such plans, known as ESOPs.
   ``Once again, we have witnessed a special tax benefit provision
become an abusive loophole through the ingenuity of Wall Street
investment bankers,'' Rostenkowski said Wednesday. ``Congress did
not intend for this special tax provision to be used in such an
excessive manner.''
   ESOPs were given preferential treatment under federal tax law to
make it easier for employees to buy stock in the companies for which
they work. In many cases, ESOPs have been used to keep alive
employers threatened by bankruptcy.
   The government estimates that 10 million workers are covered by
about 10,000 ESOPs.
   Rostenkowski said there is evidence that many companies are
borrowing to set up ESOPs only to obtain a tax benefit while
providing nothing new for employees.
   He noted a week-old Internal Revenue Service ruling that
authorized public sale of bonds issued by ESOPs. That ruling,
Rostenkowski said, will produce even more ESOP borrowing.
   He estimated the tax preference for ESOPs will cost the treasury
$8 billion in lost revenues over five years.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890608-0243 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-08-89 1016EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f PM-WallStreet10am     06-08 0299</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Wall Street 10am,0316</SECOND>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The stock market headed higher today, extending
its recent rally fueled by takeover news and rumors and declining
interest rates.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials rose 3.49 to 2,515.81 in
the first half hour of trading.
   Advancing issues outnumbered declines by about 4 to 3 in
nationwide trading of New York Stock Exchange-listed issues, with
534 up, 389 down and 533 unchanged.
   Volume on the Big Board came to 30.41 million shares as of 10
a.m. on Wall Street.
   New takeover bids this week for Time Inc. and LIN Broadcasting
touched off buying in a wide range of stocks thought to be possible
future candidates for acquisitions or buyouts.
   Eastman Kodak, said to be a potential target, led the active list
and rose { to 51.
   Time stock, meanwhile, dipped 2 to 168 and LIN slipped 1} to 127}
after both experienced dramatic runups in Wednesday's trading.
   Beyond the takeover hubbub, analysts say the market has benefited
from signs this week that the Federal Reserve might be starting a
change of course in its credit policy.
   After more than a year of tightening credit conditions, the Fed
is widely believed to have made an initial step toward easing, by
permitting a decline in the interest rate on federal funds, or
overnight loans between banks.
   The NYSE's composite index of all its listed common stocks edged
up .11 to 182.45. At the American Stock Exchange, the market value
index was up .23 at 364.64.
   On Wednesday the Dow Jones industrial average climbed 16.00 to
2,512.32.
   Advancing issues outnumbered declines by about 9 to 5 on the
NYSE, with 976 up, 536 down and 493 unchanged.
   Big Board volume totaled 213.71 million shares, against 187.57
million in the previous session.
</TEXT>
