<FILEID>AP-NR-06-08-89 1021EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f PM-LIN-McCaw 1stLd-Writethru   06-08 0711</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-LIN-McCaw, 1st Ld-Writethru,0737</SECOND>
<HEAD>McCaw Begins Tender Offer For LIN</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Leads with 5 new grafs to UPDATE with tender offer beginning;
uppicks 5th graf pvs: ``We certainly ...; edits to conform.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE TIBBITS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KIRKLAND, Wash. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   McCaw Cellular Communications Inc. today
began its $5.85 billion tender offer for the shares of LIN
Broadcasting Corp. it does not already own.
   The $120 a share offer, which will expire on July 6 unless
extended, requires among other conditions approval from the Federal
Communications Commission. In a news release, McCaw stated such
approval could take six months.
   Shares of both companies edged lower in early trading today, LIN
was down $1.75 to $127.75 a share and McCaw dipped 75 cents to
$46.25 in national over-the-counter trading.
   On Wednesday, a day after McCaw announced its bid for the New
York-based cellular phone, television and publishing company, LIN
stock soared $26 a share to $129.50 in over-the-counter trading and
McCaw stock rose $3.75 to $47 a share.
   But the bid had a broad spinoff effect on the stock prices of
other companies involved in the cellular telephone business.
Officials at rival companies said the bid created a new benchmark
for the value of their cellular properties.
   ``We certainly see this as an important announcement,'' said
Diane Olberg of Pacific Telesis Group in San Francisco.
   On the New York Stock Exchange, Pacific Telesis rose $1.12{ to
$42 and Southwestern Bell Corp. of St. Louis rose $1 to $53.87{.
Cellular operations are a small part of those companies' revenue.
   By acquiring LIN, McCaw would have twice the potential cellular
market of Pacific Telesis and Southwestern Bell, its closest
competitors.
   Combining both sets of franchises would form the ``regional
supersystem'' of cellular holdings that McCaw has been seeking, said
analyst Geoffrey Johnson of Argus Research Corp. in New York.
   Cellular franchises have grown in popularity with improvements in
technology and customer demand for mobile phones.
   Johnson said a battle for LIN's stock was likely.
   ``The market is obviously anticipating a bidding war erupting,''
he said.
   Spokespersons for Pacific Telesis and Southwestern Bell refused
to comment on whether their companies are interested in LIN,
although analysts have cited both as possible suitors.
   McCaw spokesman Steven Bruce declined to say whether the company
might raise its offer. He would only say that ``the offer is on the
table.''
   LIN, which said it was studying the offer, has interests in
cellular systems serving New York, Los Angeles, Philadelphia, Dallas
and Houston, in addition to owning seven network-affiliated
television stations and a specialty publishing house that produces
hardcover tourist guides for hotel rooms.
   McCaw, LIN's largest shareholder, has franchises serving
customers in Seattle, San Francisco, Miami, Denver, Minneapolis and
Portland, Ore.
   LIN's rights in five of the nation's top 10 markets ``would fit
in very nicely'' with McCaw's small- to medium-sized properties,
Johnson said.
   Details on how the deal would be structured will be announced
before the end of the week, Bruce said.
   Analysts estimated McCaw has amassed close to $3 billion for the
acquisition, including $1.5 billion through the sale of a 22 percent
interest to British Telecommunications PLC, a $1.3 billion line of
credit and $800 million in cash.
   A source close to McCaw who asked not to be identified confirmed
the company had put together around $3 billion.
   McCaw's offer values LIN at about $6.5 billion. But since McCaw
already owns 9.8 percent of LIN, it would cost $5.85 billion to
acquire the remaining shares.
   Two weeks ago, LIN announced its board had approved in principle
spinning off a new subsidiary that would own its TV stations. It
said it would operate its cellular operations and publishing
business as a separate company.
   LIN said the move was made for operating and strategic reasons
and was ``not intended as a precursor to any other corporate
transaction.''
   McCaw's cellular telephone systems serve 50 million ``pops,'' an
industry measure that refers to market-area population multiplied by
percentage ownership in the cellular systems serving those areas.
   LIN has more than 18 million pops, while Pacific Telesis and
Southwestern Bell each have about 30 million.
   At $6.5 billion, McCaw would be paying about $360 per pop. As
recently as 1986, McCaw was buying franchises for $6 per pop.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890608-0245 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-08-89 1028EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f BC-EEC-SovietUnion     06-08 0245</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-EEC-Soviet Union,0255</SECOND>
<HEAD>EEC Ready To Negotiate 10-Year Pact With Soviet Union</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A top EEC official said Thursday the
trade bloc is ready to negotiate an ``ambitious'' 10-year trade and
cooperation agreement with the Soviet Union.
   In a speech to a conference in Moscow, External Relations
Commissioner of the 12-nation European Economic Community Frans
Andriessen said formal negotiations on a pact could start before
August.
   ``It will be an ambitious agreement covering trade, commercial
and economic cooperation whose scope matches the importance of the
two parties,'' Andriessen said. Copies of the speech were made
available in Brussels.
   EEC foreign affairs ministers are to discuss on Monday proposals
for a mandate to start negotiations with the Soviet Union.
   Trade with the EEC currently accounts for 11 percent of the
Soviet Union's imports and 14 percent of its exports, while the
EEC's exports to the Soviet Union account for only 3 percent of its
total.
   Andriessen said exchanges between the two should grow in the
1990s.
   He indicated the EEC would not offer any trade concessions to the
Soviet Union, saying that the accord would include ``most favored
nation'' treatment under international trade rules established by
the General Agreement on Tariffs and Trade.
   The agreement also would offer management training, joint
ventures and ``other forms of business cooperation,'' Andriessen
said.
   The EEC has signed bilateral trade agreements with Hungary and
Czechoslovakia and is in advanced talks for accords with Poland and
Bulgaria.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890608-0246 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-08-89 1046EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f PM-TrumpShuttle 3rdLd-Writethru   06-08 0743</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Trump Shuttle, 3rd Ld-Writethru,0763</SECOND>
<HEAD>Trump Shuttle Takes Off With a Flair</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 7th graf to CORRECT to accordion, sted accordian.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARCY GORDON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   From the Mozart-playing string quartet at
LaGuardia Airport to the miniature bottles of champagne handed out
in flight, Donald Trump didn't spare the glitter in launching his
new Northeast shuttle airline today.
   The New York-to-Washington flight of the Trump Shuttle was one of
the inaugural flights for the service that Trump acquired from
strikebound Eastern Airlines.
   Trump wasn't able to meet his advertised claim for getting the
flights off on time _ the scheduled 8 a.m. flight from LaGuardia to
Washington took off at about 8:17 a.m., while another flight from
Washington to New York was delayed by weather and heavy traffic _
but he did live up to his reputation for hoopla.
   At LaGuardia, a string quartet played Mozart near a buffet
crammed with mimosas and muffins. During the flight, which was
packed with reporters and regular travelers, attendants dressed in
new navy-and-burgundy uniforms handed out miniature bottles of
champagne.
   ``The name `Trump' carries a lot of weight,'' said flight
attendant Denise McCain, 33, an 11-year Eastern veteran. ``We're all
very excited about it.''
   At one point the billionaire businessman, who sat in the front
row with Trump Shuttle President Bruce Nobles, grabbed the public
address microphone to announce, ``Ladies and gentlemen, this is your
flight attendant.''
   Passengers arriving at Washington's National Airport were met by
a strings and accordion quintet, whose statuesque, blond violin
player mugged with Trump for photographers.
   The shuttle's rebirth had been trumpted for days by newspaper and
radio ads, touting Trump's plans to rejuvenate the business that had
been Eastern's only profitable enterprise before the company was
crippled by a strike that began March 4.
   Trump formally closed the deal in a signing ceremony at his
opulent Plaza Hotel, buying the shuttle from strikebound Eastern
Airlines for $365 million.
   The real estate and casino tycoon, with trademark bravado,
pledged to make the Trump Shuttle ``the best transportation system
in the world.''
   ``I want the shuttle to be a diamond,'' Trump said. He promised
to spend as much as $2 million on each plane for refurbishing,
safety checks and painting of the new color scheme: white fuselage
with red, black and gold stripes, the name ``Trump'' above the
stripes and a red ``T'' on the tail.
   Trump, who will function as chairman and chief executive officer,
called it ``the largest scheduled airline startup in U.S. airline
history,'' with 21 Boeing 727 jets and more than 1,000 employees.
Many of the pilots, flight attendants and mechanics worked for
Eastern before the strike and were tentatively hired by Trump
starting last fall.
   The shuttle, which links New York with Washington and Boston, is
used mainly by business travelers. It was Eastern's only consistent
profit maker before the March 4 strike. Miami-based Eastern filed
for bankruptcy protection from creditors on March 9.
   U.S. Bankruptcy Judge Burton R. Lifland formally approved the
sale to Trump on May 25, after America West Airlines withdrew its
rival $415 million buyout proposal because of failure to arrange
financing.
   The Eastern shuttle lost many passengers to Pan Am Corp.'s rival
service because of the strike and now has less than a 25 percent
market share.
   Full-page ads for the Trump Shuttle in The New York Times, the
Washington Post and other East Coast papers Wednesday blared the
message in giant letters: ``Starting Tomorrow, Business Travel Will
Be Back on Schedule.''
   The ads, as well as a similar radio version, announced that the
Trump Shuttle will begin service at precisely 7 a.m. EDT today.
   ``Which means that now, you can go back to the time you prefer
traveling _ on the hour,'' the newspaper ads read. ``What's more,
when we say on the hour, we mean on the hour. Seven a.m. does not
mean 7:01 a.m.'' Like Eastern did, Trump promises to roll out
another plane if the first one for a given hour is full.
   Pan Am's shuttle offers flights leaving on the half-hour.
   Not to be outdone, Pan Am launched the ``Corporate Jet Game,'' a
sweepstakes for passengers. The grand prize is free use of a 727 to
fly the winner and 25 guests to a weekend trip in Bermuda.
   ``We think that we can out-Trump Mr. Trump,'' said Pan Am
spokesman Jeff Kriendler. ``The battle will be won on service
considerations.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
