<FILEID>AP-NR-06-08-89 1143EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>s f BC-UAW-Chronology Adv11   06-08 0603</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-UAW-Chronology, Adv 11,0632</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv11</HEAD>
<HEAD>For release Sunday, June 11</HEAD>
<HEAD>Significant Dates In UAW History</HEAD>
<HEAD>With BC-UAW</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Here is a summary of major dates in the history of
the United Auto Workers union, as provided by the UAW's public
information department:
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   August 1935 _ American Federation of Labor charters the United
Automobile Workers union.
   Spring 1936 _ UAW bolts from the AFL and becomes independent. It
later is a co-founder of the Congress of Industrial Organizations.
   December 1936 _ UAW begins a sit-down strike at General Motors
Corp. plants in Flint. The strike spreads to other GM plants in the
United States and Canada.
   February 1937 _ Workers return to their jobs at GM plants after a
one-page agreement is signed recognizing the UAW as the bargaining
agent for GM employees.
   February 1937 _ UAW ends a 15-week strike with the signing of the
first contract with an agricultural implement company, J.I. Case.
   March 1937 _ A sit-down strike begins at Chrysler Corp. plants,
ending in union recognition.
   June 1940 _ GM and the union agree to a contract that includes,
for the first time, paid vacations.
   April 1941 _ The UAW strikes Ford Motor Co. and gains
bargaining-agent recognition.
   November 1945 _ GM is struck for 113 days for first postwar pay
raise.
   May 1948 _ The UAW and GM agree to the nation's first major
cost-of-living protection clause.
   September 1949 _ UAW and Ford agree to the nation's first
employer-paid and jointly administered pension fund.
   February 1950 _ A ``closed shop'' clause is negotiated between
the UAW and GM, making union membership mandatory.
   May 1950 _ A 104-day strike at Chrysler results in a
hospitalization and medical program.
   April 1954 _ UAW strikes Kohler Co. in Kohler, Wis., a plumbing
products, small engine and generator maker, in what becomes the
nation's longest walkout. It's settled five years later.
   June 1955 _ UAW and Ford agree to ``supplemental unemployment
benefits,'' the nation's first program to stabilize workers' incomes
during layoffs.
   August 1961 _ American Motors Corp. and UAW sign agreement
setting up principle of profit sharing.
   November 1970 _ After a 10-week strike, UAW and GM agree to the
industry's first paid Christmas-New Year's week shutdown.
   Early 1980s _ UAW agrees to a series of concession contracts with
Chrysler Corp. as the automaker flirts with bankruptcy. Chrysler is
bailed out by federal loan guarantees.
   Early 1982 _ UAW agrees to concessions contracts at Ford and GM.
   September 1984 _ UAW selectively strikes GM assembly plants,
resulting in job-security gains. An agreement with Ford follows a
month later.
   March 1985 _ Most UAW members in Canada set up their own union,
called the Canadian Auto Workers. Only UAW Local 251 in Wallaceburg,
Ontario, stays with the U.S. union.
   June 1985 _ UAW and management of New United Motor Manufacturing
Inc. in Fremont, Calif., a joint venture between GM and Toyota Motor
Corp. of Japan, sign an agreement calling on management cuts before
hourly workers are laid off.
   November 1985 _ UAW completes organizing drives for 22,000
Michigan state employees.
   October 1985 _ Chrysler workers approve a contract that brings
unionized employees at the Big Three automaker into pay parity.
   Autumn 1987 _ UAW agrees on new three-year contracts with Ford
and General Motors that strengthens job security language.
   May 1988 _ Chrysler workers approve a contract providing for a
signing bonus, improved job security language and an expiration date
common with GM and Ford, Sept. 14, 1990.
   June 1988 _ Jai Alai ballplayers in New England choose UAW as
their bargaining agent.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End adv for Sunday, June 11</NOTE>
</DOC>
