<FIRST>u f PM-BoardofTrade Open   06-08 0311</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Board of Trade, Open,0323</SECOND>
<HEAD>Wheat Price Firm Despite China Turmoil</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Grain and soybean futures opened mixed this
morning on the Chicago Board of Trade despite the continued concern
over conditions in China.
   Early trading indicates wheat prices are firming, although
analysts say traders are worried about delays in the shipment of
wheat on order by the Chinese. But the market is largely ignoring
the turmoil still evident in that nation and the possible impact it
could have on future grain sales.
   Favorable weather outlooks are expected to put pressure on corn
and soybean prices.
   However, soybean futures could get a boost from a threatened
sales boycott by Brazilian farmers who say they are worried about
their government's exchange rate policy. In addition, dockworkers in
Brazil are threatening another nationwide port strike, which would
hamper that soybean exports.
   A strike by dockworkers last month shut down most Brazilian ports.
   In early trading, wheat was a { cent to 2 cents higher, with the
contract for delivery in July at $3.84 a bushel; corn was } cent to
1{ cents lower with July at $2.55} a bushel; oats were a { cent to 1
cent higher with July at $1.63 a bushel; soybeans were 1 cent lower
to 8 cents higher with July at $7.19 a bushel.
   Livestock prices were mostly lower and meat futures were mixed in
early trading on the Chicago Mercantile Exchange.
   Live cattle were .33 cent lower to .23 cent higher with June at
69.05 cents a pound; feeder cattle were .15 cent lower to .13 cent
higher with August at 78.87 cents a pound; hogs were .05 cent to .18
cent lower with June at 48.45 cents a pound; frozen pork bellies
were .23 cent to .30 cent higher with July at 32 cents a pound.
   Livestock and meat futures settled higher Wednesday.
</TEXT>
