<FIRST>u f PM-Time-Paramount 1stLd-Writethru   06-08 0799</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Time-Paramount, 1st Ld - Writethru,0822</SECOND>
<HEAD>Time, Warner Weigh Options in Wake of Paramount Bid for Time</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 6th graf pvs, That bid...with 2 new grafs to UPDATE stock
prices.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SKIP WOLLENBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Time Inc. and Warner Communciations Inc. have an
array of options to protect their planned merger deal despite
Paramount Communications Inc.'s $10.7 billion buyout offer for Time.
   Securities analysts expressed little doubt that Time would resist
the unsolicited tender offer that Paramount launched only 2{ weeks
before shareholders are to vote on the Time-Warner merger that would
create the world's largest media and entertainment concern.
   Top executives of both Time and Warner were said to be
unavailable Wednesday for comment on what course they intend to take.
   Peter Appert, media analyst at C.J. Lawrence, Morgan Grenfell
Inc., said he expects Time officials ``will be pretty tough about
trying to retain their independence.''
   Paramount, the entertainment and publishing concern formerly
called Gulf &amp; Western Inc., said late Tuesday it was launching a
tender offer of $175 in cash for each of Time's shares.
   That bid prompted heavy trading Wednesday in the stock of all
three companies. Time jumped $44 to close at $170 a share in
consolidated New York Stock Exchange trading, while Warner rose
$1.75 to $53.50 a share and Paramount rose 75 cents to $54.75 a
share.
   At mid-day today, Time was down $2.75 to $167.75, Warner was up
$1.12{ at $54.62{ and Paramount ws up $2.12{ at $56.87{.
   Among the options securities analysts said Time was likely to be
considering were making its own tender offer for Warner or turning
the tables on Paramount by making a ``Pac-Man'' takeover bid for the
uninvited suitor.
   Analysts said Time previously arranged a $5 billion line of
credit that could be used if a competing bidder emerged. The down
side is that a buyout would dilute Time's earnings by saddling it
with debt.
   They said Time could exercise of any of several takeover
defenses, including a ``poison-pill'' that would make stock
available to its shareholders at a bargain rate, making a hostile
takeover more expensive.
   Time and Warner also could buy stakes in each other under terms
of their merger plan, a move that would further dilute their stock
and make a takeover of either of them more costly.
   John Reidy, media analyst for Drexel Burnham Lambert Inc., said
he doesn't think the Paramount offer necessarily dooms the
Time-Warner merger plan. But he said it is ``hard to envisage a
shareholder vote taking place in two weeks while the Paramount offer
is outstanding.''
   Warner and Time shareholders are scheduled to vote June 23 on the
merger.
   Paramount filed a lawsuit in Delaware Chancery Court seeking to
block Time and Warner from exercising contingency plans designed to
deter uninvited biddders from interfering with their merger. But a
judge declined Wednesday to immediately grant Paramount's requests.
   Also Wednesday, Warner said it had filed suit in New York State
Supreme Court against Citibank, seeking an order that would prevent
the bank from providing or arranging the $14 billion in financing
that Paramount said the bank plans to arrange for its bid. The sum
includes the cost of buying Time's shares, refinancing debt and
other costs.
   Warner said it had an agreement with Citibank under which the
bank had agreed not to help finance an unsolicted offer that would
interfere with the merger between Warner and Time.
   In a statement, Citibank's parent, Citicorp, said it was not
aware of ``any violation of any agreement with Warner.''
   Paramount Chairman Martin Davis met privately with securities
analysts Wednesday, saying that while the deal would result in
``significantly lower'' earnings in the near term, the chance to buy
Time was ``a once-in-a-lifetime opportunity to maximize Paramount
Communication's long-term potential.''
   He told the analysts he has no plans to sell any assets.
   Time, a publishing and cable giant, may have a tough job
explaining to its shareholders how the proposed stock swap merger
with Warner would be a better deal than the $175 a share in cash
that Paramount is offering.
   Under the planned Time-Warner merger, Time shareholders would get
a share in the new company for each share they currently own while
Warner shareholders would get 0.465 share of the new company for
each Warner share.
   J. Kendrick Noble, media analyst for PaineWebber Inc., said he
estimated the combined company's stock would trade at about $110 a
share.
   But he said that figure is not strictly comparable with the $175
a share price Paramount is offering, because anyone taking that
offer would face a capital gains tax and would have to give up their
stock to boot.
   ``Some credit has to be give to the idea of continuing to be an
equity investor,'' he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
