<FIRST>r f BC-S&amp;LTakeovers     06-08 0134</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-S&amp;L Takeovers,0139</SECOND>
<HEAD>Government Takes Over Two More Savings Institutions</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: also on general news wires.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Federal regulators took over two more savings
institutions Thursday _ one in Ohio and another in Pennsylvania _
bringing the total under government control to 221 in 32 states.
   The two institutions are Civic Savings Bank in Portsmouth, Ohio,
with $101 million in assets, and Horizon Financial in Southampton,
Pa., with $2.5 billion in assets.
   The Federal Deposit Insurance Corp., at President Bush's
direction, has been taking over some insolvent S&amp;Ls since early
February. The goal is to minimize losses until Congress provides the
money to close them or to subsidize their sale to new owners.
   The FDIC plans to take over about 60 more institutions in the
next several weeks, officials have indicated.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890608-0256 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-08-89 1321EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-BusinessInvestment Bjt   06-08 0541</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Business Investment, Bjt,0559</SECOND>
<HEAD>Spending to Expand Business Production Seen Rising</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: also on general news wires.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN D. McCLAIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   American businesses plan a strong 6.5 percent
increase in plant and equipment spending this year, the government
said Thursday, and economists said the investments would help
economic expansion while tending to limit inflation.
   Analysts said much of the spending will involve equipment that
would permit businesses to modernize their production capabilities,
thereby reducing both costs and prices.
   According to the Commerce Department survey, completed in May,
business investment is now estimated at $451.43 billion for 1989, up
from $423.69 billion in 1988. The numbers are adjusted for inflation.
   Although the economy has been slowing this year, business
spending plans have been expanding.
   In an initial survey completed last December, businesses told the
department they planned a 5.9 percent increase in expansion and
modernization spending this year. A survey completed in March showed
the forecast rising to 6.3 percent.
   ``Just about all of the increase is projected in equipment rather
than physical plants,'' according to Irwin Kellner, chief economist
for Manufacturers Hanover in New York.
   ``This is good, in the sense that it shows that industry is aware
that it has to improve product quality and reduce input costs,'' he
said. ``To the extent that industry is more productive, it will hold
down inflation.''
   The Federal Reserve has been putting upward pressure on interest
rates for 15 months as it attempted to slow the economy and ease
inflation.
   The spending forecast suggests the slowdown is not about to turn
into recession.
   ``Basically this is a plus for the economy both in terms of
continued expansion and, over the longer time, helping relieve
pressure on capacity and therefore limit the extent that price
pressures will accelerate,'' said David M. Jones, chief economist
for Aubrey G. Lanston &amp; Co. in New York.
   Both Jones and Kellner said one drawback to the increased
spending is that much of the new equipment is expected to be
imported.
   ``So even as businesses become even more productive on the one
side,'' Kellner said, ``on the other, they're adding to the balance
of trade deficit.''
   But at the same time, Jones said, much of the spending to
increase capacity is to meet expanding orders for U.S. exports.
   Capital spending grew 10.1 percent in 1988 as companies rushed to
expand production to meet rising export demand.
   That was the sharpest increase since a 16.6 percent hike in 1984,
when businesses were still recovering from the 1981-82 recession.
Since then, spending fell 3.9 percent in 1986 but rose 2.3 percent
in 1987.
   Business investment in the manufacturing sector was forecast to
increase 3.6 percent to $170.54 billion this year, compared to a
12.8 percent rise in 1988. That includes a 1.4 percent hike in
industries producing durable goods, those expected to last three
years or more. Non-durable spending was expected to rise 5.7 percent.
   Non-manufacturing spending in such industries as mining and
transportation was seen rising 8.4 percent to $280.89 billion,
compared with last year's 8.4 percent increase.
   Before adjusting for inflation, 1989 plant and equipment spending
is expected to rise by 9.9 percent to $472.08 billion, down from
10.3 percent in 1988.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
