<DOCNO> AP890608-0257 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-08-89 1336EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>s f BC-UAW Adv11   06-08 1200</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-UAW, Adv 11,1239</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv11</HEAD>
<HEAD>For release Sunday, June 11</HEAD>
<HEAD>Autoworkers Union Facing Challenges, Internal Dissent As Convention
Looms</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto DT5 of June 7</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Retransmitting to restore advance slugline</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By FREDERICK STANDISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Born in protest 54 years ago, the United Auto
Workers union today advocates constructive teamwork with company
bosses and it bargains contracts for professionals who range from
clerks to jai alai ballplayers.
   The 1 million member union is discovering, as have manufacturers
and other labor organizations, that peaceful coexistence and
diversification can be keys to survival.
   The transition has come at a price.
   The UAW is taking an increasingly active role in running
companies, from the board room to the factory floor. This has shaken
the workings of a labor organization that up to now has largely
avoided the factionalism plaguing some sister unions.
   As UAW members prepare for a convention later this month, their
agenda will include how to address a growing dissident movement that
claims the union has forgotten the lessons of history.
   During the past three years, the New Directions movement has
grown within the UAW urging the organization's leaders to honor the
axiom _ managers manage and workers work.
   New Directions leader Jerry Tucker says the union is getting too
chummy with management in developing team approaches to the job and
assisting with problem-solving on the plant floor.
   It goes deeper than that, he says.
   ``I've been trying to force a debate on fundamentals from the
start of this thing'' about five years ago, Tucker says. ``I'm
relentless in my pursuit of answers to why certain hallowed
principles have to be discarded. And if they have to be discarded in
favor of corporatist activity, what's in it for us?''
   Jobs, says UAW President Owen Bieber. As times change, so must
the union.
   That doesn't mean the UAW isn't prepared to fight companies. It's
been building up a strike fund, which now totals $740 million and
pays $100 a week and insurance coverage per worker during walkout.
   ``They came up with the slogan of New Directions,'' he says. ``I
must say that I fail to see that. I sort of equate them to George
Bush _ I don't know what that program is because nobody's explained
that program.''
   The drive of New Directions really isn't new at all, says David
Cole, director of the Office for the Study of Automotive
Transportation at the University of Michigan.
   ``New Directions, despite their name, is very much oriented to
the old ways,'' he says. The loosely knit group claims widespread
shop-level support but declines to estimate it in numbers.
   In one sense, labor specialists agree, the union will benefit
from the debate New Directions is forcing. The movement is by far
the most serious and most public challenge to the UAW leadership
since the union's founding in Flint, Mich., on Aug. 26, 1935.
   ``It's good for the union to have a debate,'' says David Bensman,
director of the graduate program in labor studies at Rutgers
University in New Brunswick, N.J. ``When you have people who are
critical, it forces or gives the leadership more incentive to
explain its policies to the members.''
   That debate comes as the union looks outside the automobile
industry for membership growth. The UAW has organized some state
workers in Michigan, university staff in New England and jai alai
players in Connecticut, Florida and Rhode Island.
   For years, it has represented aerospace, agricultural equipment
and clerical workers.
   Riki Lasa, a professional jai alai player and president of UAW
Local 8868, said his organization talked with other unions,
including the United Food and Commercial Workers and the Hotel and
Restaurant Employees, before deciding in June 1988 to affiliate with
the UAW.
   ``They spoke about the democracy within the union that we, the
players, make our decisions,'' Lasa says. The 500 players are
continuing a strike that began April 14, 1988 over claims that
management violated federal labor laws.
   The jai alai players are seeking their first contract with
management.
   The UAW also has been looking outside the auto industry in
advertising campaigns that have cost the union $20 million during
the 1980s.
   The most recent campaign, running in large media markets and
costing the union about $4 million, reminds Americans of labor's
role in building the economy and criticizes financiers to make quick
profits on takeovers.
   Some doubt the ad's effectiveness.
   ``They probably make the people who run them feel better,'' says
ad analyst James Dougherty of County Securities in New York.
   The UAW's outside recruiting success hasn't been matched in the
newest segment of the auto industry _ ``transplants'' from abroad.
   Japanese companies, and joint ventures between Japanese and U.S.
automakers, have been erecting carmaking plants in the United States
since 1982. Some now are expanding.
   The UAW has organized workers at the Mazda Motor Corp. plant in
Flat Rock, Mich., and two joint ventures _ the New United Motor
Manufacturing Inc. factory by General Motors Corp. and Toyota Motor
Corp., and the Chrysler-Mitsubishi Motors Corp. Diamond-Star Motors
Corp. plant in Bloomington, Ill.
   But workers in Toyota's Georgetown, Ky.; Honda Motor Corp.'s
Marysville, Ohio, and Nissan Motor Corp.'s Smyrna, Tenn., assembly
plants aren't unionized.
   ``Nobody will admit this,'' Bieber says, ``but there can't be any
secret as to why they located any of these plants out there in the
hinterlands. It's also no accident that most of the people who got
hired probably had their ancestry checked through at least three
generations to find out whether anyone ever belonged to a union or
not.
   ``We've had an extremely tough time in organizing, and Honda was
a good example,'' he said. In March 1986 in Marysville, on the eve
of a representation election, the UAW _ fearing defeat _ withdrew
its bid to unionize the workers.
   Harley Shaiken, a labor professor at the University of California
at San Diego, says worker boredom could help bring more transplants
into the union fold.
   ``I think they will be organized, I think when they will be
organized is hard to gauge,'' he says.
   In the late 1970s, the UAW had more than 1.5 million members.
Today, it stands at 1 million, a decline that is a trend in
organized labor. Union workers also have become more conservative,
partly because of the popularity of former President Reagan.
   ``Reagan had a tremendous hold on our membership,'' said former
UAW President Douglas Fraser, now a professor at Wayne State
University in Detroit.
   ``He was kind of a macho man and the blue-collar worker is sort
of a macho fellow and that had a great attraction for them.
   ``Also I think that some of our members thought that the union
leadership and the liberals were too caught up in equal rights, and
the other factor is that I believe that as their income increases
their values change.''
   The base hourly wage for an auto assembler is about $14.50 an
hour, among the highest of any U.S. factory worker today. When
health and other benefits are included, annual compensation is about
$37,000, more with overtime. Of that, workers pay the equivalent of
two hours pay per month in dues.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End adv for Sunday, June 11</NOTE>
