<SECOND>BC-Britain-Stocks, 1st Ld-Writethru,0183</SECOND>
<HEAD>London Shares Sharply Higher</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: UPDATES with closing prices</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Stock prices closed sharply higher in heavy trading
Thursday on the London Stock Exchange amid a favorable economic
background and some institutional buying.
   The Financial Times-Stock Exchange 100-share index finished 25.5
points, or 1.2 percent, higher at 2,143.4.
   The index moved in positive territory throughout the day,
recording a minimum gain of 12.4 points shortly after the opening
and then surging as much as 36.6 points around midday.
   Volume was heavy, as 782.3 million shares changed hands. But much
of the turnover was concentrated in a handful of special situation
stocks. By comparison, volume was 481 million shares Wednesday.
   A steady pound and a recovery in long-term British government
bond prices, following last week's sell-off, provided a favorable
background for equity prices to move higher, dealers said.
   In addition, some institutions stepped in with selective buying.
Various takeover rumors also made the rounds, centering on some of
the market's larger capitalized companies, pushing up prices and
inflating turnover in selected stocks.
</TEXT>
