<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The stock market pushed ahead today, squeezing a
little more mileage out of its recent rally fueled by takeover news
and rumors and declining interest rates.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials, up 31.62 points over the
last two sessions, rose another 6.25 to 2,518.57 by 2 p.m. on Wall
Street.
   Gainers outnumbered losers by about 7 to 6 in nationwide trading
of New York Stock Exchange-listed issues, with 751 up, 649 down and
541 unchanged.
   New takeover bids this week for Time Inc. and LIN Broadcasting
touched off buying in a wide range of stocks thought to be possible
future candidates for acquisitions or buyouts.
   Eastman Kodak, said to be a potential target, climbed } to 51\.
   Time stock, meanwhile, dropped 2} to 167\ and LIN lost 2{ to 127
in the over-the-counter market after both experienced dramatic
runups in Wednesday's trading.
   Burlington Resources, the volume leader among NYSE issues, fell
2\ to 44[. Pennzoil, which had been considered a possible bidder for
Burlington, sold its stake of 11.7 million shares in a block at 45\.
   Pennzoil, which reaped a profit on the investment, gained 1 to 81.
   Beyond the takeover hubbub, analysts say the market has benefited
from signs this week that the Federal Reserve might be starting a
change of course in its credit policy.
   After more than a year of tightening credit conditions, the Fed
is widely believed to have made an initial step toward easing, by
permitting a decline in the interest rate on federal funds, or
overnight loans between banks.
   Energy stocks were mostly lower amid skepticism that members of
the Organization of Petroleum Exporting Countries would adhere to
new oil production quotas set this week.
   Exxon dropped { to 43}; Texaco ] to 49{; Amoco 1 to 43}; Atlantic
Richfield 1} to 91|, and Chevron 1[ to 53}.
   The NYSE's composite index of all its listed common stocks edged
up .02 to 182.36. At the American Stock Exchange, the market value
index was up .72 at 365.13.
   Volume on the Big Board came to 157.19 million shares with two
hours to go.
