<FILEID>AP-NR-06-08-89 1431EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-OPEC Bjt   06-08 0637</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-OPEC, Bjt,0656</SECOND>
<HEAD>Kuwait Says It Won't Abide By OPEC Accord</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SALLY JACOBSEN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>VIENNA, Austria (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Kuwait said Thursday it will pump extra
crude in the coming months in defiance of the latest OPEC production
accord, and other cartel members could follow suit.
   Just a day after an agreement was reached, Kuwaiti Oil Minister
Ali Khalifa al-Sabah said his country has temporarily withdrawn from
OPEC's quota system because other ministers failed to increase its
share of total production in the last half of the year.
   Other members of the 13-nation Organization of Petroleum
Exporting Countries appeared to accept Kuwait's decision to cheat on
the new agreement.
   In fact, the United Arab Emirates and a few others were
considered likely to ignore their output limits. They, too, wanted a
bigger share of the production pie.
   But Algeria's Sadek Boussena said, ``I think that all countries
have committed themselves to something. That's what's positive.''
   It was Kuwait's insistence on a higher share of increased
production that stalled negotiations for a new accord.
   Sabah said he wrote in the new agreement that he would not feel
bound by his new quota. But he also told reporters that Kuwait
``will use that freedom (from the quota system) very, very
responsibly.''
   In restraining supply in the past, he said, Kuwait has
``sacrificed more than the others for a very, very long time. ...
But there is a limit to what we can do.''
   Sabah said Kuwait intended to produce 1.35 million barrels a day
in the coming months, noting that it is ``almost physically
impossible'' to pump less than that in part because of commitments
to long-time customers. Kuwait's new new quota is 1.09 million
barrels, and its current supply is estimated at nearly 2 million
barrels.
   Saudi Arabia's Hisham Nazer indicated to a small group of
reporters that Kuwait's extra sales would be tolerated as long as
they did not exceed 1.35 million barrels a day.
   Indonesia's Ginandjar Kartasasmita noted Kuwait would have to
make cutbacks to come down to the promised level.
   ``The accord is even better than what we could have dreamed of,''
he said. ``This is the maximum that we could have.''
   After six days of bargaining, the cartel agreed to boost its
supply ceiling to 19.5 million barrels a day in the July-December
period. While that is up a million barrels from the current official
level, analysts estimated output in recent weeks has risen to 21
million barrels a day.
   The ministers agreed to divide the extra sales proportionately
among all members. To meet the new ceiling, some countries will have
to cut production.
   Nazer said he would have liked to see the ceiling upped to 20
million barrels a day in the last half of the year, but he noted
that ``several of the OPEC members were just afraid it may have an
impact on price.''
   The ministers said in a statement the ceiling could be raised to
20 million barrels a day or more, effective Oct. 1, if demand
remained strong.
   ``I honestly feel that demand in the market is much stronger,''
Nazer said.
   Boussena agreed, saying that if prices hold steady, ``there is no
reason not to add another 500,000 barrels a day'' to the cap.
   OPEC retained in the new agreement its benchmark price of $18 a
barrel. The average price of a basket of seven crudes monitored by
OPEC was nearly $17.70 a barrel last week.
   The new accord was designed to keep a firm grip on production so
that prices would remain robust. But oil markets reacted skeptically
to the cartel's ability to limit output. U.S. crude prices initially
tumbled but recovered somewhat on Thursday.
   OPEC members are: Algeria, Ecuador, Gabon, Indonesia, Iran, Iraq,
Kuwait, Libya, Nigeria, Qatar, Saudi Arabia, United Arab Emirates
and Venezuella.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890608-0261 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-08-89 1438EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-China-ForeignBusiness     06-08 0674</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-China-Foreign Business,0697</SECOND>
<HEAD>China Turmoil Damages Foreign Business Confidence</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LARRY THORSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Foreign businesses' confidence in China has been
shattered by the eruption of violence.
   ``It will take years to restore credibility,'' Jan VanDenBerg, an
economist at Merrill Lynch &amp; Co., said Thursday in Tokyo.
   In Washington, the United States-China Business Council said
Thursday that commercial and economic relations between the
countries ``have been disrupted and could suffer long-term damage.''
   The business council said its members ``deplore the violent
suppression and wanton killing of pro-democracy demonstrators in
Beijing'' and said the countries should ``preserve the links between
us until they can again be expanded.''
   While some businesses away from Beijing continue to do business
as normal, many report they have been crippled by workers staying
home and expatriates leaving the country.
   Many companies that had been attracted by China's cheap labor and
huge potential market have been forced into a wait-and-see attitude,
hoping their investments will survive.
   Kumigai Gumi Co., a major Japanese construction company, has
stopped work on a 51-story skyscraper in Beijing because of the
danger. ``We don't know when we can resume the project,'' an
official said. ``It doesn't look like it's going to be any time
soon.''
   But Mattel Inc. said it is continuing to operate two toy plants
in Guangdong Province, 1,500 miles from Beijing, which make clothes
for Barbie dolls and some Disney-theme pre-school toys.
   McDonnell Douglas Corp. ordered 51 employees and dependents at an
airliner assembly plant outside Shanghai to leave the country
Tuesday, said Garth Chang, Douglas' top Asia-based executive in Hong
Kong.
   Workers weren't aware of the turmoil that had engulfed the
country because of the government's news blackout, Chang said.
   Mac Jeffery, spokesman for International Business Machines Corp.
in Tokyo, said the company has 120 employees in China supplying and
maintaining computers. Half are foreigners, he said, and all but two
of those had left China by Thursday.
   ``The office is technically open, but if someone needs service,
it would depend on the situation whether we could help,'' he said.
   ``I wonder what business is to be had,'' Jeffery added.
   About 30 American staffers of an Occidental Petroleum Corp. coal
mine in north-central China were on a U.S. government-chartered
evacuation flight from Beijing Thursday. They declined to give their
names to a reporter at Tokyo's Narita airport, but said there had
not been any trouble at the mine.
   The danger of being on Beijing streets caused Sanyo Electric Co.
to tell some 100 workers to remain at home and not report to their
jobs at a joint venture plant in the capital making electronic
calculators, Sanyo said in Tokyo.
   Nippon Steel Corp. spokesman Takeshi Itagaki said the company had
no problems at a project giving technical assistance to a steel
plant near Shanghai, and its exports of steel products to 10 Chinese
cities were going ahead normally.
   Yokogawa Electric Corp., a leading Japanese manufacturer of
industrial instruments, shut a joint venture factory in Xian, Shaaxi
province, early this week, said spokesman Takeshi Mizuno.
   The 260 workers ``are participating in rallies in protest against
the military suppression in Beijing,'' Mizuno said. ``Even students
and workers from other factories are coming to call for a series of
major protest rallies. ... Some circles in the city are calling for
a general strike.''
   Japanese Foreign Minister Hiroshi Mitsuzuka, speaking in
Parliament Thursday, said, ``It cannot be denied that the
international image of China has been impaired a lot.''
   Singapore, where for five years the government has urged
businessmen to boost trade ties with China, also expressed worry
that the violence could damage China's ``open door'' economic policy
of welcoming foreign investment.
   After hearing of the violence early this week, Prime Minister Lee
Kwan Yew said, ``We hope wiser counsels will prevail to pursue
conciliation, so that the Chinese people can resume the progress
which the open door policies have brought them.''
   The turmoil has caused some price jumps for commodities exported
by China, such as peanuts, soybeans and silk cocoons.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
