<FIRST>u f BC-BoardofTrade Close   06-08 0246</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Board of Trade, Close,0256</SECOND>
<HEAD>Grains and Soybeans Lower</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Grain and soybean futures prices closed mostly
lower Thursday on the Chicago Board of Trade.
   Wheat futures, which have been on a downswing because of the
political turmoil in China, were off for the third consecutive
trading session. Analysts say the problems in China may result in no
new orders by that country for U.S. wheat.
   ``There was no feature to today's trading,'' said Frank Kouba, an
analyst with Shearson Lehman Hutton Inc. in Chicago. ``There was
some concern over China and additional wheat sales, but the market
lacked any real direction.''
   Soybean futures were mixed, getting a boost from a threatened
sales boycott by Brazilian farmers who say they are worried about
their government's exchange rate policy.
   In addition, dockworkers in Brazil are threatening another
nationwide port strike, which would hamper that nation's soybean
exports, Kouba said. A strike by dockworkers last month shut down
most Brazilian ports.
   Corn prices were pressured by light demand and reports of
improved growing conditions in major crop areas.
   At the close, wheat was a \ cent to 2 cents lower with the
contract for delivery in July at $3.81 a bushel; corn was 2{ cents
to 5\ cents lower with July at $2.53 a pound; oats were a { cent to
2 cents higher with July at $1.64{ a bushel; soybeans were 5} cents
lower to 3 cents higher with July at $7.14 a bushel.
</TEXT>
