<FILEID>AP-NR-06-08-89 0613EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>a f BC-PersonalFile-Sorrell Adv11   06-08 0917</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Personal File-Sorrell, Adv 11,0947</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv11</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Sunday, June 11</HEAD>
<HEAD>Martin Sorrell: Marketing Maven Builds Ad Empire Through Takeovers</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto planned</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SKIP WOLLENBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   When Martin Sorrell engineered an industry record
$566 million purchase of the parent of the J. Walter Thompson
advertising agency two summers ago, he called it the ``opportunity
of a lifetime.''
   But opportunity seems to have knocked more often than the
bespectacled 44-year-old financial maven foresaw. His WPP Group PLC
verges on a larger takeover, the $864 million buyout of another
Madison Avenue icon, Ogilvy Group.
   In his three years at WPP, the Cambridge- and Harvard-educated
son of a British retailing executive has built a global
communications empire.
   He's done it by adding more than three dozen advertising, public
relations and marketing services firms to the framework of a company
that still makes wire shopping baskets and plastic dish drainers.
   The Ogilvy deal, expected to close within weeks, will make WPP
the world's second biggest advertising and marketing company,
trailing only Saatchi &amp; Saatchi Co. PLC where Sorrell toiled nine
years as the top financial officer.
   Sorrell has said the Ogilvy purchase will make his company the
world's finest advertising and marketing services company, but
eschews any interest in surpassing Saatchi as the largest.
   His rapid rise to the top of the advertising-marketing industry
has left some people gushing at what they call his business genius
and others describing him as arrogant and vindictive.
   Sorrell has been embroiled in a bitter legal battle for more than
a year with a half dozen former executives of the ad agency Lord
Geller Federico Einstein that WPP acquired as part of the J. Walter
Thompson deal.
   The Lord Geller executives, including agency founders Richard
Lord and Arthur Einstein, walked out in March 1988 to form their own
agency after chafing under eight months of WPP ownership.
   Philip Geier, chairman of the advertising conglomerate
Interpublic Group of Cos., has criticized Sorrell for his
unsolicited advances against both Thompson and Ogilvy.
   He said WPP's assault on Ogilvy exposed Sorrell as a financial
gambler who has ``taken a major company that was doing fine and
leveraged it to the hilt.''
   WPP is using a combination of stock and debt to finance the
Ogilvy takeover. People close to Sorrell say Geier may be biased
since Interpublic failed in its eleventh-hour bid to wrest Ogilvy
from WPP's grasp by proposing a stock swap.
   Several top executives of the packaging, design, sales promotion
and corporate identity firms that WPP has acquired say they are
delighted with the deals. They speak glowingly of the opportunities
Sorrell created for their businesses by associating them with a
prestigious name like Thompson and by imposing financial discipline
they individually lacked.
   WPP's acquisition ``was the best thing that ever happened to
Reese,'' said Lynn Pounian, president of Reese Communications Co.
Inc., a 20-year-old marketing concern based in Arlington, Va.
   In a manner typical of Sorrell's approach in acquiring privately
held companies, WPP Group bought Reese in September 1987 for an
initial payment of $14 million in cash and a promise to pay up to
$21 million more depending on earnings performance over the next
several years.
   The approach, which Sorrell honed during his days at Saatchi,
enables WPP to hold onto the management of the companies it acquires
by giving them a continuing stake in the success of the firm.
   Sorrell stays out of the day-to-day operations of WPP's
companies, but has them file daily financial reports and holds them
accountable for meeting performance goals.
   ``The critical thing is what questions you ask,'' Sorrell said in
an interview following the Thompson acquisition in 1987. ``If you
ask certain things, people in giving you the answers will ask
themselves, `Why did they ask me that question?' Good things come
out of that if you are asking the right questions.''
   Reese's Pounian said officials at her company rarely had time to
ask themselves the financial questions Sorrell asks, and she
welcomes the discipline.
   ``Is it a picnic in the park every day? No. ... But the benefits
so outweigh the minor inconveniences that there is no question we
are in a better position than we would have been,'' she said.
   Sorrell, who pronounces his name with the accent on the first
syllable, was born on Valentine's Day in 1945. His father ran the
retail division of a large British industrial concern, and the
youngster worked in its credit department when he was 16. He studied
economics at Cambridge University and earned an MBA from Harvard.
   One Harvard classmate, Alabama real estate developer Still Hunter
Jr., remembers Sorrell as ``very incisive ... very bright'' and a
standout in finance. ``If he believed in something, he would
persist,'' Hunter recalls.
   After Harvard, Sorrell worked for Glendinning Associates, a
marketing consulting firm in Westport, Conn. Later bosses included
sports promoter Mark McCormack and food retailer and investor James
Gulliver, both in London.
   It was while working for Gulliver that he met the Saatchi
brothers. They hired Sorrell as their top financial officer in 1977
and the firm grew rapidly in the following nine years.
   Sorrell struck out on his own in 1986 as chief executive of Wire
&amp; Plastic Products, precursor of WPP Group.
   He lives in Hampstead, near the north London neighborhood where
he grew up. He and his wife have three sons, and Sorrell spends his
free time with them, sometimes skiing or playing cricket.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Sunday, June 11</NOTE>
</DOC>
