<DOCNO> AP890608-0267 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-08-89 1918EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f AM-AlleghenyInternational     06-08 0236</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Allegheny International,0245</SECOND>
<HEAD>Management Loses Reorganization Right</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PITTSBURGH (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal bankruptcy judge Thursday stripped
Allegheny International Inc.'s management of its exclusive right to
file a plan to bring the company out of Chapter 11 protection.
   Judge Joseph L. Cosetti's action means any creditor can file a
plan to compete with one filed by the company's management.
   Reasons for the decision were not given, but the move came after
the about 10 days after Allegheny International filed its fifth plan
since entering Chapter 11 in February 1988. Its unsecured creditors
are owed $220 million.
   Allegheny International's lenders and unsecured creditors
immediately said they would file reorganization plans of their own.
   Allegheny International's most recent plan was to bring its
Sunbeam Corp. subsidiary, the profitable small appliance maker that
includes virtually all of Allegheny's operating companies, out of
Chapter 11 bankruptcy separately from the parent company.
   Gary Blum, an attorney representing company stockholders, said
Cosetti's action ``just made getting the financing impossible'' for
the Sunbeam plan.
   The last reorganization plan for Sunbeam would have paid cash to
settle all of the approximately $240 million in claims pending
against the subsidiary. It would have left the Pittsburgh-based
parent still in bankruptcy court to haggle with creditors.
   After collapse of the fourth reorganization plan, Allegheny
International said the judge was so aggravated that he suspended
payment of most fees to attorneys and accountants involved in the
case.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
