<DOCNO> AP890608-0270 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-08-89 1731EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-OilPrices     06-08 0360</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Oil Prices,0374</SECOND>
<HEAD>Crude, Gas Futures Finish Higher; Heating Oil Off</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Wholesale gasoline and crude oil prices rose
Thursday, rebounding from the previous session's sharp selloff.
   Home heating oil futures finished lower, depressed by sluggish
demand typical for this time of year.
   On the New York Mercantile Exchange, the contract for July
delivery of unleaded gasoline rose 0.66 cent to 64 cents a gallon,
after Wednesday's loss of 1.60 cents.
   The July contract for West Texas Intermediate, the benchmark
grade of U.S. crude oil, settled at $20 per 42-gallon barrel, a gain
of 33 cents for the day. The crude contract had dropped 79 cents
Wednesday.
   But the selling continued in the heating oil pits, although not
as aggressively as on Wednesday. July-delivery No.2 heating oil fell
by 0.05 cent to 48.66 a gallon, adding a minor amount to Wednesday's
loss of 2.29 cents.
   Jerry Samuels, an energy broker at Shearson Lehman Hutton Inc.,
attributed the buying of gasoline futures to renewed demand,
particularly for New York harbor delivery gasoline, at the beginning
of the peak summer driving season.
   ``As the value of gas moves up, so will crude,'' said Samuels.
``Heating oil got left in the dust, which is understandable from a
seasonal perspective.''
   Crude also got a boost from buying in reaction to the tumble
prices took Wednesday when the outcome of the OPEC meeting
disappointed the markets.
   Ministers of the 13-nation Organization of Petroleum Exporting
Countries ageed to boost the cartel's production ceiling to 19.5
million barrels a day in the July-December period.
   The new ceiling is 1 million barrels per day higher than the
current level but below the estimated daily output in recent weeks
of about 21 million barrels.
   The OPEC ministers also decided during their Vienna meeting to
divide the extra production proportionately among all members.
Analysts said this means that some countries will have to curtail
some pumping to keep within their self-imposed quotas.
   Kuwait and several other OPEC members have indicated they intend
to pump more crude than their quotas allow and energy brokers doubt
OPEC will be able to control production enough to maintain strong
prices.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
