<FIRST>u f AM-Dollar-Gold     06-08 0492</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Dollar-Gold,0515</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Mixed in Quiet Trading; Gold Lower</HEAD>
<HEAD>Precede LONDON BC</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER COY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar finished mixed against foreign
currencies Thursday in light trading ahead of Friday's release of
figures on U.S. wholesale price inflation.
   Gold prices moved lower.
   The dollar rose against the Japanese yen and French franc but
fell against other major currencies.
   Dealers said the dollar rose briefly against the West German mark
on rumors that U.S. citizens were injured or killed in China. The
dollar eased back after the U.S. State Department said it had no
information to confirm those reports.
   Secretary of State James A. Baker III said no U.S. citizens had
been killed in the violence and that only one had been injured.
   Traders were uncertain about how the dollar might be affected by
the Labor Department's report on the Producer Price Index for May.
   Cases could be made that either a big inflation increase or a
small one was good for the dollar, said Craig Sloane, a currency
analyst at Smith Barney, Harris Upham &amp; Co. On the other hand, he
said, the dollar also could fall in reaction to a big or small
increase.
   In Tokyo, where trading ends before Europe's business day begins,
the dollar rose 0.25 yen to a closing 143.05 yen. Later in London,
it was quoted at 143.32 yen. In New York the dollar rose to 143.25
Japanese yen from 142.84 on Wednesday.
   In London, the dollar gained against the British pound. It cost
$1.5735 to buy one pound, compared with $1.5815 late Wednesday. In
New York the pound rose against the dollar to $1.5773 from $1.5730.
   Other late dollar rates in New York, compared with late
Wednesday's rates, included: 1.9725 West German marks, down from
1.9735; 1.7085 Swiss francs, down from 1.7100; 1.1973 Canadian
dollars, down from 1.1975; 6.6910 French francs, up from 6.6867; and
1,435.5 Italian lire, down from 1,436.2.
   Other late dollar rates in Europe, compared with late Wednesday:
1.9770 West German marks, up from 1.9610; 1.7100 Swiss francs, up
from 1.6965; 6.7040 French francs, up from 6.6600; 2.2220 Dutch
guilders, up from 2.2138; 1,439.50 Italian lire, down from 1,441.00,
and 1.1967 Canadian dollars, unchanged.
   Gold moved lower in London to a late price of $373.25 per ounce,
from $375.65 Wednesday. In Zurich, the bid price was $374.35, down
15 cents from late Wednesday.
   Later on the Commodity Exchange in New York, gold bullion for
current delivery fell to $373.50 an ounce from $376.10. Republic
National Bank of New York said gold was bid at $372.80 an ounce as
of 4 p.m. EDT, down from $374 late Wednesday.
   Silver was quoted in London at a bid price of $5.44 a troy ounce,
up from Wednesday's $5.38. On New York's Comex, silver bullion for
current delivery fell to $5.443 an ounce from $5.464.
   Financial institutions were closed in Hong Kong on Thursday for
the Chinese Dragon Boat festival.
</TEXT>
