<DOCNO> AP890608-0274 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-08-89 1801EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-Grumman-China     06-08 0345</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Grumman-China,0364</SECOND>
<HEAD>40 Chinese Nationals Dismissed in Grumman Project</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAT MILTON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BETHPAGE, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Forty Chinese nationals were ordered banned
from Grumman's Long Island plant under President Bush's suspension
of military dealing with China, the company said Thursday.
   The Chinese nationals, mostly engineers, were working on a
project to modernize electronics in the Chinese fighter plane.
   The Chinese were notified at a meeting at Grumman corporate
headquarters on Wednesday that they would not be permitted on
Grumman property after 5 p.m. that day, said the spokesman Robert
Harwood.
   They were told to turn in the identification badges allowing them
on the premises in Bethpage.
   As of Thursday, they were waiting instructions from their
government, Harwood said.
   Grumman is the prime contractor on the largest U.S.-Chinese
military project.
   The company was formally told by the Pentagon on Wednesday that
under Bush's order no Chinese nationals were to be allowed into the
plant.
   ``The Chinese were very upset,'' said Harwood. ``They had a
feeling they had been let down.''
   The Chinese, many of whom had been working at Grumman since 1987,
had built up strong relationships with their American counterparts,
according to Grumman employees.
   They had been to parties and barbecues at the homes of many of
the Grumman workers.
   Now they feel cut off because they have had no contact with
officials in China, the workers said.
   All of the Chinese are here without family and are renting
apartments or houses on Long Island.
   ``We have told them if they need anything of a personal nature
that they should call us,'' said Harwood.
   Grumman officials do not know if the project will be eventually
canceled.
   Grumman was awarded a $500 million U.S. Air Force contract to
develop and modernize a weapons control system for 55 existing F-8
Chinese fighters. The Chinese had contracted with the U.S. Air force.
   Grumman had 250 employees working on the program. Those employees
will be shifted to other projects or layed-off, said Harwood.
   Grumman, Long Island's largest employer, employs some 19,000
people on the island.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
