<FILEID>AP-NR-06-08-89 2126EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>s f BC-SEC-Glance Adv11   06-08 0274</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-SEC-Glance, Adv 11,0286</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv11</HEAD>
<HEAD>Advance for release Sunday, June 11</HEAD>
<HEAD>With BC-SEC Future</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Here are some facts and figures about the
Securities and Exchange Commission:
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   HISTORY: The SEC was created in 1934 as part of the Securities
Exchange Act in a wave of financial regulation under President
Franklin D. Roosevelt reacting to the stock market crash of 1929 and
subsequent Depression.
   DUTIES: The Washington-based commission is charged with
regulating the nation's financial markets and market professionals,
including all stock exchanges, brokers and investment firms. It
regulates financial disclosures by companies and enforces federal
securities laws.
   The SEC is run by a panel of five commissioners, including a
chairman.
   It has a total staff of about 2,130, including 800 attorneys, in
13 cities: Atlanta; Boston; Chicago; Denver; Fort Worth, Texas;
Houston; Los Angeles; Miami; New York; Philadelphia; Salt Lake City;
San Francisco; Seattle; and Washington.
   The commission has the power to penalize securities-law violators
with fines, suspensions and oversight. It can refer cases to the
Justice Department for criminal prosecution.
   In 1988, the SEC brought 252 enforcement actions, including
insider trading, corporate reporting, market manipulation, fraud and
other cases. It also reviewed 10,985 disclosure filings, 4,000 more
than in 1983.
   FINANCING: The SEC had a budget of $142.6 million, up from $73
million in 1980. It has requested $168.7 million for fiscal 1990.
   In 1987, the commission raised about $264 million from stock
registration fees and $121 million from court orders to defendants
to return illicit profits. Under federal securities laws, though,
the agency cannot use any of the money it raises.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End advance for Sunday, June 11</NOTE>
