<FIRST>u f AM-Northwest     06-08 0461</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Northwest,0479</SECOND>
<HEAD>MEI One Of Spurned Bidders For Northwest Airlines</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MINNEAPOLIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A company owned by Minneapolis investor Irwin
Jacobs and Minnesota Twins owner Carl Pohlad Thursday confirmed it
was one of the spurned bidders for NWA Inc., the parent company of
Northwest Airlines.
   A special NWA board committee rejected the bid by a group of
investors that includes MEI Diversified Inc., MEI President Donald
E. Benson said in a news release.
   Benson could not be reached by telephone for further comment late
Thursday.
   MEI, a Minneapolis-based snack foods company, submitted a bid of
about $3.3 billion, or about $110 a share, The Wall Street Journal
reported Thursday, quoting unidentified sources.
   A special NWA board committee rejected all bids earlier this week
after finding none acceptable. Board members have declined comment
on the bids and have not released information to Northwest
management, said Bob Gibbons, a spokesman for the airline.
   The other known bidders for NWA are oil billionaire Marvin Davis,
New York-based Pan Am Corp., Northwest's 20,000-member machinists'
union and an investment group led by former hotel executive Alfred
Checchi.
   The committee asked for new bids by 4 p.m. EST June 16, and said
bids should be held open until June 30 to give the committee time to
evaluate the revised proposals, Gibbons said.
   Benson was quoted by the Journal as saying an investment in an
airline was an option, as MEI seeks to diversify.
   ``We're looking for areas outside the snack food business and
we're sitting on a great deal of cash,'' he said.
   As of Dec. 31, MEI showed $123 million in cash and marketable
securities on its balance sheet, most of which came from a 1987
equity and debt offering, the Journal said.
   MEI reported revenue, primarily from sales of nuts, candies and
other snack foods, of $219.9 million last year and earnings of $6.7
million, or 35 cents a share, the newspaper said.
   Pohlad, a Minneapolis banker, is a member of Texas Air Corp.'s
board and has been involved in Eastern Airlines' efforts to
reorganize.
   Jacobs, who owns Minstar Inc., recently joined Amway Corp. to bid
for Avon Products Inc.
   Forbes magazine lists Pohlad's personal net worth at $670 million
and Jacobs' as $240 million.
   Pohlad and Jacobs did not return phone calls Thursday.
   In another development Thursday, Marvin Davis announced that his
$2.67 billion, or $90 per share, tender offer for NWA Inc. was
extended to 6 p.m. EDT, June 14. The offer previously was scheduled
to expire at 6 p.m. EDT June 7. Davis originally made his offer in
March and has extended the deadline several times.
   NWA stock rose 87{ cents a share to $108.12{ Thursday following a
gain of $1 a share the previous day amid the new takeover reports.
</TEXT>
