<FILEID>AP-NR-06-08-89 1832EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-CommodityRdp     06-08 0734</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Commodity Rdp,0766</SECOND>
<HEAD>Grain Prices Continue to Tumble</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HERBERT G. McCANN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Grain and soybean futures prices declined Thursday
on the Chicago Board of Trade due to continued pressure from
favorable weather forecasts and slack demand.
   On other markets, copper prices were up while precious metals
were down; energy prices rallied; livestock and meat futures were
down, and sugar and cotton prices rose.
   Wheat futures, which have been declining because of the political
turmoil in China, were off for the third consecutive trading
session. Analysts say the problems in China may mean that country
won't place new orders for U.S. wheat.
   ``There was some concern over China and additional wheat sales,
but the market lacked any real direction,'' Frank Kouba, an analyst
with Shearson Lehman Hutton Inc. in Chicago, said Thursday.
   Soybean futures were mixed, getting a boost from a threatened
sales boycott by Brazilian farmers who say they are worried about
their government's exchange rate policy.
   In addition, dockworkers in Brazil are threatening another
nationwide port strike, which would hamper Brazilian soybean exports.
   Corn prices were pressured by light demand and reports of
improved growing conditions in major crop areas.
   Wheat settled \ cent to 1{ cents lower with the contract for
delivery in July at $3.81} a bushel; corn was 3 cents to 5 cents
lower with July at $2.53\ a bushel; oats were 1{ cents to 2{ cents
higher with July at $1.65 a bushel; soybeans were 5} cents lower to
3 cents higher with July at $7.14 a bushel.
   Copper futures moved higher on New York's Commodity Exchange on
speculation about supply disruptions.
   The start of contract talks next week between U.S. producers and
their unions, with the possibility of strikes, and the continued
closure of Bougainville Copper Ltd.'s Papua, New Guinea mine boosted
prices, said Bette Raptopoulos, an analyst with Prudential-Bache
Securities Inc. in New York.
   Copper settled 1.10 cents to 2.50 cents higher with June at $1.35
a pound.
   Precious metals prices declined as the dollar showed renewed
strength.
   Gold settled $2.60 to $3.10 lower with June at $373.50 a troy
ounce; silver was 2.1 cents to 2.7 cents lower with June at $5.443 a
troy ounce.
   Energy futures mostly were higher on the New York Mercantile
Exchange in reaction to promises by Kuwait to cut back oil
production.
   Kuwaiti Oil Minister Ali Khalifa al-Sabah said his country
intended to produce 1.35 million barrels a day in coming months.
   On Wednesday the Organization of Petroleum Exporting Countries
signed a new production accord that placed Kuwait's new quota at
1.093 million barrels. Its current output is estimated at nearly 2
million barrels a day.
   West Texas Intermediate crude oil was 12 cents to 33 cents higher
with July at $20 a barrel; heating oil was .19 cent lower to .17
cent higher with July at 48.66 cents a gallon; unleaded gasoline was
.57 cent to .66 cent higher with July at 64 cents a gallon.
   Livestock and meat futures were mixed in lackluster trading on
the Chicago Mercantile Exchange.
   Live cattle settled .30 cent lower to .50 cent higher with June
at 69.32 cents a pound; feeder cattle were .05 cent to .15 cent
higher with August at 79.02 cents a pound; hogs were .25 cent lower
to .15 cent higher with June at 48.30 cents a pound; frozen pork
bellies were .10 cent lower to .52 cent higher with July at 32.25
cents a pound.
   Sugar futures were up strongly on New York's Coffee, Sugar &amp;
Cocoa Exchange.
   The political tension in China, which spurred selling earlier in
the week, was set aside as rumors spread that India might enter the
market, said Kim Badenhop, an analyst with Merrill Lynch Capital
Markets Inc. in New York.
   China had been expected to enter the market for 300,000 metric
tons of sugar. Rumors are that India will buy 500,000 metric tons,
Badenhop said.
   Sugar settled .22 cent to .39 cent higher with July at 11.72
cents a pound.
   Cotton futures continued their run up on the New York Cotton
Exchange as new buyers entered the market, said Ed Whitten, an
analyst with Balfour Maclaine Corp. in New York.
   ``What spurred the buying was the overselling in reaction to the
situation in China,'' Whitten said. ``Equilibrium has been
recovered.''
   Cotton settled .37 cent to 1.02 cents higher with July at 64.18
cents a pound.
</TEXT>
