<FIRST>u f AM-PrimeComputer     06-08 0462</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Prime Computer,0481</SECOND>
<HEAD>Prime, MAI At Odds Over Meeting</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A hostile suitor for Prime Computer Inc. said
Thursday the computer maker showed no interest in a merger during a
meeting, but Prime termed the charge ``a gross misrepresentation.''
   Bennett S. LeBow, chairman of MAI Basic Four Inc., accused Prime
of refusing to provide confidential information it has given other
prospective bidders during a meeting over their prolonged and
contentious takeover battle.
   He said in a statement that Prime's representatives ``evidenced
no interest in negotiating a business combination of Prime and MAI
at this time on the terms of MAI's current tender offer.''
   Prime responded by saying it was ``shocked at the gross
misrepresentation'' of the meeting by LeBow.
   Tustin, Calif.-based MAI last November launched a hostile
takeover bid for the Natick-based minicomputer maker. Its latest
offer is worth about $1.05 billion.
   Prime confirmed that its chairman, David Dunn, and two board
members met with LeBow and his partner, William Weksel, on Wednesday.
   ``We went into the meeting in good faith, without lawyers or
other advisers attending, totally willing to enter into meaningful
discussions, as we are with any qualified buyer,'' said Anthony L.
Craig, Prime's chief executive.
   ``To have MAI represent us as `showing no interest in
negotiating' is simply a gross misstatement,'' he said.
   Craig also said Prime's representatives gave LeBow the same
projections of earnings, income and costs that have been supplied to
other potential bidders.
   Last week, MAI cut its tender offer for Prime's stock from $20
cash per share to a mixture of cash and securities valued by most
Wall Street analysts at $17 to $19 a share, said Barry Willman, an
analyst with the investment firm of Sanford Bernstein &amp; Co. in New
York.
   The original, all-cash offer amounted to about $970 million for
Prime's outstanding shares, or $1.25 billion for all of its stock,
including shares that can be converted from bonds.
   The new offer is worth about $1.05 billion for all of the stock,
said Jay Stevens, an analyst with Dean Witter Reynolds Inc. in New
York.
   Prime has said that if it does not receive a better offer before
its annual meeting, it will enter into negotiations with LeBow to
explore a merger.
   MAI has filed a lawsuit in Delaware Chancery Court to try to
compel Prime to hold the annual meeting June 14, as previously
scheduled. Prime announced this week it was rescheduling the meeting
to July 26. A hearing on the suit is set for next week.
   Wednesday's meeting took place at LeBow's request.
   A Prime spokeswoman said it was the first meeting between LeBow
and top Prime executives since last fall, when LeBow met with former
Prime chief executive Joe Henson shortly before launching the
hostile bid.
</TEXT>
