<FILEID>AP-NR-06-08-89 2210EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f BC-GtechOffers     06-08 0273</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Gtech Offers,0285</SECOND>
<HEAD>Gtech Committee To Review Offers</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KAREN SCHWARTZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PROVIDENCE, R.I. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Gtech Corp., a major supplier of lottery
networks long rumored as a takeover target, said Thursday a special
managment committee would evaluate merger and takeover offers.
   Gtech acknowledged that ``certain parties have expressed interest
in possibly acquiring'' the company, but said no offers had been
received.
   The company said its directors were working with financial
advisers Bear, Stearns &amp; Co. and Alex, Brown &amp; Sons Inc.
   ``Companies apparently, from time to time, visit Gtech and raise
the issue of possible business combinations,'' Cato Carpenter, an
analyst with Alex, Brown, said from his Baltimore office.
   Carpenter added that the company was not currently in
negotiations, but that it wanted a committee to monitor these
inquiries.
   Rumors of a possible takeover first surfaced last fall, with
Bally Manufaturing Corp. of Chicago most often identified as a
possible suitor.
   Guy B. Snowden, Gtech's president, was not in the office
Thursday, his secretary said, and could not be reached for comment.
   Carpenter said Gtech was capable of adequately financing its
growth, and ``it isn't outright apparent why they would need to be
acquired.''
   Lower earnings last fall forced Gtech to lay off 10 percent of
its 1,300 workers.
   Gtech's stock, traded nationally over the counter, closed
Thursday at $14 a share, up $1.25. There were 253,000 shares traded,
three times the normal activity, Carpenter said.
   The company designs, produces and installs computerized lottery
networks, with 32 customers on five continents, including many of
this country's state lotteries. Much of its income comes from
maintaining and operating the systems.
</TEXT>
