<FILEID>AP-NR-06-08-89 2110EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-Eastern 1stLd-Writethru f0272 06-08 0464</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Eastern, 1st Ld-Writethru, f0272,0474</SECOND>
<HEAD>Eastern Makes Contract Offer to Striking Pilots</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 9 grafs to UPDATE with union reax, company response.
Picks up 6th graf pvs, `A federal ...'.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAN SEWELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Eastern Airlines presented a contract proposal
Thursday to the striking pilots union that seeks temporary pay and
vacation reductions similar to those implemented for non-union
workers last week.
   The proposal was made at the second official negotiating session
since Eastern was hit by a crippling strike March 4. The concessions
are necessary to help the airline emerge from bankruptcy, the
company said at a news conference.
   The Air Line Pilots Association responded by describing the news
conference as a ``public relations hoax'' and said the contract
proposal ``does not address the primary issues'' that led to the
strike.
   Eastern officials said part of the latest proposal is identical
to an offer first made last July. New elements include the company's
request that pilots take a 10 percent pay cut for six months and a 5
percent cut during the second six months. After a year, pay would be
fully restored.
   Eastern also proposed suspending contributions to a pension fund
through 1990 and canceling vacations for the rest of this year.
   As part of its plan to emerge from bankruptcy, Eastern last week
announced an austerity program that includes a 20 percent pay cut
for senior management and increased work hours at the same pay for
non-union employees. Vacations for those workers have been canceled
for the remainder of the year.
   ALPA spokesman Ron Cole said the union was angry that Eastern
announced the proposal at a news conference before it was presented
to ALPA negotiators.
   ``Obviously the cameras are more important than the contract,''
Cole said. ``It's nothing more than a public relations hoax
presented to establish a paper trail to the doors of the bankruptcy
court, where we expect Eastern will file for abrogation of our
contract.''
   Eastern spokesman Robin Matell said abrogation of the contract
``is simply an option, one that we would not even address at this
time. ... Our primary thrust is to successfully negotiate a pilots'
contract.''
   A federal appeals court on Wednesday rejected Eastern's request
to have the pilots ordered back to work. The pilots union says it
has been honoring the picket lines of the Machinists union, while
the company argued the pilots were striking to advance their own
contract negotiations without going through federal mediation
procedures as the Machinists did.
   The pilots' last contract expired in July 1988. Negotiations on a
new agreement have been held off and on since August 1987.
   Eastern filed for bankruptcy under Chapter 11 five days after it
was crippled by the strike by Machinists, pilots and flight
attendants.
 
</TEXT>
