<FILEID>AP-NR-06-08-89 2112EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-Japan-Markets     06-08 0208</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Japan-Markets,0218</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Opens Higher, Share Prices Advance In Early Trading</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. dollar opened higher against the Japanese
yen Friday morning, while share prices on the Tokyo Stock Exchange
rose moderately shortly after trading began.
   The dollar began trading at 143.25 yen, up 0.20 yen from
Thursday's 143.05-yen finish.
   Traders said the dollar opened higher after its similar uptrend
overnight in New York, where the currency ended at 143.05 yen.
   A trader with the Bank of Tokyo said Japanese investors'
dollar-buying incentives continued to be strong, with most trying to
push the dollar up even higher.
   ``Turmoil in China is no longer a strong dollar-buying incentive
here, and the majority of market players, who have kept buying the
dollar, are now sort of testing how much farther they can go,'' he
said.
   On the stock exchange, the Nikkei Stock Average of 225 selected
issues, a 91.40-point gainer the previous day, added another 84.56
points, or 0.25 percent, rising to 33,802.56 within the first 15
minutes of trading.
   Stock brokers attributed the Nikkei's early gains to overnight
gains in foreign markets. In New York, the 30-issue Dow Jones
industrial average added 4.59 points.
   Participants targeted their buy orders at electricals and
automobiles, they said.
</TEXT>
