<FILEID>AP-NR-06-08-89 2234EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f BC-Ethanol-CleanAir     06-08 0404</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Ethanol-Clean Air,0415</SECOND>
<HEAD>Lawmaker Says Bush Clean Air Plan Promising For Corn Growers</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STEVEN P. ROSENFELD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DES MOINES, Iowa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush's plans to reduce auto
emissions are expected to increase demand for corn-based ethanol and
expand markets for other corn products, a congressman says.
   U.S. Rep. Tom Tauke, R-Iowa, said Thursday he expects Bush will
place greater emphasis on alternative motor fuels, such as ethanol,
as part of a clean air program the president is scheduled to
announce Monday.
   The Iowa Corn Promotion Board has estimated that with just normal
growth in gasohol use, the United States would need 390 million
bushels of corn to meet ethanol demand in 1989. About three-quarters
of the nation's ethanol is produced in Iowa and Illinois.
   Tauke said he expects the president's proposal to increase the
demand for gasohol _ a blend of 10 percent ethanol and gasoline _
and to encourage higher concentrations of ethanol _ up to the use of
pure ethanol _ as a fuel for cars, buses and trucks.
   ``If there is a commitment at the national level to have a
substantial portion of the automotive fleet in the country, or buses
or trucks, being operated by alternative fuels, then there's going
to be a major expansion in the use of ethanol,'' Tauke said.
   Bush is a long-time proponent of increasing the use of ethanol to
clean auto emissions and reduce carbon monoxide and other pollutants
in the air. He promised Thursday that he will unveil ``the most
sweeping changes to the Clean Air Act since it was last amended 12
years ago.''
   The clean air program also will focus on factory emissions and
acid rain. On Tuesday, Bush is scheduled to deliver a speech on
alternative fuels at Lincoln, Neb.
   Tauke said he based his assessment on the program's content on
discussions he had Wednesday with Bush's chief of staff, John
Sununu, and other White House officials.
   ``Our expectation is that the announcement will include
substantial incentives for the use of alternative fuels, in some
case the requirement for the use of alternative fuels,'' Tauke said.
   Use of ethanol as a motor fuel is touted for reducing the release
into the air of carbon monoxide, nitrogen oxide and smog. Tauke said
ethanol also is safer and easier to transport than another
alternative fuel, coal-based methanol, because it is not toxic and
burns with a visible flame.
</TEXT>
