<FIRST>r f BC-AmericanMedical     06-08 0221</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-American Medical,0229</SECOND>
<HEAD>Second Bidder Emerges For Hospital Chain</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEVERLY HILLS, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A second bidder emerged Thursday for
American Medical International Inc., a New Jersey consultant who
proposed creating an employee stock ownership plan to buy the big
hospital company.
   The offer from Brian M. Freeman Enterprises Inc. of Roseland,
N.J., was revealed by American Medical. Freeman, a business
consultant who has arranged other ESOPs, refused to comment on his
offer.
   Freeman's proposal values the company at $2 billion or $27 a
share, $23 of that in cash and $4 in new preferred stock. The
company's description of the bid said it was conditional on
obtaining financing. Details of the proposed ESOP weren't provided.
   American Medical, which owns 75 hospitals, already is weighing a
bid of $21 a share cash and $3 a share in securities by minority
shareholder M. Lee Pearce, a Miami physician and investor.
   A special committee of the board of directors that is weighing
the bids, along with a management-proposed restructuring designed to
boost shareholder value, on Thursday set a June 29 deadline for
submitting buyout offers.
   ``Several other expressions of strong interest'' in buying the
company have emerged, but there haven't been formal offers, said
spokesman Mick Taylor.
   American Medical has about 76 million shares outstanding,
including warrants and options to buy stock.
</TEXT>
