<FILEID>AP-NR-06-08-89 2237EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f BC-GibraltarLawsuit     06-08 0322</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Gibraltar Lawsuit,0334</SECOND>
<HEAD>Parent of Seized S&amp;L Sues Federal Regulators</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The parent company of Gibraltar Savings on
Thursday sued the federal regulators who now control the thrift,
demanding the release of $11 million the parent says it is owed.
   Gibraltar Financial Corp.'s lawsuit, filed in U.S. District
Court, is the latest development in a dispute with federal agencies
over whether the holding company will be able to stay afloat now
that the thrift is under regulators' control.
   Gibraltar Savings, the nation's ninth-largest thrift, with
operations in California, Washington state and Florida, was seized
March 31 by the Federal Home Loan Bank Board, which declared the
institution unsound.
   Gibraltar Financial, a holding company whose stock is publicly
traded and which hasn't any significant assets other than two
Gibraltar Savings units in California and Washington state, wasn't
included in the seizure of its thrifts.
   The suit names as defendants the Federal Home Loan Bank Board,
the Federal Savings and Loan Insurance Corp., the Federal Deposit
Insurance Corp. and Gibraltar's own seized subsidiaries.
   Bank Board spokesman Karl Hoyle responded that regulators had
ample reason to take over Gibraltar, and are required by law to
preserve the assets of the savings &amp; loan without regard to the fate
of the holding company.
   ``Our responsibility is to the insured deposits and to the
depositors and to the FSLIC,'' Hoyle said from Washington, D.C.
``Unfortunately, that means, in the case of a stock institution, the
stockholders, the debtholders, they're cut out.''
   The holding company missed a $1 million interest payment to
bondholders June 1, blaming regulators' withholding of the $11
million.
   Gibraltar Savings of California has 83 branches and the sister
thrift in Bellevue, Wash., has six branches in Washington and 18 in
Florida. Together, they had $8.8 billion in deposits when seized.
   Gibraltar Financial lost $100.5 million in 1988 and $146.5
million in 1987. In 1986, it had a $43.9 million profit.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
